Subject: Electronic Mail4

Date: June 5, 1996
To: Tibet Supporters
From: Larry Gerstein
         Co-Director, International Tibet Independence Movement
Re: E-Mail Boycott Petition

As you know, during the month of June, we are supporting a "Boycott Chinese
Goods" program.  Students for a Free Tibet & many other organizations are
involved in this program as well. Very recently, I received a request from
the Milarepa Foundation to support an electronic petition drive. We have
agreed to this request. What follows is a statement & petition to accomplish
this. Please sign on to this petition by entering your name & returning your
endorsement to me. Simply e-mail me with your decision. Also, pass this
document on to others who will support the boycott & ask them to e-mail you
back with their support. When you have accumulated 50 names and/or by June
30, return your list of names to me.

Also contact President Clinton, Congress, and the Senate to voice your own
opinions.  A list of their e-mail addresses are below.

Thanks for your assistance.

CURRENT SUPPORTERS
1. John Dinusson
2. Erin Potts
3. Jon Voss
4. Josh Shrei
5. Larry Gerstein

BACKGROUND
In recognition of the brutal Chinese occupation of Tibet, and the continued
human rights violations in Tibet and China, an international consumer
boycott of all Chinese goods has been called for the entire month of June,
1996.

Since Tibet was invaded by China in 1950, the land and people of Tibet have
been systematically destroyed. Over 20% of the population (1.2 million
people) have been murdered, over 6000 monasteries have been destroyed, and
many hundreds of thousands of Tibetans remain in Chinese prisons simply for
exercising their religious, cultural and/or political beliefs. Similar
conditions exist in China as well. Amnesty International, Asia Watch, Laogai
Foundation and other Human Rights groups have reported  gross human rights
violations including forced prison labor.

Chinese prison labor camps produce a number of goods that we use in our
homes everyday. Though this is widely acknowledged and highly illegal, no
economic sanctions are levied against China. In fact, the United States
continues to renew China's Most Favored Nation trading status on a yearly
basis. While this directly  helps large corporations, it does nothing to
move China towards improving its human rights policies.  Consumers around the
world will demonstrate that they will not tolerate either a destruction of a
people or massive  human rights violations.  The one month boycott of Chinese
goods will send  a clear message to the world community, the business
community, and the present government of China.

This boycott is particularly timely since President Clinton just signed MFN &
congress now has 60 days to decide whether it supports this decision. It is
very critical that we contact the President & congress to share our views.
Congress appears to be leaning toward not supporting MFN & our input will
provide them with further evidence to make this decision.

