<a name=L10000></a><a href=#L10001>So</a>: U-vre
From: outreach@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: pn.announcements
Subject: CONFERENCE ANNOUNCEMENT
Date: 12 Jun 1996 09:50:54 -0800 (PST)

From: IGC Outreach Desk  outreach@igc.apc.org 

Date: Thu, 6 Jun 1996 12:48:58 GMT-500
From: Ginger Mann  mann@faculty.law.duke.edu 
Subject: CONFERENCE ANNOUNCEMENT


                     CONFERENCE ANNOUNCEMENT

                      JUSTICE IN CATACLYSM:
                        CRIMINAL TRIBUNALS
                              IN THE
                      WAKE OF MASS VIOLENCE

                   An International Conference,
                           sponsored by
                  DUKE UNIVERSITY SCHOOL OF LAW
                     in conjunction with the
                    OFFICE OF THE PROSECUTOR,
                      INTERNATIONAL TRIBUNAL
               FOR THE FORMER YUGOSLAVIA AND RWANDA


                        July 20 - 21, 1996
                        Brussels, Belgium

The Conference, "Justice in Cataclysm: Criminal Tribunals in the
Wake of Mass Violence," sponsored by Duke University School of Law in
conjunction with the Office of the Prosecutor of the International
Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia and Rwanda, will bring
together leading thinkers to identify the most appropriate and
efficacious roles for national and international criminal justice
systems in responding to mass crimes in contexts of violent conflict.
 Such crimes include genocide, war crimes, and crimes against
humanity.

The timing of this Conference promises to maximize its benefits and
impact.  The International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia is presently conducting its first trial. Prosecutions by
the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda will commence
shortly. National-level criminal justice processes are currently
being prepared in Rwanda.  Trials of members of Ethiopia's Mengistu
regime for genocide and crimes against humanity are scheduled to
begin on April 4 of this year.

By July of 1996, prosecutions by these new national and
international criminal tribunals will have been underway for several
months, while the bulk of their work will still lie ahead.  The
summer of 1996 will therefore be the optimal time to convene.
Equipped with the insights already gained in several months of
experience, we will evaluate the successes achieved and the problems
encountered in these efforts, and will seek to develop valuable
approaches for the future course of these momentous judicial
proceedings.



                        CONFERENCE AGENDA

SATURDAY, JULY 20, 1996

PANEL I

NATIONAL PROSECUTIONS IN COLLAPSED JUSTICE SYSTEMS: NATIONAL
APPROACHES AND INTERNATIONAL ASSISTANCE

Girma Wakjira, Chief Special Prosecutor, Republic of Ethiopia
Jaime Malamud-Goti, Professor of Law, University of Arkansas
Madeline Morris, Professor of Law, Duke University

PANEL II

NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL TRIBUNALS: THE IMPLICATIONS OF
CONCURRENT JURISDICTION

Frederik Harhoff, Legal Expert on Mission, International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda
M. Cherif Bassiouni, Professor of Law, DePaul University
William Schabas, Dean, Department of Law, University of Quebec at
Montreal

PANEL III

ISSUES CONFRONTING THE INTERNTIONAL CRIMINAL TRIBUNAL FOR THE
FORMER YUGOSLAVIA AND RWANDA

William Fenrick, Senior Legal Advisor, International Criminal
Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia and Rwanda
Fran=87ois Hampson, Dean and Professor of Law, Essex University
Christopher Greenwood, Professor of International Law, London School
of Economics

DINNER SPEAKER: Justice Richard Goldstone, Prosecutor, International
Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia and Rwanda


SUNDAY, JULY 21, 1996

PANEL IV

PROSECUTIONS AND THE RECONCILIATION PROCESS

Ruth Wedgwood, Professor of Law, Yale University
Payam Akhavan, Legal Advisor, International Criminal Tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia and  Rwanda
Ephraim Zuroff, Director, Simon Wiesenthal Center, Israel

PANEL V

ALTERNATIVES AND ADJUNCTS TO CRIMINAL PROSECUTIONS

Alexander Boraine, Vice Chair, South African Truth and Reconciliation
Commission
Jose Zalaquett, Professor of Law, University of Chile
Michael Scharf, Assistant Professor of Law, New England School of Law


                           REGISTRATION

The Conference will be held at the five-star Conrad Hotel, 71 Avenue
Louise, Brussels, Belgium.


                         Conference Costs
                     (Check desired category)

_____  500 USD per person (single occupancy)*
_____  400 USD per person (double occupancy)*
_____  300 USD per person (includes all meals and conference
amenities, but no hotel accommodations)

* Includes  hotel accommodations on Friday, July 19 and Saturday,
July 20, breakfast, lunch and dinner on Saturday and breakfast on
Sunday, and all conference amenities.

Please note that late registrations will be tentatively accepted on
a space available basis through June 30.

