<pre>
So: U-ind
From: susanodo@web.apc.org
Newsgroups: indig.canada
Subject: CANADA-HUMAN RIGHTS: Extremist Grou
Date: 19 Jun 1996 05:53:56 -0500 (EST)

/* Written  4:06 PM  Jun 15, 1996 by igc:newsdesk in web:ips.english */
/* ---------- "CANADA-HUMAN RIGHTS: Extremist Grou" ---------- */
       Copyright 1996 InterPress Service, all rights reserved.
          Worldwide distribution via the APC networks.

                      *** 12-Jun-96 ***

Title: CANADA-HUMAN RIGHTS: Extremist Groups a ''Growing Phenomenon'' in
Canada

by Barbara Borst

TORONTO, Jun 12 (IPS) - In a recent report to Parliament, the
Canadian Security Intelligence Service (CSIS) said there are very
few people here who seek to ''move the political agenda through
violence.''

Public and private groups that monitor hate groups disagree.

Rosemary Brown of the Security Intelligence Review Committee,
an independent, government-appointed body, warns that it would be
''a very serious mistake for either CSIS, SIRC (Security
Intelligence Review Committee), or, indeed, th}s nation to think
that right-wing activity in this country is on the decline or that
it is not a threat.''

Karen Mock, national director of the League for Human Rights of
B'nai Brith Canada, says her group's research on extremism across
Europe and North America shows that it is ''a growing phenomenon''
here and elsewhere.

One of the rallying points for hate groups in Canada is
opposition to immigration. The face of the nation is changing
dramatically as an increasing number of Asian, Caribbean and
African people migrate here.

The groups also oppose legal protections for homosexuals and
rights for native peoples.

Linking these causes with the hatred of Jews and blacks
expounded by the Ku Klux Klan and neo-Nazis, extremists have
inspired acts of hatred that have shocked Canadians, who pride
themselves on a less violent political and more tolerant social
climate than that of their neighbor, the United States.

The extent of the problem became obvious in 1993, when an
investigation into the killing of a Somali youth by Canadian
soldiers while on a humanitarian mission to Somalia revealed
members of the elite Airborne Regiment belonged to extreme-right
organizations.

In response, the military disbanded the regiment and set a
policy of ''zero tolerance'' for racist conduct, including
membership in extremist organizations. (Human rights organizations
argue that a fuller investigation is still urgently needed.)

Concern about the growth of hate crimes is fueling
investigations by all levels of government.

The Metropolitan Toronto Council has commissioned a study, due
in July, by the League for Human Rights on the nature and extent
of hate activity in the Toronto area.

Charles Smith of the council's Anti-Racism, Access and Equity
Committee says Toronto police statistics show an increase in hate
crime, particularly against racial minorities and native
Canadians.

Although anti-Semitic acts have been tracked for years, there
is insufficient data concerning racial minorities, indigenous
peoples, immigrants, gays and lesbians, he said.

In 1995 there were 290 reported anti-Semitic incidents,
according to the league, ''the highest number reported in 14 years
of documentation.''

The World Anti-Fascism League in Montreal filed a report with
the U.N. Human Rights Commission in February citing ''racism,
xenophobia and intolerance,'' especially stemming from Quebec's
push toward independence from Canada.

WAL's Peter Vorias says extremist groups include the National
Movement for the Liberation of Quebec and Roman Catholic right-
wing groups such as Cercle Jeune Nation and Centre d'Information
Nationale Robert Rumilly.

The CSIS reported that in Quebec ''extremists on both sides
have issued isolated threats, including death threats against
political leaders.''

Warren Kinsella, in his 1995 book 'Web of Hate', chronicles the
activities of the extreme right in the western prairies and major
cities, exposing their international connections.

''Across Canada, in every region, in almost every town and
city, the web of hate continues to spread,'' writes Kinsella, a
journalist, lawyer and former special assistant to Jean Chretien,
now prime minister.

Extremists have been charged with brutalizing gays and members
of minority groups, assaulting anti-racists, defacing synagogues,
burning crosses and disseminating hate propaganda.

Many of the names play on democratic ideals -- the Canadian
Free Speech League, Citizens for Foreign Aid Reform. Others,
however, boldly announce their agenda with names such as Aryan
Nations, White Aryan Resistance (WAR) and the Hammerskins.

CSIS says the extreme right is composed of a variety of groups
drawn to the same issues but ''without a central leadership, a
phenomenon they find to be a source of strength.''

''Prominent members...establish the broad direction of the
movement, and decisions on what actions to take rest with
individuals or small cells,'' according to the CSIS.

However, the League for Human Rights says extremists are ''not
a loose amalgamation of like-minded malevolents,'' but rather ''an
organized network of groups and individuals'' promoting hatred of
nearly all the ethnic groups that form multicultural Canada.

Extremists, Mock warns, use media interviews and computer
networks to spread their message, often targeting alienated youth
in schools across the country.

Some extremist groups, however, have found that publicity is
also their foe.

Exposure in the news media, and in court, has reduced the
Toronto-based Heritage Front's prominence and finances. Image-
conscious officials from the conservative Reform Party expelled
members who belonged to the Heritage Front.

Canadian law, which makes it a crime to preach hatred of
identifiable groups, has been used to shut down the Heritage Front
Hotline and other phone-in operations.

The conviction of Alberta high school teacher James Keegstra
for promoting anti-Semitism was recently upheld by the Supreme
Court, which has also backed the provincial New Brunswick Human
Rights Commission order that barred an elementary school teacher
who authored books denying the Holocaust and accusing Jews of
international conspiracy from the classroom.

There also has been a backlash -- sometimes violent -- against
the extreme right.

Kinsella writes of Anti-Racist Action and Skinheads Against
Racial Prejudice, both of which have clashed violently with the
far right.

Additionally, the CSIS says Militant Direct Action Task Force,
a previously unknown group, mailed two pipe bombs last year to
white supremacists.(end/ips/bb/pz/96)


Origin: Washington/CANADA-HUMAN RIGHTS/
