Subject: Onkwehonwe Languages Conference
Date: 20 Jun 1996 05:34:39

______________________________ Forward Header __________________________________
Subject: Onkwehonwe Languages Conference
Author:  bf145@freenet.carleton.ca
Date:    19/06/96 23:40


MEDIA ADVISORY -- June 17, 1996

ONKWEHONWE LANGUAGES AND WORLDVIEW -- A CONFERENCE

HOSTED BY THE STUDENTS OF KAWENNI':IO/GAWENI:YO HIGH SCHOOL

WHERE: Kawenni':io/Gaweni:yo High School, corner of Seneca and Sour
Springs Roads, Six Nations of the Grand River Territory.

WHEN: Friday June 21 to Sunday June 23 (see attached agenda, which
includes directions to the school).

WHY: To bring together parents and educators, from other Hodinohsoni
communities and nations, so they may assess and evaluate the curriculum of
the Kawenni':io/Gaweni:yo High School. Organizers will share the hands-on
experience they've gained in their ten years of involvement in the
planning and implementation of curriculum geared specifically to the
Onkwehon:we. It is also hoped the conference will encourage our youth and
fluent speakers to pursue careers in teaching.

MEDIA CONTACT: Allen Gabriel at (613) 234-7283, Fax: (613) 235-4040.

Of Special Interest:

- The concept for the school was developed, and is driven, by the parents
of the students. Working closely with leaders of the Hodinohsoni (People
of the Longhouse or Iroquois), they have developed a unique and exciting
curriculum which brings to life the distinct culture the Hodinohsoni.

- The school has provided an opportunity for young people to build
self-esteem by restoring, in them, a strong sense of identity.

- The program provides the necessary skills to ensure the continued growth
of our culture and society. Our youth are able to express their modern
perspectives within the context of the languages and worldview of our
living, thriving culture.

- In its June 1996 report, The Standing Committee on Aboriginal Affairs
and Northern Development encouraged the government to support communities
which provide students with "a complete education that places emphasis on
culture and language and provides students with a solid foundation in
subjects required for post-secondary education and employment." This
program does that, and can be a model for other communities.

Highlights include:

- Participants include parents who could not speak their languages prior
to this program being implemented, and who are now teaching the languages
in the school.

- There will be presentations on the history of the school, and on the
curriculum and its outcomes. Faithkeepers and Elders panels demonstrate
the integration of the community as a whole into the curriculum.

- There will be displays on computer applications to Onkwehonwe languages,
and on curricula from visiting communities.

AGENDA

ONKWEHONWE LANGUAGES AND WORLD VIEW A CONFERENCE -- JUNE 21, 22 23, 1996

KAWENNI':IO/GAWENI:YO HIGH SCHOOL, SIX NATIONS (CORNER OF SENECA & SOUR
SPRINGS ROADS)

