            *** FAN International Update - June 17, 1996 ***




    Hi friends!  Thanks for your continued interest and support for FAN and
our Great Coast Rainforest Campaign.  We've now moved into our spacious new
office in Bella Coola and we're happy and excited to have a permanent home
again!  We have boats in harbour and are ready to blockade at any time...


TRRP (TEMPERATE RAINFOREST RESEARCH PROJECT)

    We've also finished setting up the TRRP camp in the beautiful
Skowquiltz valley (pronounced "so-wilk"), and FAN researchers have begun a
scientific survey of three rare, old-growth dependent species - the marbled
murrelet, the tailed frog, and the Queen Charlotte goshawk.  Each of these
species is provincially classified as threatened or vulnerable.  By
documenting the use of the Skowquiltz as habitat for these species, we hope
to encourage other researchers to come to the area to carry out more
exhaustive studies.  We'll also use the findings of the study to lobby for
a moratorium on logging of the watershed.

    The Skowquiltz is the largest undeveloped primary watershed in the
mid-coast forest district, with one of the last pristine estuaries of its
size in the region.  This ecologically-rich valley forms part of a 1
million hectare roadless area, which we believe is the largest expanse of
intact temperate rainforest left on the planet.  Unfortunately, the
Skowquiltz is slated for roadbuilding in 1998.  This valley is truly one of
the most precious jewels remaining on the whole mainland coast, and we
cannot allow it fall in to the ongoing chainsaw massacre.


CANADIAN RAINFOREST NETWORK

    FAN also participated earlier this month in the launch of a major new
environmental coalition of 20 diverse environmental groups from across B.C.
and the U.S.  We held a press conference on June 6th to announce the
formation of the Canadian Rainforest Network and issue the coalition's
demands for the temperate rainforest.  We also unveiled a new hotspots map
depicting 10 of the most immediately threatened areas on B.C.'s coast.
World renowned scientists Dr. Elliott Norse and Dr. Michael Soule were on
hand to endorse our demands and explain the global importance of protecting
B.C.'s rainforests.  56 other environmental organizations from around the
world also endorsed the CRN's the demands. The demands are:

* to protect key ecological areas of the temperate rainforest
* to stop all clearcutting in the temperate rainforest
* to halt all roadbuilding in the ancient temperate rainforest
* to support the work of First Nations to protect their traditional
      territories and the survival of their cultures, and
* to promote ecologically sustainable community development

    Quite a strong, new stance for some of the more conservative
participants in the coalition!  Indeed, this is the first time we can think
of that such a broad spectrum of environmental groups - from big,
mainstream groups like the Sierra Club and Natural Resources Defense
Council to small, grassroots, action-oriented groups like FAN - have chosen
to work together in British Columbia.  It's surely a testament to just how
important protecting B.C.'s remaining ancient rainforests is!

    If your organisation wants to officially sign onto the CRN's demands,
contact CRN co-ordinator Jill Thomas at (604) 669-4303, fax (604) 669-6833,
email crn@helix.net

***** Please let us know if you would like a copy of a feature-length
article from the Vancouver Sun on the launch of the coalition.


TRIAL UPDATE

    Currently, FAN is organizing support for the trial of the 22 people
arrested last September at Ista.  (See attached press release.)  The
arrests have had to endure months of repeated trips to Vancouver for court
appearances, only to have the court refuse to address the jurisdiction
question.  Most have also spent several days or even weeks in jail already.
We are now hoping for a speedy resolution of the trial so that everyone
can get on with the other important battles that still lie ahead of us this
summer!


AAC LETTER-WRITING CAMPAIGN

    Unfortunately, the fight does not end with Ista.  There are still many
key pristine areas within Nuxalk territory and elsewhere in the Great Coast
Rainforest scheduled for roadbuilding or clearcutting this summer, and even
more in the following few years.  The level of cutting in most areas of the
province, known as the A.A.C. (Annual Allowable Cut), continues to far
exceed even the government's own estimates of what is sustainable. (For
example, in the mid-coast forest district around Bella Coola, the rate is
47% above what the government has estimated to be sustainable.)  And most
ecologists and ecoforesters would agree that even the government's
estimates of what is sustainable are far too high.  Despite the claims of
sweeping forest reform that the B.C. government has been loudly trumpeting
to the international community, very little has actually changed on the
ground. Clearcutting continues to be used in over 90% of all logging done
in the province, and the new Forest Practices Code has actually resulted in
an increase in roadbuilding into pristine areas.  By limiting the size of
clearcuts and restricting how close together they can be, without lowering
the amount of wood being cut, the Forest Practices Code has actually
dispersed the destruction over about 4 times as great an area!  The truth
remains that the greed for short-term corporate profits means too much is
being taken too fast, leaving behind a legacy of impoverished local
communities as well as degraded ecosystems.

+---------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                                                     |
|     We're calling on all of our supporters around the world to join |
| us in condemning the unsustainable level of cutting in British      |
| Columbia that is destroying the Great Coast Rainforest.  Please     |
| write to the B.C. government and demand that the AAC be drastically |
| lowered.                                                            |
|                                                                     |
|     If you live in one of the primary market countries for B.C.     |
| forest products (US, Japan, England, Germany), tell them your       |
| organisation is working to educate wood products buyers about the   |
| destruction their consumption is causing to this globally important |
| ecosystem.                                                          |
|                                                                     |
|     You can also let the government know that you endorse the       |
| Canadian Rainforest Network's demands.                              |
|                                                                     |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------+

Please write to B.C.'s new Premier Glen Clark, and send copies to the new
Minister of Forests and the B.C.'s Chief Forester (who's officially
responsible for setting the level of the A.A.C.)


