<pre>
So: U-ref
From: bpf@igc.apc.org
Newsgroups: pol.immigrate
Subject: Rockwood on Haiti in Berkeley
Date: 30 May 1996 12:51:52 -0800 (PST)

JAILING THE TRUTH -HAITI, THE U.S. MILITARY, AND CONSCIENCE
AN EVENING OF INQUIRY WITH U.S. ARMY CAPT. LAWRENCE ROCKWOOD
 
 
PRESS RELEASE
 
Contact:
Buddhist Peace Fellowship
510/525-8596
Alan Senauke or Elsie Tep
 
 
"A real danger exists when a society is not willing to address military
issues.  Too often the false cloak of righteousness can be used to mask
what is really an indifference to the suffering of others."
                                                - Lawrence Rockwood
 
U.S. Army Captain Lawrence P. Rockwood is a military
counter-intelligence officer, court martialed in 1995 for following the
orders of his Commander in Chief, President Clinton, to establish peace
and safety in Haiti.  He will speak about his case, the U.S. presence
in Haiti and the forgotten legacy of My Lai and Vietnam at 7:30 PM on
Friday, June 7, at the Berkeley Unitarian Fellowship, at the corner of
Cedar and Bonita Streets  in Berkeley.  He will be joined by honored
guest Maclaine Lumas, an exiled teacher, Methodist activist with
Lavalas, and survivor of the Haitian jails.  Tickets are available at
Gaia Books in Berkeley, Walden Pond Bookstore in Oakland and also from
BPF at 510/525-8596 or EBSC at 510/540-5296.   Suggested donation -
$6-$10.
 
        In September, 1994, Capt.Rockwood obeyed the dictates of his
conscience, walking into a Haitian jail in Port-au-Prince to witness
the conditions for political prisoners held there.  For that action of
honor and concern he was court martialed and removed from active duty.
Lawrence Rockwood, a practicing Buddhist, is presently appealing his
court martial and speaking around the country.  His views challenge the
U.S. military and us as well.
 
        This event is sponsored by the Buddhist Peace Fellowship (BPF)
and the East Bay Sanctuary Covenant's (EBSC) Haiti Committee.
Co-sponsors include the International Action Center, the Bay Area
Haitian-American Council and the Ecumenical Peace Institute.  Proceeds
from the event will support the work of BPF and the EBSC's Material Aid
for Haiti Campaign.
 
 ***********
 
        In 1990, the Haitian people voted for a democracy headed by
Father Jean Bertrand Aristide.  In 1991, Aristide, Haiti's first
democratically-elected president, was ousted in a military coup dUetat
that killed over 4,000 people and forced tens of thousands more to flee
the country.  The Haitian people lived in constant fear of the death
squads of the Front Revolutionaire pour le Avancement et Progres
d'Haiti (FRAPH) who persecuted any who were suspected of supporting the
ideals of the Aristide government.  In September of 1994, U.S. troops
were sent to Haiti to provide a safe and secure environment for the
return of democracy. President Clinton stated the primary objective of
Operation Uphold Democracy was to stop the brutal atrocities that
threaten tens of thousands of Haitians.  Yet the refusal of the U.S.
military to release documentation of the atrocities committed by the
dictatorship and FRAPH and its unwillingness to hold them responsible
for their actions gives credence to the indifferent attitude that
compelled Rockwood to take action.
 
        Witnesses from the National Lawyers Guild have thoroughly
documented the reign of terror in Haiti.  Maclaine Lumas was a second
grade elementary school teacher at John Wesley Methodist School in
Jeremie.  She was active in the neighborhood committee which sponsored
adult literacy, reforestation and social education projects for the
betterment of the area.  She was also a member of Operation Populaire
Lavalas.  From February 1992 through August 1994, she was subjected to
a series of arrests, beatings, and death threats.  In fear for her
life, Maclaine was able to leave her homeland through the efforts of
Bay Area supporters.  A survivor of this systematic violence,
Lumas will share with us her experiences in Haiti as well as her dreams
and concerns for her country's future.
 

.
