<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Waldorf Microwave</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/waldorf.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/micro.jpg">
<h1>Microwave</h1>
<hr>
<h4>Towards the end of the 70's when Wolfgang Palm
developed wavetablesynthesis, he surely couldn't have
foreseen, even in his wildest dreams, that this then
revolutionary technology would stitl serve as a creative
tool today. Nearly twenty years later, both the
Microwave and its big brother,the Wave, are still
satisfying the demands of the current generation of
musicians. What's more, the popularity of Waldorf
sound-generating machines has achieved cult status,
the only comparable instrument being the perennial
MiniMoog.</h4>
<hr><p>
The Microwave, with its midnight blue designer
chassis, red "nose", and a display that is actually much
too small, has survived many generations of ROM
sample players. Its longevity came despite the fact
that in 1989, when it was introduced, many critics
considered its sounds very interesting but ultimately
not viable, since it featured only eight voices and no
FX unit. Why so many musicians (including the upper
echelon of internationally renowned professionals) fell
in love with the Microwave despite this dour forecast is
no great mystery; the Microwave sounds absolutely
unique and it also sounds great. We've already
mentioned wavetable technology, and that's the
reason why the Microwave sounds the way it does.
Authentic analog filters with 24dB roll-off and a more
than extensive modulation matrix also contribute.
In the 80's, the hot sounds were chiming, metallic,
alien-sounding digital sounds, while nowadays, fat,
powerful analog sounds with real-time filtering and
extreme sweeps are hip.<br>
The Microwave generates all of these types of sounds
in an unrivalled quality. Its sounds are synthesized at
the lowest sound generation stage and, basically, are
structured in the same manner as in a classic analog
synthesizer; what this means to you is that the
Microwave is a cinch to program. The sound
generating modules are tuned to deliver a level of
quality that meets the most discerning musician's
demands. You can therefore convert your ideas about
happening, quality sound into reality without having to
add a load of external effects and EQ. This quality
makes the Microwave an inspirational creative tool.
<b>Musicians tend to get addictive about their
Microwaves, and this is precisely the secret of its
phenomenal success.</b>
<hr>
Now that the Mlicrowave has been around for a while,
there is a vast range of interesting sounds available on
RAM and ROM cards as well as on disks. Moreover, we
have kept the Microwave at the cutting edge of
software technology via regular system updates. If you
buy a Microwave today, you will be the proud owner of
a device that incorporates the latest technological
standards. Wolfgang Palm's vision was to implement
his ideas with an eye on the future, and this
philosophy is still a bench-mark at Waldorf, reflected in
all our synthesizers.
<hr>

<a href="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/index.html"><img align=bottom src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/home.gif"></a> 
</BODY></HTML>


























