<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Korg Trinity</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/korg.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/trinity.jpg">
<h1>Trinity Series Music Workstation DRS</h1><hr>
<h2>SOUNDS</h2><b>The TRINITY-Series represents a new breakthrough in PCM sound generation. By painstakingly sampling only the best sounds and processing
them through flexible filters and effects, ACCESS
ushers in a new era in PCM sound quallty.</b><p>

ACCESS fully digitizes sound production from
source to filter to effects. This system takes the
conventional concept of simply sampling good
instrumental sounds under good conditions a giant
step further. It reproduces the best sounds created
by the best artists playing the best instruments
under ideal conditions.<p>
Trinity's large 24MB PCM ROM makes it possible to store 375 multi-samples and 258 drum samples. And it plays back at a state-of-the-art 48kHz
sampling frequency.<p>
A multi-mode filter featuring High-Pass, Low-Pass, Band-Pass and Band-Reject modes plus
Resonance makes highly flexible filtering possible.
Trinity features 100 insert effects and 14 master effects which are used for overall ambiance.
These include reverbs, delays, distortion and
rotary speaker plus new algorithms like a two-
voice resonator, pitch shifting, stereo random
flanging, decimator and many more.<p>
In the sequence and combination modes,
each timhre can have its own insert effects for a
total of up to eight simultaneous effects. For exam-
ple, you can have reverb on a snare, distorted gui-
tar and a chorused electric piano all at the same
time. All these sounds can then go through the
two modulation/delay and reverb/delay master
effects for further processing.<p>

<b>Korg's DSP-based Multi Oscillator Synthesis
System (MOSS) is capable of reproducing and
combining five different synthesis methods like
Analog Synthesis, Physical Modeling and Variable
Phase Modulation (VPM).</b><p>

MOSS', Trinity's other sound source, also
powers Korg's exciting new Prophecy Solo
Synthesizer. It uses DSP to create monophonic
sounds that range from heart-stopping vintage
synth leads and basses through amazingly accurate physical models of brass, reed and plucked
acoustic instruments right on through to sounds
you've never heard before.<p>

<b>Diverse sound programs that consistently deliver.</b><p>

TRINITY is programmed with all the sounds
you require for both live performance and music
production. TRINITY's ACCESS sound source
delivers 256 programs and 256 combinations
while its DSP-based MOSS' sound source delivers an additional 64 programs.<p>
Split, Multi and Layer Combinations are all possible using programs produced by
both sound sources. For example, you can perform solo MOSS" sounds with your
right hand while playing ACCESS sounds with your left! Your sounds can also be
 saved on floppy disk or, with SCSI, onto a hard drive.
<p>
<b>Sample Playback/Flash ROM makes it possible to use an even broader range of sounds.</b><p>

Trinity's PCM memory is substantially expanded with the addition of its
optional 8MB Flash ROM board. When using the optional sample-playback system
disk, data sampled in either the KORG Sample Data Library or the AKAI Sampler
format is read into the flash ROM and 256 program and combination memory
locations are added.<p>
The Flash ROM option provides another bonus. With Flash ROM, Trinity's MOSS'-
based Solo Synth option provides 128 programs -- double the original 64!<p>
<hr>
<h3>TRINITY SERIES SPECIFICATIONS</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Sound Generation Method:</b>
<ul>
<li>ACCESS (Advanced Combined Control Synthesis System)
<li>MOSS (Multi Oscillator Synthesis Synthesis System) -- Solo Synth Option (Solo-TRI)
</ul>
<li><b>Sound Source:</b>
<ul>
<li>ACCESS=32 voices, 32 oscillators (single mode); 16 voices, 32 oscillators (double mode)
<li>MOSS = 1 voice, Multi oscillator
</ul>
<li><b>Keyboard:</b>
TRINITY proX = 88 notes weighted, TRINITY pro = 76 notes, TRINITY plus and TRINITY = 61 notes, with velocity and after-
touch sensitivity
<li><b>Wavetorm Memory:</b> 24 Mbytes PCM ROM
<li><b>Effects;</b> Stereo digital muiti-eftect system, 2 master effects and
8 insert effects simultaneously. 14 effects algorithms for master effect and 100 effects algorithms for insert effect
<li><b>Program/Combination:</b> 256 programs /256 combinations
<li><b>Sequencer Section:</b> 20 songs, 100 patterns, 1/192 resolutions,
80,000 notes, 16 tracks, 16 timbres, Standard MIDI File capability
<li><b>Expansion options</b>
<ol><li>Hard disk recorder option (with
SCSI port); 4 tracks, 16-bit resolution, 48kHz sampling frequency, synchronizes with the built-in MIDI sequencer
<li>SCSI
option (SCSI-TRI)
<li>Sample playback / Flash ROM option (PBS-TRI); 8 Mbyte Flash ROM board and sample playback system disk set
<li>Digital I/F option (DI-TRI); ADAT compatible optical outputs
</ol>
<li><b>Controller:</b> Joystick, Ribbon controller, 2 x
Assignable switch  Control Inputs: Damper pedal (SUSTAIN), Assignable (SWITCH,PEDAL)
<li><b>Outputs:</b> DIGITAL - ADAT compatible <option>, S/P DIF <option> ANALOG - 1/UMONO, 2/R, 3, 4, Headphones * Inputs: DIGITAL - Word clock IN <option>, S/P DIF <option> ANALOG - 1, 2 <option>
<li><b>Floppy Disk Drive:</b> 3.5 inch 2DD/2HD
<li><b>MIDI:</b> IN, OUT, THRU
<li><b>Display:</b> TouchView Graphical User Interface, 320 x 240 dots
<li><b>Power Supply:</b> AC, Local voltage
<li><b>Power Consumption:</b> TRINITY, TRINITY plus and TRINITY pro = 22W, TRINITY proX = 45W
<li><b>Accessories:</b> AC-cord, Preload program disks (TFD-00P and TFD-01P)
<li><b>Dimensions:</b> TRINITY proX = 1,540 (W) x 463 (D) x 147 (H) mm TRINITY pro = 1,297.1 (W) x 348.3 (D) x 125.9
(H)mm TRINITY plus, TRINITY = 1,090.1 (W) x 348.3 (D) x 125.9 (H)mm
<li><b>Weight</b> TRINITY proX = 31.3 kg TRINITY pro = 17.05 kg TRINITY plus = 14.25 kg TRINITY = 14.05 kg
<li><b>OPTIONS:</b>
<ul>
<li>PS-1, PS-2 Pedal Switches
<li>DS-1 Damper Pedal
<li>FC6 Foot Controller
<li>KVP-002 Volume Pedal
<li>XVP-10 EXP/VOL Pedal
<li>EXP-2 Foot Controller
<li>ST-T1 Stand for TRINITY proX, ST-LV Stand for TRINITY pro, TRINITY plus, TRINITY
<li>Hard Cases HC-TRINITY for TRINITY and TRINITY plus, HC-TRINITY pro for TRINITY pro
</ul>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2>FUNCTlON & USER INTERFACE</h2>

<b>With the TRINITY-Series, a musician can perform, compose, arrange and record
with just one instrument. And its easy to-use TouchView Graphical User
Interface and controllers make the TRINITY an efficient tool that enhances, not
hinders, the creative process.</b><p>

<h3>How TouchView Graphical User Interface responds to your touch.</h3><p>
The TRINITY-Series features a TouchView
Graphical User Interface system. TouchView boasts
a large, high resolution 320 x 240 dot touch-screen
display that presents a clear view of the instru-
ment's functions and parameters. Rather than
pressing an endless series of cursor keys to select a
parameter, you simply touch it on the screen.<p>

<h3>On-board 16-track MIDI sequencer.</h3>

Trinity's sequencer is 16-part multi-timbral and features 16-tracks, 1/192 note res-
olution and a memory capacity of 80,000 notes. It is also compatible with Standard
MIDI files. With the TouchView Graphical User Interface, track volume slider and
parameter values can be visually confirmed and operated by just touching the screen.<p>

<h3>Flexible controllers, maximum expression.</h3>

TRINITY features an Alternate Modulation System and Effect Dynamic
Modulation that allow you to assign control sources such as the ribbon controller,
joystick, switches and foot controllers flexibly. And other control sources like the
sound's envelope or note number can also be assigned to yield hands-free, real-
time expression.<p>
It's worth noting that, in addition to the instrument's many other control sources,
TRINITY's pressure-sensitive, dynamic ribbon controller really allows the player to
imprint his personality onto its sounds. Moving one's finger across its surface and
varying pressure with the fingertip provide an intuitive, "gut-level" interface.
<hr>

<h3>DRS (Digital Recording System)</h3>

<b>The TRINITY-Series employs a Digital
Recording System that completely revises the conventional concept of a music workstation. A harddisk recorder and various digital interfaces make
it possible to network a digital reeonting system
configured with ADAT, DATrecorder and harddisk</b><p>

<h4>HaRd Disk Recorder function</h4>

The TRINITY-Series can utilize a 4-track digital
hard disk recorder, making it possible to record
external signals via the input terminal in 16-bit resolution and at a 48kHz sampling frequency.
Punch in/out, copy/insert, delete, erase and other
editing features are all provided. It is capahle of 50
minutes of recording time (using a 543MB hard
disk and recording in stereo at 48kHz).<p>
The built-in MIDI sequencer is also capable of
synchronous control. This means, for example,
that a prerecorded piece can be synchronized
when recording vocals or guitar parts on the hard
disk recorder -- an ability that is not possible with
conventional music workstations.<p>
The TRINITY proX comes standard with a hard
disk recorder and a 543MB on-board hard drive.
<hr>
<b>Korg's new Trinity series of music
workstations features a huge collection of high-quality sounds, new featuras, a new
tone generator, new parameters, a unigue
TouchView- graphical user interface and a
wide variaty of expansion options.</b>
<hr>
With all the new features of this instrument, Korg has
created a fresh palette of sounds to go with them.
The Trinity's PCM ROM features an entirely nev set
of 375 multisounds and 258 drum sounds, sampled at 48kHz.
Great care was taken at the sampling sessions to ensure the
highest quality sound. Everything from top-quality microphones to top musicians were used to get the best source
material from which to create the samples.<p>
The Combination mode features eight timbres, each with
its own key windows and velocity windows for creating
multitimbral layers, splits and complex performance setups.
Add to this another eight timbres and you have the basis for
the Trinity's powerful 16-track 80,000-note sequencer.<p>
The Combination and Sequencer modes feature graphic
faders and panpots that you can adjust simply by touching the
screen! Both modes also take advantage of the Trinity's breakthrough effects system. You can use up to eight simultaneous
insert effects as well as two master effects. This means that you
can put a distortion effect on the guitar track, a rotary speaker
effect on the organ track, heavy flanging on the drum track,
EQ on the bass track...you get the idea. After all that you can
still run everything through varying amounts of chorus and hall
reverb (or flanging and delay, or delay and room reverb, or...)<p>

<b>Room to Grow</b><p>
0ne of the great things about the Trinity that sets it
apart from the rest of the workstations out there is its
wide variety of options. Some of these, like the Solo
Synth option, come standard on all but the base model Trinity.
Others, such as the Flash ROM option are optional for all
models.<p>
The Solo Synth option gives you the heart of Korg's nev,
Prophecy solo synthesizer built right into the Trinity. This
gives you a whole new world of synthesis techniques such as
Physical Modeling for creating emulative and original tone
colors. You can even create combinations and sequences
using these sounds together with the Trinity's A.C.C.E.S.S. tone
generator sounds.<p>
The Flash ROM option lets you add up to eight
megabytes of new sampled sounds. These sounds can come
from Korg sounci libraries or from any Akai format sound
library. When you add the Flash ROM option, you also get
two more banks of programs and combinations -- that's 512
programs and 512 combinations in all! What's more, if you
installed the Solo Synth option, you'll get an additional 64 Solo
Synth memory locations, for a total of 128.<p>
The SCSI option lets you connect a hard disk for saving
your programs, combinations and sequences, or for loading
samples to the Flash ROM. (It is also part of the Hard Disk
Recorder option -- read on.)
The Digital Output option adds an Alesis ADAT
compatihle output for digital transfer of Trinity signals for up
to four channels.
<p>
And last, but certainly not least: the Hard Disk Recorder
option. With this option, it is actually possible to incorporate
up to four tracks of real-world sounds such as vocals, saxophone, guitar -- or anything you want -- into your sequences.
This option makes the Trinity the world's first true music
workstation, allowing the entire music procluction process --
from composing and recording to editing and mixing -- to he
realizedl completely on the Trinity without the need for additional equipment. What's more, you can mix your final product directly to D)AT, keeping everything in the digital domain.<p>

<b>Putting It All Together
</b><p>
Now, lets create a theoretical song. Start by laying
down a basic drum track.Next we'll add bass and
synth pad parts. We can have some of the melody
playedby a physically-modeled trumpet from the Solo Synth
option. Later in the song we'll insert a program change message to clxinge the Solo Synth trumpet to a fat analog synth
bass. Add to this orchestral hits, ethnic percussion and digeridoo samples from the Flash ROM. Then, using the Hard Disk
Recorder, recordl some vocals and a distorted electric guitar
playing rhythmic accents. Finally, from DAT, fly in some
stereo background ambiance recorded at a nearby cafe.<p>
Each sequence track and audio track has its own volume,
panning; and effect sends (the audio tracks can he processed
by the master effects). Each audio track also has its own high
and low EQ. Insert control changes into the sequencer to
change sequence track volume and panning. You can even
automate the Hard Disk Recorder tracks' mix. Now that we've
got everything sounding just right, we can mix down to DAT.<p>

<b>The addition of the Hard Disk Recorder opens new possibilities for music production. You can start by flying-
in a basic rhythm track of drums, bass and guitar from
a DAT and work around that, adding keyboard parts, percussion, special effects and other audio sweetening. You can also
use the Hard Disk Recorder to create huge multitrack
sequences that go beyond the Trinity's 16-track 32-note polyphonic limit, by recording 16 tracks at a time from the S/PDIF
output to the S/PDIF input (this requires an RCA cable). Of
course you'll want to make sure that you are satisfied with the
choice of programs, effects and the mix before doing so,
because it's the sound of the sequence and not the sequence
data itself that gets recorded.<p>
All the henefits of random access are available, such as
the ability to instantly jump to any location of a song without
having to wait. We haven't even touched on the editing capabilities of the Hard Disk Recorder which include the ability to
copy and move auclio in a track, as well as keep multiple
takes of a vocal, for example, ancl edit them together to
create a new take of only the best sections.
After a project is finished, you can back up your hard disk
information to a DAT tape, for archiving and later retrieval.</b>


