<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Steinberg Recycle</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/steinber.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/recycle.jpg">
<p>
<h1>RECYCLE: The Ultimate Tool For Sampled Grooves</h1>
<hr><p>
<h4>Every now and then a truly innovative product hits the market. You know, the kind that makes you shake your head in wonder, maybe smile a little and say: "Now why on earth didn't somebody think of that before? Why didn't I?". Steinberg ReCycle! has just this effect on people. So what is it, anyway?
<p>

Well, that's a tricky one. You see, things that are truly new are often hard to describe. No label sticks to them, no neat little marketing slots fits them. Perhaps you might call it "the first specialized software tool for people using sampled loops and grooves". Or maybe a "breakbeat analyzer and editor". Or maybe something else. Whatever you want to call it, ReCycle! is set to revolutionize the way we work with sampled loops and grooves in much the same way that sampled loops and grooves have revolutionized music itself.
<p>

Pretty BIG words, eh? They get even bigger...</h4>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
We gave up trying to find that magic all-inclusive five
  word description of ReCycle!.
  Instead, let us tell you what it does:
  In simple terms, ReCycle! lets you do with sampled loops
  what you can do with beats programmed from individual
  drum sounds - like alter the tempo, replace the sounds
  and process them individually.
  Sounds impossible?  Wait until you've read the full menu:
<p>
<b>With ReCycle! you can:</b>
  <ul>
<li>Automate the tedious process of making a sampled groove fit the tempo of your song.
<li>  Change the tempo of a groove without altering its pitch.
<li>  Change the pitch of a groove - or the individual hits that make up the groove - without altering its tempo.
<li>  Remove and/or replace any sound inside the sampled groove without altering its feel.
<li>  Send different sounds in the groove to different sampler outputs for individual processing.
<li>  Alter the volume of the individual sounds of the groove.
<li>  Change the timing of the groove - yes, you can even quantize it!
<li>  Use the feel of the groove to quantize other MIDI recordings.
<li>  Alter the ambience of a groove.
<li>  Make pitched grooves (like guitar riffs) fit songs in other keys than the recorded one.
<li>  Automatically isolate and extract individual sounds out of long samples.
<li>  Automatically normalize the levels of the sounds in the groove for optimum sound quality.
<li>  And of course, a whole lot more...
</ul>
<hr>
<p>
<h2>How is it done?</h2>

 As in Japanese cooking, it's all in the slicing.
<p>

 After receiving the groove from the sampler, ReCyc:le! analyzes it (using Digital Signal Processing methods) and breaks it
 up into its rhythmic components.  Each is called a "slice".
<p>

 The process itself is fully automated, but the amount of slices and their "thickness" is controlled by you, using on-screen
 controls and tools.
<p>

 Then, ReCycle! assigns each slice to a MIDI note number, creates a key map and transmits the whole package back to
 the sampler as sample files and a program file.  Each slice can now be triggered individually from its own key on your
 MIDI keyboard.
<p>

 But that's not all.  From the original groove, ReCycle! creates a MIDI file ready for importing into Cubase - or other
 sequencer.  When played back, it triggers each slice in turn, retaining the timing of the original groove.
 Now your groove is under complete MIDI control, while remaining rhythmically intact!
<p>

  Need to change the tempo? just do it!  When the groove is sliced (and stretched if necessary) it'll play back perfectly at
 almost any tempo.  If it doesn't, just edit or quantize it like any MIDI recording.  Since each slice has its own note number,
 programming a fill is no more difficult than doing it with sounds from a drum machine.  You can silence certain hits or
 use Velocity data to control the dynamics of the groove.  And so on...
<p>

 And of course, there is a lot of fun to be had by using the editing functions in your sampler.  You can retune the sounds,
 replace them with others, or send them to individual outputs for external processing (why not add some reverb to the
 snare only?).  You can change the decay of the samples to alter the ambience, or even use other audio processing
 software for further redesign.
<p>
<hr><p>
<h2>How do I use ReCycle!?</h2>
                                                                                             
   A good answer is "instinctively". 
<p>
    ReCycle! is a decidedly non-technical piece of software.  Its menu choices are deceptively few, and its graphic interface is
   clear and user-friendly.  Most processes are fully automated.  Smart analysis algorithms handle the slicing.  The loop position
   markers snap to musically "intelligent" positions in the sound.  You can set the loop positions while auditioning the sound, so
   your ears will tell you when you got it right!
<p>
   Uploading a loop from your sampler, and downloading the resulting slices and program, is a completely automated process.

<p>
<hr><p>
   <h2>You need to ReCycle!</h2>
   Perhaps you have stayed away from using sampled grooves because it  
                                                                             
  seems too technical? An arcane DJ-ing art, beyond the grasp of ordinary      Support for the Ensoniq EPSIEPS 16+

  ivory-tinkling mortals?
<p>
   ReCycle! will make this exciting technique available to you in an intuitive and transparent manner.

   Or maybe you're one of those who think that using

   loops is the aural equivalent of painting

   by numbers?  Then think again.  With ReCycle!

   you have as much musical control over a

   sampled loop as you do with MIDI recording.

   But what if you're a seasoned groove master,

   perhaps with many years of experience?                                              

   Well, then we suggest you read the ReCycle!   
   limenu" once more.  Consider carefully what

   new possibilities each function would give you.

   We're pretty sure you'll find it exciting..
<p>
<hr><p>

<h2> Included Free!</h2>

<ul>
<li>CD with an outstanding collection of loops and
grooves from Sounds Good - creators of the highly
acclaimed Drum Tools and New World Order Sampling CD's!
<li>Cubase Demo Disk
</ul>
<p>

<hr>                                                 
<h2>HARDWARE REQUIREMENTS</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>MAC</b>
Apple Macintosh (SE-30 or later) with 4Mb RAM and a hard disk, System 7.1 or later. Audio playback via Sound Manager 3 on Macs with built-in 8/16 Bit audio support.
<li><b>PC</b>
386DX, 33Mhz, 4Mb of RAM
VGA monitor, hard disk.
Sound playback via MME compatible 16-bit soundcards.
MME-MIDI interface and/or SCSI card (adaptec)  supported. ASPI compatible.
</ul>

<h2>Supported file formats:</h2>
<ul>
<li>Mac: Sound Designer I, Sound Designer II, AIFF.
<li>PC: AIFF and .WAV with loop points
</ul>

<h2>Supported samplers:</h2>
Akai S1000, S1000PB, S1100, S2800, S3000, S3200 and CD3000.
Digidesign Samplecell 1 and 2<br>
Version 1.5: Roland S-760, K-2000/R/2500
Ensoniq EPS, EPS 16+ and ASR 10.
