<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Soundscape</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUNDCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"  background="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/logoback.gif">
<img align=right src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/soundsca.gif">
<img align=top src="http://www.knooppunt.be/~hit_run/caerts/soundsca.jpg">
<h1>Soundscape Multitrack Hard Disk Recorder</h1><hr>
The Soundscape SSHDR1 Multi-track Hard Disk Recorder is a high quality 16 bit digital audio system, which can be used
for both pre and post-production work and can be easily expanded to provide from 8 to 128 tracks of CD quality audio.
The system can be used for recording and composing with MIDI, in a broadcast studio environment for radio program or
jingle arrangement, and also for theatre productions and movie or TV soundtrack recording and editing.
<p>
Each rack mounted unit has 2 track recording and 8 track playback through 4 outputs (configured as 2 stereo pairs), from 64
virtual tracks. As the system is modular, up to 16 rack units can be used together, synchronised with sample rate accuracy,
providing a maximum of 32 inputs, 64 outputs and 128 tracks. This is a standard feature and does not require other software
as with other systems.
<p>
Each unit provides a real-time digital stereo mix of up to 8 tracks from disk and 2 tracks from the analogue or digital inputs.
Fader and pan settings can be changed on-screen or from external controllers in real-time, allowing automated mixing (via
MIDI). With multiple units, an entire stereo mix of all tracks can be produced, completely in the digital domain. The system can
also run as a 4 track, with real-time cross-fading for use with external mixing consoles.
<p>
There are 8 real-time fully parametric digital EQ's per unit and in 4 track mode, the 8 EQ's can be assigned in any combination
to the 4 active tracks. In 8 track mode, 2 tracks can be previewed with all 8 real-time EQ's active and EQ'd takes can be
generated to disk (approximately 4 times faster than real-time).
<p>
Operation is from IBM PC or compatible under Windows 3.1, which makes it possible to run other programs, e.g. a MIDI
sequencer, at the same time (using 386/486 PC only).
<p>
SSHDR1 is currently being used for a wide cross section of audio applications, from recording music in home studios,
up to multiple unit 32 and 48 track systems used by major TV studios for audio post-production linked to video.
Studios with multitrack analogue tape machines can now add digital tracks from SSHDR1 with full chase lock
via SMPTE timecode using a low cost MTC convertor. SSHDR1 can closely follow varispeed from the tape
machine and is frame accurate for use with video. With the release of low cost synchronizers and digital I/0
convertors SSHDR1 can now be used for editing audio tracks from digital multi-track tape machines and the
tape machine can also be used to backup the hard disk.
<hr>
<h3>Features</h3>
<ul>
<li>Professional quality D/A's and A/D's
<li>Full chase lock synchronization
<li>Expandable up to 128 physical tracks
<li>Very fast non-destructive editing
<li>8 real time parametric EQ's
<li>Real time non-destructive fades
<li>Automatic de-glitching
<li>Fader automation
<li>S/PDIF and AES/EBU digital I/0
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>Hardware Specifications</h3>
<ul>
<li>2U 19" rackmounted unit
<li>Physical tracks: 8
<li>Sampling rate: 22.05/32/44.056/44.1/47.952/48KHz
<li>Data format: 16 bit linear
<li>Signal processing: 24-bit internal
<li>Data storage: IDE hard disk, fitted in the rack unit (not supplied), size depends upon recording time required, e.g. 250MB gives 47min 14sec total @ 44.1KHz, 1GB gives 3hrs 9min
<li>2nd internal IDE drive can be fitted giving upwards of 3.4GB allowing 10hrs 42 min recording time
<li>A/D conversion: 16 bit sigma-delta 64 x oversampled
<li>D/A conversion: 18 bit sigma-delta 64 x oversampled
<li>Synchronisation: Master or Slave, MTC, MIDI song pos. pointer + clock
<li>Analogue in: 2 x RCA/cinch, unbalanced -- 10dBv/+4dBv (2 tracks in)
<li>Analogue out: 4 x RCA/cinch, unbalanced + 4dBv
<li>Digital in: 1 x RCA/cinch, S/PDIF format (2 channels)
<li>Digital out: 2 x RCA/cinch, S/PDIF format (4 channels)
<li>Input S/N Ratio: > 93dB un-weighted
<li>Output S/N Ratio; > 113dB un-weighted
<li>Wow and Flutter: Un-measurable
<li>Pro-Audio Option: XLR balanced Analogue inputs and outputs, AES/EBU Digital inputs and outputs (XLR)
<li>Host Interface: IBM-AT: parallel via PC expansion plug-in card (ISA). Supports 2 x 4 track rack units
<li>MIDI: in, thru, out
<li>Back-up medium: DAT-recorder with digital I/0, or via the PC (e.g. to a SCSI optical drive or any logical PC drive)
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>PC Hardware and Operating Requirements</h3>
<ul>
<li>IBM PC-AT or compatible 80386/486 running Microsoft Windows 3.1, local hard disk for operating software (1M byte required) and arrange files
<li>VGA/SVGA graphics adaptor and monochrome/colour monitor (colour SVGA recommended)
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>Software Specifications</h3>
<ul>
<li>Microsoft Windows 3.1 compatible
<li>Using the virtual tracks, up to 64 audio takes can be recorded at the same timing position in an arrangement, allowing for instance, a sub mix of multiple backing vocal harmonies, Instrument solos or sound effects to be selected on any physical track later
<li>Arrangements are created in the arrange window which display PARTS of a soundtrack and play the actual recorded audio TAKES on disk. A TAKE can be used in different ways by any number of PARTS which can play all or any section of the TAKE, e.g. a chorus vocal can be recorded just once, but used four times within an arrangement. These PARTS build up the song or soundtrack, and can be edited in a non-destructive way at waveform level, or 'zoomed out' without reference to the waveform, using a 'snap' to bars/beats/16ths etc
</ul>
<hr>
<h3>Part Edit Functions</h3>
<ul>
<li>Move/Copy/Repeat/Delete/Cut/Glue edit functions
<li>Volume controls (real-time, non-destructive)
<li>Fade in/out (real-time, non-destructive)
<li>Merge (stereo digital mix-down)
<li>Reverse
<li>8 physical output channels, selectable for each PART within a virtual track
<li>Non-destructive sample-resolution editing with 'glitch-less' join
<li>Total disk space is dynamically shared by all tracks
<li>Cycle Record mode with stacked TAKES and pre-roll (like analogue multi-track tape recorder)
<li>Left/Right locators
<li>Synchronisation: MIDI Song Position Pointer+ MIDI clock or MIDI Time Code
<li>Time axis display in SMPTE (hours, minutes, seconds & frames) or Measure (bars & beats)
<li>Arrangements are saved in separate arrange files on the host PC
<li>Backup of audio data takes place on DAT-recorder equipped with digital I/0, or arrangements/takes can be transferred to any logical PC drive
</ul>


<hr>
