<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>McMillan Binch: Canada Responds to U.S. &quot;Cuba&quot; Laws with
a Carrot and a Stick
</TITLE>

<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<P></CENTER>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><CENTER>        Canada Responds to U.S. &quot;Cuba&quot; Laws with
a Carrot and a Stick<BR>
<BR></CENTER></FONT>
The Canada - U.S. dispute over trade with Cuba intensified
on January 1, 1997 when amendments to the <I>Foreign Extraterritorial
Measures Act</I> (&quot;FEMA&quot;) came into force.  The amendments
to FEMA expressly target <I>The Cuban Liberty and Democratic Solidarity
(Libertad) Act of 1996</I> (&quot;<I>Helms-Burton</I>&quot;).
The purpose of the amendments is to deter Canadian companies from
complying with <I>Helms-Burton</I>, while also providing relief
for Canadians who have been sued in the U.S. under that legislation.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>The Stick<BR>
<BR>
</I>The maximum fines that Canadian businesses face if they violate
the <I>Foreign Extraterritorial Measures (United States) Order,
1992, </I>as amended<I> </I>(the &quot;Order&quot;), have been
significantly increased by the amendments.  The Order prohibits
Canadian businesses from complying with U.S. anti-Cuba legislation
such as <I>Helms-Burton</I>.  For a more detailed discussion of
the Order, please refer to McMillan Binch's Website and the article
entitled: &quot;<I>Canadian and U.S. &gt;Cuba' Laws: The Risks
of Getting Caught in the Crossfire</I>&quot;(March 13, 1996).
 The increased Canadian fines are now more in line with the fines
faced by those convicted under U.S. anti-Cuba laws.  The clear
objective is to ensure that companies operating in Canada pay
as much attention to FEMA as to the U.S. legislation. <BR>
<BR>
The maximum fines now faced by Canadians who violate the Order
are:<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=101></TD><TD WIDTH=181>On Summary Conviction<BR>
<BR>

</TD><TD WIDTH=199>Conviction on Indictment<BR>
<BR>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=101><I>Corporation<BR>
<BR>
</I></TD><TD WIDTH=181>$150,000<BR>
<BR>

</TD><TD WIDTH=199>$1.5 million<BR>
<BR>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=101><I>Individual<BR>
<BR>
</I></TD><TD WIDTH=181>$15,000<SUP> </SUP>and/or <BR>
imprisonment for 2 years<BR>
<BR>

</TD><TD WIDTH=199>$150,000<SUP> </SUP>and/or <BR>
imprisonment for 5 years<BR>
<BR>

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>
The amendments to FEMA set out criteria for Canadian courts to
consider in sentencing.  They include the degree of premeditation
in the commission of the offence, the size, scale and nature of
the offender's operations and whether any economic benefits have,
directly or indirectly, accrued to the offender as a result of
having committed the offence.<BR>
<BR>
<I>The Carrot<BR>
<BR>
</I>The amendments to FEMA offer Canadians the following types
of relief if they are sued under <I>Helms-Burton</I>:<BR>
<BR>
<UL>
<LI><I>Helms-Burton Judgments Not Enforceable in Canada C</I>
FEMA now expressly prohibits the recognition and enforcement in
any manner in Canada of any judgment given under <I>Helms-Burton</I>.
</UL>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier New"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><I>Recovery of Expenses Before Final Judgment C</I> The Attorney
General of Canada is authorized to maintain a schedule of foreign
trade laws which in his opinion are contrary to international
law or international comity. Currently, all of the provisions
<I>Helms-Burton</I> are on the schedule. Where proceedings are
instituted under a foreign trade law listed in the schedule, and
no final judgment has been given under those proceedings, a Canadian
party may, with the consent of the Attorney General, at any time
during the proceedings sue the person who instituted the action
and recover all expenses incurred by the party in defending those
proceedings and in instituting proceedings under FEMA, including
legal and other costs.
</UL>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Courier New"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><I>&quot;Clawback Rights&quot; C</I> A Canadian against whom
a final judgment under <I>Helms-Burton</I> has been rendered may
apply to the Attorney-General for an order declaring that that
party may recover from the person in whose favour the <I>Helms-Burton</I>
judgment was given (the &quot;foreign party&quot;), any or all
amounts obtained under the judgment, expenses incurred, or loss
or damages suffered. Once such an order is issued, the Canadian
party may sue the foreign party in Canada. To enforce the clawback
right, in addition to any other available means of enforcement,
a Canadian court is authorized to order the seizure and sale of
the property of the foreign party (or any person who controls,
or is a member of a group of persons that controls, the foreign
party). Such property includes shares of any corporation incorporated
by or under a law of Canada or a province, regardless of where
the share certificates are located.<BR>
</UL>
<P>
<I>The Future<BR>
<BR>
</I>The amendments to FEMA send a message to Canadian companies
that business with Cuba must go on as usual.  The relief mechanisms
provide a carrot for maintaining business relations with Cuba.
 If the carrot fails to entice, the government's stick has also
gotten a lot bigger.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
      <P ALIGN=RIGHT>  January 3, 1997<BR>
<BR><P ALIGN=LEFT>
Edward Akkawi:  (416) 865-7088<BR>
Neil Campbell:  (416) 865-7025<BR>
John Kazanjian: (416) 865-7071<BR>
<P>
