<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>McMillan Binch: GETTING THE DEAL THROUGH: A GUIDE TO INTERNATIONAL MERGER CONTROL
</TITLE>

<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<P></CENTER>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>
<CENTER>GETTING THE DEAL THROUGH: <BR>
A GUIDE TO INTERNATIONAL MERGER CONTROL<BR>
<BR>
Canada Chapter<BR>
<BR>
By<BR>
John F. Clifford<BR>
J. William Rowley, QC<BR>
McMillan Binch<BR>
Toronto, Canada<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER></FONT>
<P>
1.      What is the relevant legislation and who enforces it?
<BR>
<BR>
The Competition Act, a federal statute, governs all aspects of
Canadian competition law, and provides one stop shopping for the
review and control of mergers.<BR>
<BR>
The Director of Investigation and Research (the &quot;Director&quot;)
has exclusive authority to investigate and restrain mergers. 
The Director alone can move to block a merger by seeking an order
of the Competition Tribunal, Canada's first level adjudicator
respecting mergers having competitive implications in relevant
markets.  A reference to the Competition Tribunal occurs only
if, after Competition Bureau staff conduct a thorough investigation
and attempt to resolve any competition law concerns with the parties,
the Director concludes that the merger is likely to prevent or
lessen competition substantially in Canada.<BR>
<BR>
2.      Is filing mandatory or voluntary?<BR>
<BR>
Pre-notification is not required in all cases:  The statutory
requirement to pre-notify applies only to what may be described
as larger transactions where the transaction size and the size
of the parties involved exceed certain thresholds.<BR>
<BR>
Even if the statutory thresholds are not exceeded, thus imposing
no positive obligation on the parties to pre-notify, the parties
to a transaction that may have a significant anti-competitive
impact typically notify the Director informally about the transaction.
 In respect of such transactions, the parties should prepare and
file information similar to that which would be provided if pre-notification
were required.  Failing this, the Director may, at worst, seek
injunctive relief to oppose the transaction, or, at best, conduct
an investigation and make information requests which can delay
completion of the transaction.<BR>
<BR>
3.      What kind of transactions are caught?<BR>
<BR>
Subject to certain exemptions, pre-notification is required for
four types of transactions, namely: share acquisitions, asset
acquisitions, amalgamations and unincorporated combinations.<BR>
<BR>
4.      What are the jurisdictional thresholds?<BR>
<BR>
Share and asset acquisitions and combinations are notifiable if
they involve acquisition of assets or a company having assets
valued in excess of CDN$35 million, or gross revenues from sales
in or from Canada exceeding CDN$35 million.  To be mandatorily
notifiable a share acquisition must also involve acquisition of
a minimum percentage of voting shares (generally, 20% in the case
of a public company and 35% in the case of a privately-held company).
 Amalgamations are pre-notifiable if the aggregate value of assets
in Canada of the continuing corporation, or the gross revenues
from sales in or from Canada generated by those assets, exceeds
CDN$70 million.<BR>
<BR>
If a transaction is of a type described above, a pre-notification
is required unless it also fits within one of the statutory exemptions.
 While there are a good many of these, two may be considered basic
and should operate to exempt a wide variety of deals:<BR>
<BR>
(a)     if the parties (together with their affiliates) have assets
in Canada or gross revenues from sales in, from or into Canada
of less than CDN$400 million in aggregate, then pre-notification
is not required.<BR>
(b)     a similar exemption exists if the transaction does not
involve an operating business (a term defined in the Competition
Act to mean a business undertaking in Canada to which employees
employed in connection with the undertaking ordinarily report).
<BR>
<BR>
5.      Are foreign-to-foreign mergers caught?<BR>
<BR>
The Canadian interests giving rise to an obligation to pre-notify
may be held directly by a non-Canadian-based corporation, or indirectly
through its control of a Canadian or other subsidiary or subsidiaries.
 Accordingly, transactions which occur entirely outside of Canada
will be notifiable if the relevant Canadian businesses meet the
statutory thresholds.<BR>
<BR>
6.      What are the sanctions for not filing?<BR>
<BR>
A positive obligation to file rests on each party proposing the
transaction, and  those who fail to notify when so obliged run
the risk of criminal charges.  A person convicted of failing to
comply with the pre-notification provisions of the Competition
Act is liable to a fine not exceeding CDN$5,000 or to imprisonment
for up to two years, or both.  Any director of a corporation who
acquiesces or participates in the commission of such offense by
the corporation is subject to the same liability.  In addition,
the Director may seek injunctive relief to prevent a transaction
from closing, or in the case of a competitively significant transaction,
other remedial measures, including dissolution of the merger,
if the transaction has been completed.<BR>
<BR>
7.      What are the filing deadlines?<BR>
<BR>
Pre-notification filings may be made at any time, but must be
made in sufficient time for the statutory waiting periods to expire
before closing the transaction (the waiting periods are discussed
more fully below).  A party may file prior to the announcement
date of a notifiable transaction provided all the information
required to complete the filing is available. <BR>
<BR>
8.      Who is responsible for filing?<BR>
<BR>
The Competition Act imposes filing obligations on the &quot;person
or persons who are proposing the transaction&quot;.  Except in
unusual circumstances, the parties to the transaction will be
considered to be the persons proposing it, and thus will have
an obligation to file.  Counsel for each party typically prepares
a filing on behalf of its own client, and files it separately,
although simultaneously, with the Competition Bureau.<BR>
<BR>
9.      What is the timetable for clearance and can it be speeded
up?<BR>
<BR>
There is no mechanism under the Competition Act to shorten the
waiting periods, although amendments proposed to be made to the
Competition Act would permit the Director to waive or abridge
the waiting periods.<BR>
<BR>
10.     Are there waiting periods and does implementation of the
transaction have to be suspended?<BR>
<BR>
The Competition Act contemplates notification being made in short
form or long form, at the election of the filing party, and provides
for two alternative very short waiting periods following notification.
 A notifiable transaction cannot close until the relevant statutory
waiting period has expired.  <BR>
<BR>
If a short form of notice is used, the transaction may be completed
on the eighth day after the completed filing has been received
by the Director, unless the Director exercises his discretion
to require a long form notice or obtains an order preventing completion
of the transaction.  If a long form of notice is used, the transaction
may be completed on the twenty-second day after the completed
filing has been received by the Director unless the Director has
obtained an order preventing completion of the transaction.  
<BR>
<BR>
In practice, the waiting periods have proven to provide too short
a time frame for the Director adequately to review larger and
more complex transactions.  Possible amendments to the Competition
Act currently under discussion by the Director include extending
the waiting periods to fourteen and forty-two days, respectively.
<BR>
<BR>
11.     What are the issues involved in closing before clearance?
<BR>
<BR>
After expiry of the statutory waiting periods, the parties may
complete the transaction.  But, transactions which have the appearance
of competitive significance, whether pre-notifiable or not, will
be closely reviewed by the Director, and the Director has the
ability under the Competition Act to seek an injunction to prohibit
any such transaction.  Inevitably this has meant the voluntary
extension of time periods in transactions of competitive significance.
<BR>
<BR>
When the Director makes it known to the parties that he cannot
complete his investigation prior to the expiry of the waiting
periods or prior to a scheduled closing date, the parties customarily
will undertake to the Director in writing not to complete the
transaction until his investigation is completed, or for a reasonable
period to allow for investigation, or not to close except on prior
notice to the Director.  The undertaking essentially puts the
Director in the same position he would have been in had he moved
for an interim order before the Competition Tribunal without subjecting
the parties and the Director to the hostility and cost of litigation.
 The parties may also be expected to undertake to operate on an
arm's length and business as usual basis and to not change their
business activities in contemplation of the transaction.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Hold-separate&quot; arrangements may also be agreed in limited
circumstances, but hold-separate commitments are not a common
feature of Canadian merger practice.<BR>
<BR>
12.     What is involved in the preparation of a filing?<BR>
<BR>
The filing requirements are prescribed under the Corporation Act,
and the length of any particular filing will depend on the nature
and size of the parties' Canadian operations.  Typically, the
information required to complete a filing can be set out in 10-15
pages plus securities filings and draft legal documents which
will constitute the bulk of the filing.  Filings may be made in
either the French or English language.<BR>
<BR>
In the case of a short form filing, the transaction must be described
together with business objectives which are hoped to be achieved.
 In addition, the parties, together with certain of their affiliates,
must be identified and their respective businesses and lines of
business described and quantified.  This description must include
a list of current principal suppliers and customers and a statement
of annual purchases therefrom and sales thereto, respectively.
 Pro forma financial statements, other financial information and
copies of securities filings, if any (whether in Canada or elsewhere),
for a two-year preceding period are required to be submitted.
 Finally, copies of all relevant legal documents (including most
recent drafts) that are to be used to implement the transaction
must accompany the filing.<BR>
<BR>
In addition to the information which is required to be provided
in a short form filing, a long form filing must also include a
description of the business and lines of business (together with
supplier and customer information) of certain wholly-owned and
wholly-owned affiliates of the parties and a description (including
a statement of sales) of the principal categories of the products
of the business and a principal category of products purchased
by the parties and their affiliates.  Where the parties, directly
or indirectly, own more than 20% of the voting shares of any Canadian
operating business, disclosure of such holdings must be made.
 In addition, copies of all reports and data prepared to assist
the parties' directors and senior officers in analysing the transaction
must accompany the filing.  Finally, if any decision, commitment
or undertaking has been made by any of the parties in respect
of significant changes in any business to which a proposed transaction
relates, a summary description of the same must be disclosed.
<BR>
Provision in made in the forms for the parties to supply additional
analytical information to assist the Director in his review of
the proposed transaction.  The circumstances of each transaction
will dictate whether additional information should be supplied
and when such information should be filed.  In practice, the parties
have a variety of options ranging from a short summary analysis
of the transaction to a detailed &quot;white paper&quot; or a
competitive impact analysis.  In a transaction of competitive
significance the parties will inevitably be requested to provide
more information than that required in a short or long form filing.
 The parties to such transactions will likely find it useful to
provide the Director, in advance, with the documents and other
evidence he is bound to seek in the course of his assessment.
<BR>
<BR>
In order to mitigate the filing burdens, a number of provisions
have been introduced which limit a parties' obligation to submit
information.  For example, a filing party is not required to supply
information that is not known or reasonably obtainable or without
breaching a confidentiality requirement.  An exemption is also
provided where to comply would require the filing party to provide
information that could not reasonably be considered to be relevant
to an assessment by the Director of the transaction's competitive
impact.<BR>
<BR>
A statement must be given under oath if information is not being
supplied for reasons of confidentiality, lack of knowledge or
irrelevance.  The statement must include the reasons for not providing
the information.  The contents of the filing must also be certified
on oath or affirmation as having been examined by the person providing
the certificate and as being, to the best of his knowledge and
belief, correct and complete in all material respects.<BR>
<BR>
13.     What are the basic procedures after filing?<BR>
<BR>
The investigative process involves an ongoing dialogue and negotiations
between Competition Bureau staff and the merger parties, even
following the staff's initial recommendation to the Director.
 An investigation may be include document requests from the parties
(there is some movement to requests on the scale of US document
demands) and information requests from third parties.  The Director's
current policy is to require that responses to requests for information
(from the merger parties and complainants) be provided under oath
or affirmation.<BR>
<BR>
14.     What is the substantive test for clearance?<BR>
<BR>
The basic test, to be applied by both the Director and the Competition
Tribunal, is whether the merger is likely to prevent or lessen
the competition substantially in relevant geographic and product
markets.  This test applies to all mergers (a defined term which
covers essentially any acquisition of control over or a significant
interest in the whole or part of a business of another person),
whether or not the transaction is notifiable.<BR>
<BR>
Canadian competition authorities take a functional and analytic
approach to what may constitute a substantial prevention or lessening
of competition.  In 1991, the Director issued Merger Enforcement
Guidelines (&quot;Guidelines&quot;) which provide a detailed outline
of the Competition Bureau's approach to analysis and enforcement
of the merger laws.  Although reliable generally, the Guidelines
are not a binding statement of policy, and they do not have the
force of law.<BR>
<BR>
The Director takes the position that a prevention or lessening
of competition can only result from a merger where the parties
are or would likely be able to exercise a greater degree of market
power, unilaterally or interdependently with others, after completion
of the merger than if the merger did not proceed.  In considering
this question, the Director looks principally at whether the merged
entity would profitably be able to influence prices through unilateral
action, or as a result of increased opportunity for interdependent
behaviour (which extends beyond conscious parallelism to collusion).
<BR>
<BR>
The Competition Act expressly provides that the Competition Tribunal
(and thus the Director) may not find a merger or a proposed merger
prevents or lessens competition substantially solely on the basis
of concentration of market share.  The Guidelines make it clear
that concentration is a necessary but not sufficient condition
for finding a substantial lessening of competition.  There are
two so-called &quot;safe harbours&quot; in the Guidelines.  The
first provides that, absent any concern about coordinated behaviour,
if the post-merger market share of the merged entity is less than
35%, it is presumed not to be able unilaterally to exercise greater
market power and the merger normally will not be challenged. 
The second safe harbour applies where anti-competitive effects
are thought likely because of interdependent behaviour.  In such
circumstances, the Guidelines provide that a merger is not likely
to warrant a detailed review where the post-merger market share
of the merged entity is less than 10%, or where the post-merger
market share of the four largest firms in the market is less than
65%.  As market shares rise beyond the safe harbours, the likelihood
of the Director developing a concern will rise.<BR>
<BR>
Structural and behavioural characteristics of relevant antitrust
markets are important, and the Competition Act suggests that the
Competition Tribunal (and thus the Director) have regard to a
series of factors, each of which is discussed fully in the Guidelines.
 These include:<BR>
<BR>
<UL>
<LI>effective competition from foreign products or foreign competitors;
<LI>whether the business, or part of the business, of a party
to the merger or a proposed merger has failed or is likely to
fail;
<LI>the availability of substitute products;
<LI>entry barriers into the market;
<LI>the extent to which effective competition remains;
<LI>any likelihood that the merger or a proposed merger would
or would result in the removal of a vigorous and effective competitor;
<LI>the nature and extent of change of innovation in relevant
markets; and
<LI>any other factor that is relevant to competition in an affected
market.<BR>
</UL>
<P>
Three factors, ease of entry, business failure and effective remaining
competition, have become trump cards in that any in and of itself
may be accepted by the Director as sufficient to demonstrate that
a merger will not prevent or lessen the competition substantially.
<BR>
<BR>
The Competition Act provides a number of exemptions from coverage.
 These include where the Director has issued an advance ruling
certificate in respect of the merger; certain bank amalgamations;
joint ventures for special projects; and a statutory efficiency
defence.<BR>
<BR>
15.     To what extent are non-competition issues relevant to
the review process?<BR>
<BR>
While the Director is appointed by and serves at the pleasure
of the federal Cabinet, his duties are statutory.  The Director
traditionally has exercised an independent mandate to protect
the public interest in a competitive market place, and is not
influenced by broader public policy concerns such as reductions
in employment that might result from the merger.<BR>
<BR>
16.     Are the authorities influenced by the decision of other
authorities?<BR>
<BR>
Transactions that cross borders are a common place in Canada,
and many mergers will have similar impacts in Canada and the United
States.  While the Director will make his own determination of
the likely impact of a merger in Canada (and may take remedial
action against transactions which are approved in other jurisdictions),
he will be influenced by decisions taken by other antitrust enforcement
agencies, particularly in the United States.  It should be expected
that enforcement agencies will share their views on the possible
effects of a transaction and positions taken by the parties. 
It is therefore important to ensure that counsel in the various
jurisdictions in which submissions are made coordinate their thinking
to ensure that a position is not taken in one jurisdiction which
might prejudice a position taken in another.<BR>
<BR>
17.     Is it possible to remedy competition issues?<BR>
<BR>
If, as a result of her examination, the Director comes to the
view that a proposed merger is likely to prevent or lessen the
competition substantially, he will inform the parties of his initial
conclusions and the reasons for them.  The purpose behind this
approach is to provide the parties with an opportunity to see
whether the transaction can re-structured so as to overcome his
concerns.<BR>
<BR>
Pre-closing restructurings will be investigated by the Director's
staff to determine whether they adequately address the concerns
identified.  If such a solution presents itself, and the parties
are prepared to accept such a change in their deal, this is usually
the end of the matter.  Because the restructuring will have taken
place prior to closing, the Director's concerns will have been
answered and there will be no basis upon which the transaction
can properly be made the subject of a Competition Tribunal application.
 The reality is that many commercial deals simply cannot be held
together for the length of time which is usually necessary to
complete a divestiture of a division, or something similar so
as to effect a fix-it first solution.<BR>
<BR>
18.     What rights do complainants have?<BR>
<BR>
There is no right in a private party to attack a merger, whether
before the Competition Tribunal or the regular courts, which the
Director does not choose to contest.  This is so no matter how
adversely affected by the merger such a party may be.  However,
if the Director brings an application to the Competition Tribunal
with respect to the merger, parties affected by the merger may
intervene and make submissions.  In addition, those who believe
themselves to be detrimentally affected by a merger may complain
to the Director with a view to having him look into the transaction.
 Information provided by a complainant will be investigated and
verified by Competition Bureau staff, and complainants will be
requested to provide that information under oath or affirmation.
<BR>
<BR>
19.     What publicity is given to the process?<BR>
<BR>
The Competition Act requires that investigations be conducted
in private.  Persons involved in the administration or enforcement
of the Act are prohibited, with limited exceptions, from disclosing
information required by the Act to be provided in support of a
pre-notifiable transaction, or the fact that a pre-notification
or other information was provided in respect of a pre-notifiable
transaction.  These types of information may only be disclosed
(a) if the information is otherwise made public; (b) to a &quot;Canadian
law enforcement law agency&quot;; or (c) &quot;for the purposes
of the administration or enforcement of the Act.<BR>
<BR>
20.     What are the enforcement powers?<BR>
<BR>
Where the Director elects to refer a merger to the Competition
Tribunal, the Competition Tribunal Act provides for a straight
forward process of complaint, answer, discovery, hearing and decision.
 The procedure is open and public, although orders for in camera
proceedings may be made.  Where it is found if the merger will
lessen competition substantially, the Tribunal may (a) prohibit
a not-yet consummated merger; (b) order dissolution or divestiture;
(c) grant conditional approval; and/or (d) prohibit certain future
acquisitions.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
21.     What is the role of ministerial or other government involvement?
<BR>
<BR>
The Competition Bureau operates as a virtually independent agency
within the federal Department of Industry.  As indicated above,
the Director has considerable sensitivity about attempts to influence
exercise of his discretion.  Over time, a corresponding sensitivity
has developed in the government.<BR>
<BR>
This is not to suggest that the Director's office is off-limits
to other federal officials or to politicians.  Indeed, those who
have to steer a merger through the Director's examination will
often find close allies and important evidence in other government
departments.  However, in marshalling support of this nature,
it is important to ensure that it is offered in the context of
the factors which the Director may properly consider in assessing
a proposed merger.<BR>
<BR>
22.     What are the opportunities for judicial review?<BR>
<BR>
If the Director elects to oppose a merger, his sole recourse is
to apply to the Competition Tribunal for an order.  A decision
or order of the Competition Tribunal may be appealed to the Federal
Court of Appeal, whether final, interlocutory or interim in nature.
 There is no provision for the override of Competition Tribunal
decisions or orders by the federal Cabinet or any other political
body or agency.<BR>
<BR>
23.     Are there also rules on foreign investment, special sectors
or relevant approvals?<BR>
<BR>
A non-Canadian seeking to establish or acquire control of a Canadian
business may find its proposed transaction requires some other
approval, including notification or in some cases review by the
federal Minister of Industry under the Investment Canada Act.
 The review thresholds are based on the gross assets of the business
to be acquired: CDN$5 million for direct acquisitions, and CDN$50
million for an indirect acquisition.  Transactions subject of
review are reviewed under a &quot;net benefits to Canada&quot;
test.  <BR>
As a result of amendments to the Investment Canada Act implementing
GATT agreements to establish the World Trade Organization, higher
thresholds for review apply to acquisitions by so-called WTO investors
(nationals or permanent residents of World Trade Organization
countries) and to acquisitions of companies controlled by WTO
investors.  Indirect acquisitions by WTO investors are not subject
to review (although must still be notified), and the review threshold
for direct acquisitions is CDN$160 million (in constant 1994 dollars,
adjusted annually).<BR>
<BR>
In addition, mergers in several regulated industries may be subject
to notification and review under industry-specific legislation.
 Examples include mergers involving broadcast undertakings, life
insurance companies, loan companies and banks.<BR>
<BR>
UPDATE AND TRENDS<BR>
<BR>
(a)     Cases   <BR>
The relatively recent enactment of the merger provisions (in 1986)
and the compliance oriented enforcement approach of the Director
have resulted in there being, as yet, only three contested merger
applications decided by the Competition Tribunal, one of which
related to the amendment of a consent order.  A fourth contested
merger is currently ongoing.  Those cases plus three others which
proceeded on the basis of a consent order comprise the entire
body of merger case law.<BR>
<BR>
In the two contested merger cases considered to date by the Competition
Tribunal, the Competition Tribunal focused on real-world behaviour
of consumers and competitors rather than theoretical or statistical
economic evidence to analyse the subject mergers and determine
their competitive effects.  The Competition Tribunal's approach
in both cases was sensible and pragmatic, although somewhat vague.
 Notwithstanding that the Competition Tribunal's interpretation
of the merger provisions is basically consistent with, although
somewhat less formal than, the approach of the Director in his
Guidelines, in neither case did the Competition Tribunal specifically
endorse the Guidelines approach to merger analysis, and in one
case it did not even mention the Guidelines.<BR>
<BR>
The Federal Court of Appeal for the first time recently considered
the product market dimensions of assessing competitive effects
of a merger.   The Court conducted a wide ranging review of Canadian
and US antitrust authorities on approaches to product market definition
before concluding that the Competition Tribunal had taken too
narrow an approach in its original decision.  Without accepting
any particular paradigm, the Court concluded that the Competition
Tribunal had given inadequate attention to indirect evidence of
broad &quot;inter-industry competition&quot;, and had erred by
requiring statistical or anecdotal evidence of high price sensitivity.
 The decision is currently on appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada.
<BR>
<BR>
(b)     Legislative Amendments<BR>
<BR>
In June 1995, the Director initiated discussions regarding possible
amendments to the Competition Act.  The federal minister responsible
recently announced the government's intention to proceed with
some of the proposed amendments, including amendments to the merger
pre-notification scheme.  In addition to doubling the waiting
periods (described above), a number of technical amendments will
be made and new exemptions introduced.  Amendments to the substantive
merger provisions of the Competition Act are not contemplated.
 <BR>
<BR>
(c)     Filing Fees<BR>
<BR>
Canada does not currently impose user or filing fees.  In 1993,
the Director proposed that a fee in the range of CDN$12,000 -
15,000 be levied in connection with any pre-notification filing.
 He has since indicated that when his proposal is implemented
(possibly later this year) the fees will be higher than initially
proposed.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
        SUMMARY OF INTERNATIONAL MERGER FILING REQUIREMENTS<BR>
