<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>WHEN SHOULD A PRIVATE COMPANY 
NO LONGER BE ONE?<P>
BY<BR>
<P>
MARGARET C. MCNEE<SUP><A HREF="#0">*</A><BR>
</SUP>
McMILLAN BINCH<BR><B></B></FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
Many business lawyers who deal with private companies assume that
the prospectus and registration exemptions under the<I> Securities
Act</I> (Ontario) for securities of private companies are generally
available to private companies. However, this is not always the
case. A company which has private company<SUP><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#1">1</A></FONT></SUP>
restrictions in its articles (restrictions on share transfer and
the number of shareholders - not more than 50 exclusive of employees
and former employees, and a prohibition on offering securities
to the public)<SUP><FONT SIZE=2> <A HREF="#2">2</A></FONT></SUP> may find itself
in the position when it is in fact offering its securities to
the public in a number of common situations. For example, a small
number of sophisticated investors with no prior relationship to
the company may be interested in investing in it. Or the company
may be prepared to offer securities as an incentive to a large
number of employees. In each of these cases the recipients of
the securities may be members of the public for purposes of securities
regulation.<BR>
<P>
Case law has interpreted the concept of the &quot;public&quot;
broadly. Two tests have been articulated. The first is the &quot;common
bonds of association&quot; test which requires an investor who
is not a member of the public to have a common bond of interest
or association with the issuer of securities<SUP><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#3">3</A></FONT></SUP>
(and not just a relationship with other investors in the securities)<SUP><FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#4">4</A></FONT></SUP>. The second test, established in American case
law, identifies members of the public on the basis of whether
they &quot;need to know&quot; the type of information about the
issuer which a prospectus would provide.<SUP><FONT SIZE=2> <A HREF="#5">5</A></FONT></SUP>
At least one Ontario Securities Commission decision has required
both tests to be met before it is established that investors are
not members of the public.<SUP><FONT SIZE=2> <A HREF="#6">6</A><BR>
</FONT></SUP>
<P>
As a result of this broad definition of who constitutes the public,
questions can often arise over the availability of securities
exemptions when a private company proposes to issue securities.
For example, a private company which requires financing may approach
a venture capital investor or investors either directly or through
an agent. These investors may not &quot;need to know&quot; because
they will do their own due diligence. However, especially if they
have been found through an agent, they will be unlikely to have
common bonds of association with the private company. As a result
the company may be offering its securities to the public.<SUP><FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#7">7</A></FONT></SUP> Fortunately, the private placement exemptions<SUP><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#8">8</A>
</FONT></SUP>from the prospectus and registration requirements
of the <I>Securities Act</I> are available where the investors
purchase at least $150,000 of securities<SUP><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#9">9</A></FONT></SUP>.
However, it will be necessary to amend the company's articles
to remove the private company restrictions (this requirement will
be highlighted if the company's counsel is asked to opine that
the transaction will not result in a breach of the company's articles).
It will also be necessary for the company to file a Form 20 with
the Ontario Securities Commission reporting on the trade and pay
a fee. In addition, the securities of the former private company
will become caught in the closed system and be subject to resale
restrictions.<BR>
<P>
If the proposals recommended by the Task Force on Small Business
Financing are implemented, other exemptions would be available<SUP><FONT SIZE=2><A HREF="#10">10</A>
</FONT></SUP>to permit investment by accredited inventors or in
securities of closely-held business issuers.<BR>
<P>
In some instances even a company's employees may constitute the
public. Especially where the company has a considerable number
of employees, some employees will neither have the common bonds
with their employers nor will they have the familiarity with their
employer which would address their &quot;need to know&quot;. However,
prospectus and registration exemptions are available for trades
by an issuer to its employees or employees of an affiliate.<SUP><FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#11">11</A></FONT></SUP> Again, it will be necessary to remove the private
company restrictions from the company's articles, certain reporting
obligations arise and the securities of the former private company
become caught in the closed system and subject to resale restrictions.
<BR>
<P>
Advisors to private companies should be aware of who may be members
of the public when the company proposes to issue securities and
assess whether the private company restrictions should be removed
from the company's articles.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="WNew.pb.gif">  

