<P>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>REASONABLE EXPECTATIONS AND A PRINCIPLED
<BR>
APPROACH TO FORUM SHOPPING<B><SUP><A HREF="#1">1</A><BR>
</SUP></B></FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
I. INTRODUCTION<!--I.  INTRODUCTION-->
<P>
Forum shopping has been a favourite past time of litigators for
centuries, probably for as long as there have been forums.<SUP><A HREF="#2">2</A></SUP>
Current trends such as the increased globalization of trade and
manufacturing, as well as greater ease of communication and travel
have given the issue increased importance in recent years and
are likely to continue to do so.
<P>
In recent years the legal tests surrounding forum shopping in
Anglo-Canadian law have undergone numerous reformulations. This
paper argues that the reformulations have been required because
courts are applying rules developed for another age and are applying
them in a mechanistic fashion without regard to the policies which
the courts really mean to advance. A review of the recent Canadian
and English cases suggests that the real goal of most courts in
forum shopping cases is to help the parties achieve their reasonable
expectations. This is rarely enunciated by courts who appear to
feel bound to fit their square cases into round precedents. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
Conflicts between jurisdictions seem to arise where one court
ignores the reasonable expectations of the parties and applies
its jurisdictional rules without reference to the purpose behind
them. The express recognition of the reasonable expectations of
the parties as a guiding factor in forum shopping cases would
significantly decrease the possibility of conflicts between forums,
decrease the amount of time and energy associated with forum shopping
and make it significantly easier for practitioners to predict
accurately which is the appropriate forum in which to argue a
case.<BR>
<P>
This paper will first examine what forum shopping is and what
factors promote it. Second, it will review the recent reformulations
of the law concerning <I>forum non conveniens. </I>Since the principle
of <I>forum non conveniens</I> lies at the root of all forum shopping
cases, the bulk of the paper will be devoted to the review of
these principles. For ease of reference, the concept of the appropriate
forum will be referred to as <I>forum non conveniens</I> even
though some jurisdictions may not apply the doctrine by that name.
Third, the paper will examine the concept of reasonable expectations
for the purpose of determining whether it ought to form a basis
of choosing between different forums. Finally, the paper will
examine how the incorporation of reasonable expectations in the
principles of <I>forum non conveniens</I> will affect the law
concerning anti-suit injunctions and negative declarations. <BR>
<P>
II. WHAT IS IT AND WHY IS IT?<BR>
<P>
Most simply defined, forum shopping is the act of choosing one
forum in which to litigate when a number of choices are possible.
A widely acceptable definition is difficult to arrive at because
courts rarely, if ever, discuss the policies or principles underlying
their decisions in forum shopping cases. They tend to condemn
a choice as <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>forum shopping<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>
when they wish to express distaste for it and describe the choice
as appropriate when they agree with it.<SUP><A HREF="#3">3</A></SUP> The Supreme
Court of Canada has defined forum shopping as choosing a forum
to gain a juridical advantage rather than choosing a forum because
of its real and substantial connection to the case.<SUP><A HREF="#4">4</A></SUP>
<BR>
<P>
Plaintiffs are the most frequent forum shoppers by choosing where
to initiate their actions. Defendants, however, also have a number
of tools at their disposal which enable them to engage in forum
shopping. The most common of these are motions to set aside service
on the basis that the forum does not have jurisdiction, motions
to stay an action on the basis of <I>forum non</I> <I>conveniens</I>,
anti&#173;suit injunctions and negative declarations. <BR>
<P>
A motion to set aside service tends to be the least useful of
these tools. Most jurisdictions permit some sort of service <I>ex
juris</I>. Some permit service <I>ex juris</I> without leave of
the court, others require leave. Most jurisdictions also provide
a mechanism for setting aside service <I>ex juris</I> in appropriate
circumstances. Although the tests vary from one jurisdiction to
another, a motion to set aside service is usually determined as
a matter of law and not as a matter of discretion. That is to
say, the Court will determine whether service has been effected
in accordance with the rules which allow the forum to assume jurisdiction
over the defendant. Most such motions tend to fail because most
forums have liberal rules which allow for fairly broad assumption
of jurisdiction.<BR>
<P>
A motion to stay an action of the basis of <I>forum non conveniens
</I>or similar principles is, by way of contrast, one in which
the defendant may be prepared to acknowledge that the forum has
the legal ability to assume jurisdiction under its own rules but
invites the forum to exercise its discretion and decline to accept
jurisdiction because it is not the appropriate or natural forum
for the action.<BR>
<P>
An anti-suit injunction is a proceeding by an applicant in the
forum of his choice to enjoin a respondent from prosecuting an
action against him in a foreign jurisdiction. <BR>
<P>
Negative declarations are proceedings in which a party who is
a defendant in a foreign jurisdiction requests a Court in the
forum of his choice to declare that he has no liability arising
out of a certain set of circumstances.<BR>
<P>
Forum shopping exists for four principal reasons.<BR>
<P>
First and most obviously, different jurisdictions offer different
legal rules. In certain cases, the laws or procedures of one jurisdiction
offer one party a distinct advantage over another jurisdiction.
The following advantages have all been held to be legitimate reasons
for choosing one forum over another: cheaper and quicker trials,
provision of security for a claim, better pre-trial discovery,
higher damage awards, better interest awards, more favourable
limitation periods, remedies not available in another jurisdiction,
a lighter burden of proof, the availability of summary judgment
and more favourable substantive law provisions.<SUP><A HREF="#5">5</A> <BR>
</SUP>
<P>
The United States, for example, has long been a favoured destination
for plaintiff forum shoppers because the combination of class
actions, contingency fees, jury trials and doctrines of strict
liability for tort cases provide significant advantages.<SUP><A HREF="#6">6</A></SUP>
The incentive to seek out a favourable forum is strong even if
it will be applying a less favourable foreign law because of the
almost inescapable tendency to apply foreign law using local sensibilities.<SUP><A HREF="#7">7</A>
<BR>
</SUP>
<P>
Second, most forums have broadly based rules pursuant to which
they are entitled to assume jurisdiction. Where litigation arises
which has connections with a number of forums, each is likely
to have a rule which allows it to assume jurisdiction. For example,
most forums would assume jurisdiction over a defendant who resides
or carries on business within the forum. Most would also assume
jurisdiction with respect to damage sustained within the forum.<SUP><A HREF="#8">8</A></SUP>
Where the plaintiff and defendant reside in different forums,
both forums would be entitled to assume jurisdiction under these
two rules.<BR>
<P>
Third, conflict of law rules encourage forum shopping. It is well
accepted for example, that the substantive law of a tort is that
of the <I>lex loci delicti </I>but the procedural law is that
of the <I>lex fori</I>. A simple enough distinction if procedural
rules are limited to things such as the right to cross-examine.
Courts have, however, characterized as procedural, matters such
as limitation periods or limits on damages. Thus, a plaintiff
whose cause of action has expired in the jurisdiction in which
the tort occurred would be wise to bring the claim in a forum
which has a longer limitation period. In Canada, this practice
is likely to be less frequent in view of the Supreme Court<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
recent decision that limitation periods are to be considered substantive
rather than procedural.<SUP><A HREF="#9">9</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
Limits on damage awards may be found in statutory schemes such
as those which govern no fault automobile insurance regimes<SUP><A HREF="#10">10</A></SUP>
or Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT> Compensation
schemes<SUP><A HREF="#11">11</A></SUP> or may arise from judicial pronouncements.<SUP><A HREF="#12">12</A></SUP>
In either case, the plaintiff has a strong interest in bringing
his claim in a jurisdiction which does not have limits on damages
and which will not apply the limits applicable in the <I>lex loci
delicti</I>. <BR>
<P>
These three factors are exacerbated by a fourth: the rules governing
lawyers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT> professional
conduct. Most jurisdictions have rules of conduct which oblige
lawyers to advance every argument, however distasteful, which
the lawyer thinks will help the client<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
case and to endeavour to obtain for the client the benefit of
every remedy and defence authorized by law.<SUP><A HREF="#13">13</A></SUP> Where
a case has possible contacts with other forums, it may be part
of a lawyer<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s ethical
duty to explore the advantages of litigating in each. While a
solicitor may not expected to know what the laws or advantages
of other jurisdictions are, it may constitute professional negligence
not to address the issue.<SUP><A HREF="#14">14</A></SUP> The willingness of courts
to allow plaintiffs to choose between forums based on their relative
judicial advantages would appear to heighten a lawyer<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
duty to turn his or her mind to the issue.<BR>
<P>
III. EVOLUTION OF FORUM NON CONVENIENS <!--III.  EVOLUTION OF FORUM NON CONVENIENS -->
<BR>
<P>
To help them cope with the problems created by overlapping jurisdictional
rules, most jurisdictions have adopted some variation of the principle
of <I>forum non conveniens</I>. While the principle bears different
labels in different jurisdictions, the general goal is to try
an action in the forum with which it has the most real and substantial
connection. <BR>
<P>
To determine which is the appropriate forum in a given case, courts
have looked to a list of <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>connecting
factors<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT> which have
included the following:<BR>
<P>
- juridical advantages available to the plaintiff
<P>
- juridical disadvantages to the defendant
<P>
- the location of each party<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
residence
<P>
- the location in which each party carries on business
<P>
- the forum in which the cause of action arose
<P>
- the forum in which loss or damage occurred
<P>
- the presence of parallel foreign proceedings<SUP><A HREF="#15">15</A></SUP>
<P>
- the location of key witnesses
<P>
- applicable law and its weight compared to factual questions
to be decided
<P>
- difficulties in proving foreign law<SUP><A HREF="#16">16</A></SUP> 
<P>
- in the case of parallel foreign proceedings, which action is
more comprehensive<SUP><A HREF="#17">17</A></SUP>
<P>
- the location of the defendant<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
assets<SUP><A HREF="#18">18</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
Unfortunately, the development of the <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>real
and substantial connection<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>
test has been unsatisfactory. In most jurisdictions it has turned
into a lengthy checklist of factors which judges weigh and set
off against each other. Lord Templeman admitted as much in <I>Spiliada
Maritime Corporation v. Cansulex Ltd.</I><SUP><A HREF="#19">19</A></SUP> where he
stated that:<BR>
<P>
<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>the factors which the
court is entitled to take into account in considering whether
one forum is more appropriate are legion. The authorities do not,
perhaps cannot, give any clear guidance as to how these factors
are to be weighed in any particular case.<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
In recent years the principle has undergone a series of transformations
all of which were required, it is submitted, because of a reluctance
to acknowledge openly the policy underlying the principle, which
is the enforcement of the reasonable expectations of the parties.
To test this thesis, it will first be necessary to review the
development of the law to determine what it was and what it has
become.
<P>
a) The Vexatious and Oppressive Test <!--a) The Vexatious and Oppressive Test -->
<BR>
<P>
Traditionally, Anglo-Canadian courts would only stay an action
on the basis of <I>forum non conveniens</I><SUP><A HREF="#20">20</A></SUP> if the
continuation of the action was oppressive or vexatious to the
defendant and provided the stay did not work an injustice to the
plaintiff.<SUP><A HREF="#21">21</A></SUP> In determining whether the continuation
of an action was oppressive or vexatious, courts looked to the
connecting factors described above and weighed them against each
other.<BR>
<P>
The vexatious and oppressive test gave substantial weight to any
juridical advantage which the plaintiff enjoyed in the forum of
his choice because it essentially provided that if a stay deprived
the plaintiff of a juridical advantage, the court would not stay
the action even if its continuation was vexatious and oppressive
to the defendant. <BR>
<P>
This test reflected several realities about the world from which
it emerged. First, the concentration on connecting factors reflected
a concern for the <U>convenience</U> of trying an action in a
particular forum. The test in some jurisdictions was, after all,
forum<I> non conveniens</I> This made sense in an era where travel
was difficult and communication slow. Second, it reflected the
notion of personal jurisdiction over a defendant which was especially
important in an era where a judgment obtained in one country was
of little use in another. Third, it reflected a pervading, perhaps
chauvinistic, belief that the system of justice of the forum was
innately superior to that of others.<SUP><A HREF="#22">22</A></SUP> 
<P>
The test became increasingly difficult to meet as time went on
because the words oppressive and vexatious had taken on a much
stronger meaning than they had when the test was first developed.<SUP><A HREF="#23">23</A></SUP>
By the mid seventies the word <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>oppressive<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>
had come to mean morally delinquent while the word <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>vexatious<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>
had come to refer to the irresponsible pursuit of litigation.<SUP><A HREF="#24">24</A></SUP>
In <I>The Atlantic Star</I><SUP><A HREF="#25">25</A></SUP> the House of Lords recognized
that these definitions created too difficult a test and proposed
that the test be modernized by changing the definition of the
words and interpreting them more liberally.<SUP><A HREF="#26">26</A></SUP> The House
of Lords pointed out, however, that a juridical advantage to the
plaintiff remained a solid and often decisive factor in determining
the appropriate forum.<SUP><A HREF="#27">27</A></SUP> <BR>
<P>
b) The <I>MacShannon </I>Test<!--b) The MacShannon Test--> <BR>
<P>
The inadequacy of a more liberal interpretation of the words <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>oppressive
and vexatious<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT> as a
solution to the problem was made clear in <I>MacShannon v. Rockware
Glass Limited</I>.<SUP><A HREF="#28">28</A></SUP> In that case, the plaintiffs were
Scottish workers who had been injured in industrial accidents
in Scotland but who brought actions for damages in England. English
courts could technically assume jurisdiction because the defendant
had a registered office in England. <BR>
<P>
The employer sought to have the English actions stayed on the
basis that Scotland was the more appropriate forum but failed
both at first instance and in the Court of Appeal because it could
not be said that an action against the defendant in England was
oppressive or vexatious. On appeal to the House of Lords, the
court concluded, that the vexatious and oppressive test had caused
confusion<SUP><A HREF="#29">29</A></SUP> and reformulated it. <BR>
<P>
Under the <I>MacShannon</I> test, a defendant who wished to stay
an action had to establish:<BR>
<P>
(a) that there is another forum to which the defendant is amenable
in which justice can be done at substantially less inconvenience
or expense; <U>and<BR>
</U>
<P>
(b) that the stay did not deprive the plaintiff of a legitimate
personal or juridical advantage.<BR>
<P>
Applying this new test to the facts in <I>MacShannon,</I> the
House of Lords noted that all of the witnesses resided in Scotland
and that it would cost between <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">,</FONT>200
and <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">,</FONT>450 more to try
the actions in England<SUP><A HREF="#30">30</A></SUP> as a result of which it concluded
that justice could be done at substantially less inconvenience
or expense in Scotland. The plaintiffs<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>
evidence that England provided them with juridical advantages
in the form of increased damages and better pleadings was simply
not believed.<BR>
<P>
The MacShannon test, however, continued to give great weight to
convenience in its first branch and to juridical advantage in
its second branch. Indeed, courts were directed not to spend time
speculating about what constituted a <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>legitimate<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>
juridical advantage.<SUP><A HREF="#31">31</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
c) The <I>Spiliada </I>Test<!--) The Spiliada Test--><BR>
<P>
The House of Lords had further occasion to refine the concepts
of convenience and juridical advantage in <I>Spiliada Maritime
Corporation v. Cansulex Ltd.</I><SUP><A HREF="#32">32</A></SUP> by which time it
had formally accepted the doctrine of <I>forum non conveniens</I>
into English law.<SUP><A HREF="#33">33</A></SUP> <BR>
<P>
In <I>Spiliada</I>, a Liberian ship had been chartered to carry
a cargo of bulk sulphur from Vancouver to India. The ship owners
alleged that the cargo was wet when loaded and, as a result, caused
severe corrosion to the vessel. The ship owners obtained leave
to serve the shipper <I>ex juris</I> in Canada on the ground that
it was an action to recover damages for breach of a contract which
was governed by English law. The shippers moved to set aside service
or stay the action on the basis that England was not the convenient
forum. <BR>
<P>
The House of Lords took pains to point out that the doctrine of
<I>forum</I> <I>non conveniens</I> was based not on practical
convenience but on the appropriateness of a particular forum.
<SUP><A HREF="#34">34</A></SUP> Their lordship<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
also recognized that the mere presence of a juridical advantage
could not be decisive and that it is not necessarily unjust to
compel a plaintiff to use a different legal system.<SUP><A HREF="#35">35</A></SUP>
Their lordship<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s then
took these considerations into account and reformulated the test
to stay an action based on the principle of <I>forum</I> <I>non
conveniens</I>. Under the <I>Spiliada </I>formulation, a stay
will be granted if:<I> <BR>
</I>
<P>
(a) there is another forum in which the matter could be tried
more suitably for the interests of the parties and the ends of
justice; <BR>
<P>
(b) if such a forum exists and the plaintiff wishes to retain
England as the forum, he must establish special circumstances
by reason of which justice requires that the action proceed in
England.<SUP><A HREF="#36">36</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
In its formulation, at least, the <I>Spiliada</I> test marks a
significant change in the direction of the law. The first branch
of the test changes the focus from convenience and expense to
the interests of the parties and the end of justice. The second
branch, in its formulation at least, decreases the significance
of juridical advantages. Under the <I>MacShannon</I> test, the
plaintiff had the right to enjoy the juridical advantages offered
by the forum of his choice even where there was another forum
which was more appropriate. Under the <I>Spiliada</I> formulation,
a juridical advantage is no longer an absolute right which the
plaintiff may enjoy. Rather, the plaintiff must establish that
ends of justice require that he have the benefit of the juridical
advantage.<SUP><A HREF="#37">37</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
d) The <I>Amchem </I>Test<!--d) The Amchem Test--><BR>
<P>
Until recently, Canadian courts followed the two&#173;step tests
established in <I>MacShannon</I> and <I>Spiliada</I>.<SUP><A HREF="#38">38</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
In 1993 the Supreme Court of Canada reformulated these tests significantly
in <I>Amchem Products Inc. v. British Columbia (Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>
Compensation Board)</I>.<SUP><A HREF="#39">39</A></SUP> In reformulating the test,
the Supreme Court collapsed the two branches into one and held
that a stay should only be granted if the applicant could establish
that there was another forum which was clearly more appropriate
than Canada for the pursuit of the action and for securing the
ends of justice.<SUP><A HREF="#40">40</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
Although the court noted that it is up to the applicant to establish
<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>clearly<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>
that a more appropriate forum exists in order to displace the
plaintiff<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s choice,
it added that the burden of proof should not play a significant
role in the decision but should be relied on only when the materials
do not enable a judge to make a determinative finding.<SUP><A HREF="#41">41</A></SUP>
<BR>
<P>
This reformulation does away with loss of juridical advantage
as a separate branch of the test thereby making stays significantly
easier to obtain. Under the <I>Amchem</I> test, a juridical advantage
is simply one of a lengthy list of factors to be taken into account
when determining whether there is another forum which is more
appropriate. While juridical advantages may continue to be an
important factor, they are not to rule the day.<BR>
<P>
More importantly, when referring to the weight to be ascribed
to a juridical advantage, the court held that the legitimacy of
any advantage depended upon the reasonableness of the expectation
that such an advantage would be available to the party if litigation
resulted.<SUP><A HREF="#42">42</A></SUP> This appears to be the first express recognition
of reasonable expectations as a basis for assessing the validity
of a claim to a juridical advantage. Unfortunately the court did
not go on to assess the legitimacy of the juridical advantages
claimed in <I>Amchem</I> because it decided the case based on
a new test for anti-suit injunctions which it developed.<SUP><A HREF="#43">43</A></SUP>
Indeed, as argued later in this paper, the actual result, seems
to ignore the reasonable expectations of the parties. <BR>
<P>
The express reference to reasonable expectations is nevertheless
a welcome step towards the development of a principled approach
to forum shopping cases. Reasonable expectations should arguably
play a decisive role not only in determining whether a party is
entitled to a particular juridical advantage but also in determining
which is the appropriate forum on the whole. We will test this
by: <BR>
<P>
(a) examining the origins of reasonable expectations analysis;
<BR>
<P>
(b) assessing whether the results of past cases are consistent
with reasonable expectations analysis;<BR>
<P>
(c) examining why reasonable expectations should be used as a
guide in forum shopping cases;<BR>
<P>
(d) examining the application of reasonable expectations in some
particularly difficult fact scenarios.<BR>
<P>
IV. REASONABLE EXPECTATIONS ANALYSIS<!--IV.  REASONABLE EXPECTATIONS ANALYSIS-->
<BR>
<P>
a) The Origins of Reasonable Expectations Analysis<!--) The Origins of Reasonable Expectations Analysis-->
<BR>
<P>
The express reference to reasonable expectations in <I>Amchem</I>
marks a recognition of what, it is submitted, courts have been
endeavouring to accomplish for some time. Although the focus on
vexation, oppression, convenience or the plaintiff<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
right to a juridical advantage may have been appropriate for a
world in which there were fewer well developed legal systems,
in which travelling to another forum for a trial was truly burdensome
and in which foreign judgments were not enforced as easily as
they are today, those concerns are no longer relevant in an era
of globalization of business, instant communication, ease of travel,
video technology and mutual enforcement of judgments.<BR>
<P>
The case law has struggled to take these changing realities into
account but, has been burdened by the need to apply formulations
which no longer respond to contemporary concerns. While courts
state openly that the selection of a forum or the assumption of
jurisdiction should be based on a sense of order and fairness
rather than on the counting up of mechanical factors<SUP><A HREF="#44">44</A></SUP>
courts still continue to use the factors as a checklist and weigh
them rather mechanically. <BR>
<P>
In Canada, reasonable expectations analysis in conflicts of law
appears to originate from choice of law cases involving different
provinces. In <I>Moran</I> v. <I>Pyle National (Canada) Limited</I>,<SUP><A HREF="#45">45</A></SUP>
for example, an electrician was fatally injured in Saskatchewan
by a light bulb which had allegedly been negligently manufactured
in Ontario. The issue before the Supreme Court of Canada was whether
the action should be tried in Saskatchewan as desired by the deceased's
estate and widow or in Ontario as desired by the manufacturer.
The legal issue was whether the tort occurred in the place of
manufacture or the place of injury. The court avoided setting
a hard and fast rule to this issue <SUP><A HREF="#46">46</A></SUP> but concluded
that, where a foreign defendant carelessly manufactures a product
in a foreign jurisdiction which enters into normal channels of
trade and it is foreseeable that a plaintiff would use the product
in the jurisdiction in which he does, then the forum in which
the plaintiff uses the product may appropriately exercise jurisdiction.
<BR>
<P>
Although the court was, strictly speaking, addressing the issue
of jurisdiction rather than that of an appropriate forum, it was,
for all intents and purposes, determining the most appropriate
jurisdiction in which the action could be tried and was engaging
in reasonable expectations analysis when coming to a conclusion
based on foreseeability. A plaintiff who purchases a product and
uses it in his home forum expects the law and the courts of his
home forum to govern. To hold otherwise would suggest that there
are different laws and forums which govern the purchase of products
depending on where they were manufactured. Similarly, a defendant
has reason to expect that if he enters a foreign jurisdiction
either personally or through his products, he must comply with
the laws and submit to the courts of that jurisdiction. Subsequent
Canadian decisions have expressly referred to reasonable expectations
when deciding which choice of law should govern a particular transaction.<SUP><A HREF="#47">47</A>
<BR>
</SUP>
<P>
b) Are Past Cases Consistent with Reasonable Expectations Analysis?<!--b) Are Past Cases Consistent with Reasonable Expectations Analysis?-->
<BR>
<P>
Reasonable expectation analysis was not openly applied to <I>forum
non conveniens</I> cases because precedent required that they
be determined with reference to the list of connecting factors.
The list of connecting factors forced the courts to adopt rather
unusual logic so that their decisions would conform to these rather
formalistic rules when open acknowledgement of reasonable expectations
would have been logically simpler and more consistent with the
results of the cases.<BR>
<P>
This is perhaps best demonstrated by the <I>MacShannon</I> case
where, Scottish workers who had been injured in industrial accidents
in Scotland attempted to bring an action against their employer
in England. Lord Justice Stevenson in the Court of Appeal readily
admitted that <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>Anyone
with nothing but common sense to guide him would say that they
ought to be tried in Scotland.<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT><SUP><A HREF="#48">48</A></SUP>
The Court of Appeal had only legal rules to guide it and felt
bound to order that the actions be tried in England because, under
the prevailing test at the time, it could not be said that an
action in England was vexatious or oppressive to the employer,
who also had a registered office in England. 
<P>
The House of Lords assisted by reformulating the test to be whether
justice could be done elsewhere at substantially less inconvenience
or expense. Their Lordships then determined the matter by noting
that trying the matters in England would result in hotel expenses
for witnesses of between <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">,</FONT>200
and <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">,</FONT>450 per action
and concluded that justice could be done less expensively in Scotland.<SUP><A HREF="#49">49</A></SUP>
<BR>
<P>
While the result is sensible, it seems odd that Scottish workers
injured at a Scottish workplace in Scotland are prevented from
suing in England solely because of the cost of a hotel room. Surely
there are more compelling reasons why the actions should be tried
in Scotland. The fundamental expectation of every worker who is
injured in an industrial accident is that their rights will be
determined in the jurisdiction in which they work according to
the laws of that jurisdiction. Given this fundamental starting
point it seems curious to base the legal requirement that they
bring an action in their home forum on the cost of hotels in a
foreign jurisdiction.<BR>
<P>
In <I>Spiliada Maritime Corporation</I> v. <I>Cansulex Ltd</I><SUP><A HREF="#50">50</A></SUP>,
the House of Lords also implicitly applied reasonable expectations
analysis. As noted above, the court stated that a juridical advantage
was not decisive and recognized that it was not necessarily unjust
to compel a plaintiff to use a different legal system.<SUP><A HREF="#51"></A>51</SUP>
In assessing the type of juridical advantage to which a plaintiff
was entitled, the court examined a hypothetical scenario involving
a plaintiff's right to benefit from limitation periods in different
jurisdictions. The court first considered the example of a plaintiff
who started an action in England which was later challenged by
the defendant as <I>forum non conveniens</I> after the limitation
period in the jurisdiction espoused by the defendant had expired.
If the foreign jurisdiction were the better forum but it had been
reasonable for the plaintiff to commence the action in England,
it would be fair to stay the English action on the condition that
the defendant waived its right to a time bar defence.<SUP><A HREF="#52">52</A></SUP>
This result reflects the reasonable expectation that the action
would be tried in the foreign forum but also recognizes that parties
may reasonably have different views of these expectations and
ought not to suffer because of those views, provided they are
reasonable. If, however, the plaintiff was irresponsible in commencing
the action in England and did so after deliberately letting a
limitation period expire elsewhere in order to benefit from a
juridical advantage in England, the court may take a harsher view
of the matter and stay the action without conditions.<SUP><A HREF="#53">53</A></SUP>
This also reflects the reasonable expectations of the parties
and enforces those expectations by visiting consequences on those
who ignore or circumvent them.<BR>
<P>
In the end result, the court explained its decision in <I>Spiliada</I>
on a more traditional basis by considering a checklist of factors
including the fact that the contract between the plaintiff and
the defendant was governed by English law. This would arguably
create an expectation that Britain would be the convenient forum.
The court, however, did not focus on the choice of law clause
in the contract as the determining factor but on the fact that
a very similar case was proceeding through the British courts
at that time.<SUP><A HREF="#54">54</A></SUP> Since the case involved extensive and
highly technical expert evidence concerning the corrosive effect
of sulphur on a ship's hold, the House of Lords determined that
the expertise developed by the lawyers and judge on that case
tipped the balance in favour of British Courts. <SUP><A HREF="#55">55</A></SUP>
While the result is eminently sensible, the deciding factor of
a similar case is perhaps curious in light of the court's earlier
statement that the issue should not be determined as a matter
of practical convenience but as a question of the appropriateness
or the suitability of a forum to secure the ends of justice.<SUP><A HREF="#56">56</A></SUP>
<BR>
<P>
Arguably a decision by the parties that English law governs should
make England the forum which most closely reflects the parties'
reasonable expectations. Even though the contract did not specifically
provide that the courts of England were to govern, the typical
business person would probably expect that, absent other considerations,
a contract which was to be determined in accordance with English
law would also best be determined by English courts. <BR>
<P>
Ironically, it is in <I>Amchem</I>,<SUP><A HREF="#57">57</A></SUP> the case in which
the Supreme Court of Canada explicitly recognized the importance
of reasonable expectations in assessing a juridical advantage,
that the reasonable expectations of the parties were, in fact,
defeated. In that case, the Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>
Compensation Board of British Columbia brought a large number
of subrogated actions for damages on behalf of workers to whom
it had paid benefits. The actions were brought against a number
of asbestos manufacturers and suppliers. Although the workers
had all been injured in British Columbia, the Board brought the
actions in Texas. Texas had a legal basis for assuming jurisdiction
because each of the defendants carried on business there. The
defendant sought to have the Texas action stayed but failed, in
large part because Texas did not apply the doctrine of <I>forum
non conveniens</I>.<SUP><A HREF="#58">58</A><BR>
</SUP>
<P>
Although the Supreme Court of Canada developed a new test for
stays in Canada, it was not required to apply that test because
the case came to it as an anti-suit injunction to enjoin the Texas
proceedings. While this aspect of the case and the implications
of reasonable expectations analysis in anti-suit injunctions is
discussed elsewhere in this paper,<SUP><A HREF="#59">59</A></SUP> the Court rejected
the request for an injunction and allowed the Texas actions to
continue. It is difficult to believe, however, that employees
working in British Columbia who are injured as a result of workplace
injuries in British Columbia have any expectation of arguing their
claims in Texas.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
c) Why should Reasonable Expectations Be Used as a Guide? <!--c) Why should Reasonable Expectations Be Used as a Guide? -->
<BR>
<P>
Like any other legal test, using reasonable expectations as a
guide to resolving forum shopping cases serves little purpose
if it is simply based on an assumption by a court about what the
expectations of the parties are without further inquiry into what
this means and what social values the court is seeking to protect
by enforcing them.<SUP><A HREF="#60">60</A></SUP> <BR>
<P>
The reasonable expectations of the parties provide a desirable
basis for deciding forum shopping cases because it focuses the
inquiry on the legitimacy of a party<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
claim to a certain juridical or personal advantage. In most cases,
the advantage will be juridical and will relate either to the
substantive or procedural law of the desired forum. Reasonable
expectations analysis recognizes that the legal system and the
juridical advantages of any one forum are a product of a complete
social contract. Damage awards or other juridical advantages cannot
be looked at in isolation. They are part of a larger series of
trade-offs. <BR>
<P>
In <I>Amchem</I> for example, the Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>
Compensation Board was seeking not only to recover amounts which
it had paid out in benefits to the disabled employees but it was
also seeking general damages on the scale awarded by Texas courts.
The Board then intended to pay these additional damages to the
employees in question. In doing so the Board was trying to avoid
the generally lower damages awards that are made in Canada and
in particular, it would have been trying to circumvent the limits
on non-pecuniary damages established by the Supreme Court of Canada.<SUP><A HREF="#61">61</A></SUP>
On a reasonable expectations analysis this is an entirely inappropriate
goal. Forums with lower damage awards may offer other compensating
social advantages instead. There are, for example, significant
social policy differences between Canada and the United States
which may make lower damage awards more appropriate in Canada.
Canada offers significantly more generous social programs than
Texas does. Canada has universal, state funded medical care out
of which one cannot contract. In addition, Canada has a funded
Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT> Compensation
system pursuant to which Canadian workers have given up their
rights to tort damages in exchange for guaranteed compensation
by a Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT> Compensation
Board. In <I>Amchem</I> it appears that at least one of the asbestos
companies (Atlas) was a registered employer under the British
Columbia Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT> Compensation
scheme and may have been entitled to immunity from action in British
Columbia. These are all elements of a social contract of which
the plaintiffs in <I>Amchem</I> had enjoyed the benefits for many
years. As citizens of a democratic country they participated in
its formation. To reap the benefits of that social contract while
refusing to bear the burden, ultimately subverts the policy choices
made by Canadian courts and legislatures.<BR>
<P>
The Supreme Court of Canada ultimately did not grant the anti-suit
injunction in <I>Amchem</I> because it was concerned that doing
so would interfere with the principles of comity. While comity
is a principle to be considered in anti-suit injunctions, it should
arguably also be considered when considering motions to stay.
By allowing the action to proceed in Texas, the Texas court unwittingly
participated in undermining the Canadian social contract, albeit
in a relatively inconsequential manner. Had the Texas court enforced
the reasonable expectations of the parties and stayed the Texas
proceedings in favour of British Columbia proceedings, it would
have demonstrated a respect for comity and a respect for the social
policy choices made by another country as reflected in its legal
system.<BR>
<P>
Quite apart from policy choices, lower damage awards in some forums
also reflect lower costs of living and differing living standards.
Without wishing to be mean spirited, a plaintiff is meant to be
compensated for his damages. He is not entitled to a windfall.
By awarding American style personal injury claims to plaintiffs
in countries with lower costs of living, plaintiffs are obtaining
a significant windfall to the detriment of defendants or their
insurers who had a reasonable expectation that lower damage awards
would apply and who factored those lower awards into the cost
of doing business. <BR>
<P>
Enforcing the reasonable expectations of the parties also avoids
inequitable outcomes between plaintiffs. Take <I>Amchem </I>as
an example. Assume there are two British Columbia plaintiffs who
have been injured in an identical manner in British Columbia.
One has been injured as a result of the act of a defendant who
also happens to carry on business in the United States. The other
has been injured as a result of a defendant who does not carry
on business in the United States. Although both plaintiffs have
suffered identical damages and will incur identical costs in Canada,
the former enjoys a substantial windfall because he had the good
fortune to be injured by someone who quite coincidentally does
business in the United States. The latter will receive a significantly
lower damage award. There does not appear to be any rational basis
for treating the two individuals differently. The incorporation
of reasonable expectations analysis by courts hearing any motions
for stay would ensure that the two are treated in a similar fashion.
<BR>
<P>
Similar arguments can be made with respect to cases which grant
stays on the condition that the one party be permitted to enjoy
a particular juridical advantage. If one country has, for example,
adopted a narrower form of discovery, it has presumably done so
for good reason. The procedural rules of any system contain a
number of trade-offs. While one forum may have more restricted
rules of discovery, it may compensate for that limitation by other
procedural or substantive rights which are not available in another
forum. To impose one forum<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
discovery rules ( or other juridical advantage) on another constitutes
cherry picking which interferes with the judicial balance and
policy choices made by the courts and legislatures of the other
forum.<BR>
<P>
In most cases it is relatively easy to determine objectively what
the reasonable expectations of the parties were. In cases where
objective circumstances do not lead to one conclusion or another,
it may be appropriate for the parties to introduce evidence concerning
their expectations and the basis for them. In addition to explaining
why objective factors led one party to have a certain expectation,
such evidence might also introduce facts about whether one party
led another to believe in a certain result either expressly or
implicitly by silence in the face of the other<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
communication of a particular expectation. Such evidence does,
however, carry the danger of self serving re-characterizations
long after the fact as a result of which it is probably more desirable
to base decisions on an objective consideration of those expectations.
<BR>
<P>
d) Reasonable Expectations in More Difficult Cases<!--d) Reasonable Expectations in More Difficult Cases-->
<BR>
<P>
The cases examined so far have been relatively easy to assess
in terms of reasonable expectations. Some fact situations pose
greater difficulty. Perhaps the most difficult situation to deal
with using reasonable expectations analysis is one where the defendant
has no assets in the <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>natural
forum<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT> and where a judgment
from the natural forum would not be readily enforced in the forum(s)
in which the defendant has assets. In this type of case, it would
clearly be inequitable to prevent the plaintiff from proceeding
in the forum in which the defendant has assets.<BR>
<P>
A second category of difficult cases involves ships. It has been
said that every port is a forum shoppers emporium.<SUP><A HREF="#62">62</A></SUP>
Even here, however, reasonable expectations analysis is helpful.
Two examples may assist in demonstrating this: <I>Antares Shipping
Corporation v. The Capricorn</I><SUP><A HREF="#63">63</A></SUP> and <I>Castanho
v. Brown &amp; Root (U.K.)Ltd.<SUP><A HREF="#64">64</A></SUP> <BR>
</I>
<P>
In part, <I>Antares</I> raises the problem of the judgment proof
defendant described in the previous paragraph. In <I>Antares</I>,
the plaintiff was a Liberian corporation which claimed to have
purchased the vessel Capricorn from Delmar, another Liberian corporation
under an agreement of purchase and sale governed by English law.
While the ship was en route to Canada, Delmar purported to sell
it to another Liberian corporation named Portland pursuant to
an agreement of purchase and sale governed by American law and
through registration of a bill of sale in the United States. Antares
had the ship arrested in Quebec City, its first port of call after
the transfer to Portland.<BR>
<P>
The Supreme Court of Canada conceded that England, the United
States and Liberia were all jurisdictions with connections to
the facts but concluded that no one of those jurisdictions was
more convenient than Canada. It then assessed a checklist of factors
including the fact that Delmar's and Portland's only assets were
in Canada in the form of bail for the ship which had been released.
<BR>
<P>
The decision is arguably consistent with the reasonable expectations
of the parties. The court expressly recognized the significance
of <I>in rem</I> jurisdiction in admiralty matters<SUP><A HREF="#65">65</A></SUP>
and recognized that the only effective jurisdiction in those cases
is often the location of the ship especially if it is owned by
a shell corporation.<SUP><A HREF="#66">66</A></SUP> Ship owners are presumably aware
of <I>in rem</I> jurisdiction and are aware that part of its significance
stems from the manner in which they have arranged their affairs
to limit liability. Given the internationally recognized authority
to arrest ships in appropriate circumstances, a ship owner cannot
complain if a ship is arrested in another jurisdiction as a result
of a complaint against the owner.<BR>
<P>
A more difficult scenario would arise had the plaintiff sought
to arrest the ship not in its first port of call after the fraudulent
transfer, but in some later port of call in order to reap the
benefit of a juridical advantage offered by the later port. In
such cases it might be appropriate to require the plaintiff to
show good reason for not having moved more quickly and to have
the plaintiff establish its own expectations for believing that
the later port was the appropriate forum.<BR>
<P>
In<I> Castanho,</I> a Portuguese sailor was paralysed from the
neck down as a result of injuries he received on board a ship
while that ship was in an English port. After his injury, Mr.
Castanho returned to Portugal but started an action for damages
in England. One and a half years after starting the English action,
and after having received payments after an admission of liability
by the ship owners, Mr. Castanho started proceedings in a Texas
court on the basis that the ship was ultimately owned by Texas
defendants. <BR>
<P>
The case came to the House of Lords as an anti-suit injunction
to enjoin Mr. Castanho from prosecuting the Texas action (the
injunctive aspect of the case will be discussed later in this
paper). The House of Lords concluded that England was a forum
in which justice could be achieved at a lower cost but found that
the English action would deprive Mr. Castanho of the juridical
advantage of higher damage awards in Texas and permitted Mr. Castanho
to proceed with the Texas action.<BR>
<P>
The <I>Castanho</I> type case is one in which it is arguably more
difficult to apply reasonable expectations analysis. Since the
place of the tort is England, there is a <I>prima facie</I> reasonable
expectation that English law would apply as the <I>lex loci delicti</I>
and that it would also be the appropriate forum. <BR>
<P>
On the facts of <I>Castanho</I>, it is difficult to discern any
basis, arising from the reasonable expectations of the parties,
for a forum other than England. Indeed, as already noted, Mr.
Castanho had commenced an action there and had accepted partial
damage payments after an admission of liability by the defendant.
Nevertheless, he was permitted to proceed in Texas. On a reasonable
expectations analysis, the better result may have been to require
him to complete the English proceedings.<BR>
<P>
There are, however, competing concerns raised by these types of
cases. As a ship's employee, the plaintiff may be subject to the
tort regimes of a number of different jurisdictions. If the tort
occurs in a country with a poor tort compensation regime, should
he have to bear that risk? There is no easy answer.<BR>
<P>
On the one hand, Mr. Castanho is not unlike a tourist who visits
a country with a more rigorous tort regime. If he is injured there,
he must bear the risk of the harsher regime.
<P>
If a tourist or ship<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
employee is concerned about a tort occurring in a jurisdiction
with a harsher tort regime, this is presumably a risk against
which he can insure. Some will no doubt argue that the plaintiffs
in situations like <I>Castanho</I> tend to be relatively unsophisticated,
in many cases from developing countries in which insurance may
not be as prevalent a concept as elsewhere and that it is unrealistic
to impose an obligation to insure on such plaintiffs. In those
circumstances, it is much easier for the ship<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
owners to insure against the risk that an action will be brought
in a forum with a more generous tort compensation regime. If,
on the other hand, the concern is with less sophisticated plaintiffs
from less wealthy countries, such plaintiffs are likely to return
to their country of origin (as did Mr. Castanho), in which case
it would not appear to be that unjust to compensate them according
to the regime which exists in the place of the tort. That lower
compensation scheme may more closely reflect the cost of living
and standard of living which they would expect in their home country.
In such circumstances does the plaintiff really have a legitimate
claim to tort compensation based on an American standard of living
and an American cost of living? 
<P>
This type of case creates difficult questions which it may not
be possible to answer in a general way. As a starting point, however,
the place of the tort would still arguably be the most appropriate
forum which corresponds to the reasonable expectations of the
parties. As with any legal test, however, there may be practical
exigencies which may lead a court to depart from the rigour of
the rule. Even in such cases, however, courts should be loath
to depart from the goal of enforcing reasonable expectations.
It may simply be that the analysis of those expectations becomes
more complex.<BR>
<P>
Up to this point, we have examined reasonable expectations principally
in the context of motions to stay proceedings. Their use as an
analytical tool also arises when considering anti-suit injunctions
and negative declarations, both of which might add the complicating
factor of judicial comity into the mix. <BR>
<P>
V. ANTI-SUIT INJUNCTIONS<BR>
<!--V.  ANTI-SUIT INJUNCTIONS-->
<P>
a) Background<!--a) Background--><BR>
<P>
An anti-suit injunction is a proceeding by an applicant to enjoin
a respondent from prosecuting an action against the applicant
in a foreign jurisdiction. <BR>
<P>
Like the test for stays, the test for granting anti-suit injunctions
has evolved significantly in recent years. Despite this evolution,
Anglo Canadian case law remains difficult to work with because
it does not openly address the policies or purposes which courts
seek to advance when considering anti-suit injunctions. The express
recognition of reasonable expectations in anti-suit injunctions
would, it is submitted, simplify the law and reduce the risk of
conflicting judicial outcomes. <BR>
<P>
The contemporary starting point of Anglo Canadian law on anti-suit
injunctions is <I>Castanho v. Brown &amp; Root (U.K.) Ltd.</I><SUP><A HREF="#67">67</A></SUP>
where the House of Lords held that the test for granting an anti-suit
injunction was the same as that for granting a motion to stay
an action for <I>forum non conveniens. </I>When transposing the
test for stays at that time to anti-suit injunctions, the result
was that, in order to obtain an anti-suit injunction the applicant
had to establish:<BR>
<P>
i) that justice could be done at less inconvenience and expense
in the United Kingdom; and<BR>
<P>
ii) that granting the injunction would not deprive the plaintiff
of a juridical advantage in the foreign jurisdiction .<BR>
<P>
b) The Test in Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale<!--b) The Test in Soci--><FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J<!--t-->J<!-- Aerospatiale--></FONT>
<BR>
<P>
After <I>Castanho</I> was decided, the test for stays was changed
by <I>Spiliada.<SUP><A HREF="#68">68</A></SUP></I> By implication this also changed
the test for injunctions . Anti-suit injunctions next came before
the House of Lords (sitting as the Privy Council) in <I>Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Nationale Industrielle Aerospatiale</I> v. <I>Lee Kui Jak.</I><SUP><A HREF="#69">69</A></SUP>
Their Lordships felt that if the <I>Spiliada</I> test were applied
to anti-suit injunctions, an injunction would be granted if England
were the natural forum and justice did not require that the action
be allowed to continue in the foreign court.<SUP><A HREF="#70">70</A></SUP> Their
Lordships felt that this test meant that injunctions would almost
always be granted if the court concluded that England was the
natural forum because it would be unusual that justice required
that the action be allowed to proceed in a foreign court.<SUP><A HREF="#71">71</A></SUP>
This, it was felt, would be inconsistent both with comity and
the fundamental requirement that an injunction be granted only
where the ends of justice require.<SUP><A HREF="#72">72</A></SUP> As a result, the
Privy Council formulated a new test for anti-suit injunctions
and stated that they would be granted only if<BR>
<P>
i) England were a natural forum ; and<BR>
<P>
ii) the pursuit of the foreign action would be vexatious or oppressive
to the defendant in the foreign action.<BR>
<P>
A close reading of the <I>Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale</I> decision arguably reveals that the Privy Council
was more concerned with enforcing the reasonable expectations
of the parties (without actually saying so) than it was with applying
its newly formulated test. <BR>
<P>
The action arose out of a helicopter accident in Brunei in which
a wealthy citizen of Brunei was killed. The helicopter was manufactured
by a French company, Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale, was owned by an English company and maintained by
a Malaysian company. An accident report prepared by Brunei authorities
concluded that the accident was probably caused by faulty maintenance.
There was an argument that the faulty maintenance may have resulted
from poorly written instructions in the maintenance manual but
this, at least on the facts described by the Privy Council<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
decision, seemed difficult to support.<SUP><A HREF="#73">73</A></SUP> The deceased<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
widow, Lee Kui Jak, commenced proceedings in Brunei and in Texas.
Texas law permitted jurisdiction because <I>Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale</I> conducted business in Texas, albeit only by selling
products to a subsidiary.<SUP><A HREF="#74">74</A></SUP> The plaintiff wished to
proceed in Texas because of its more favourable product liability
laws and more favourable damage awards.<SUP><A HREF="#75">75</A></SUP> The Texas
court rejected Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale's motion to stay the Texas action and, in keeping
with the practice of that court, gave no reasons for its decision.<SUP><A HREF="#76">76</A>
<BR>
</SUP>
<P>
Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale then brought an anti-suit injunction in Brunei to
restrain the plaintiff from prosecuting the Texas lawsuit. The
Privy Council noted the complicating factor of comity when dealing
with anti-suit injunctions but also noted that an anti-suit injunction
is not directed against a foreign court, but against an individual
who is under the jurisdiction of the enjoining court.<SUP><A HREF="#77">77</A></SUP>
This presumably lessens the importance of comity significantly.
<BR>
<P>
The court found that Brunei was the natural forum because the
action arose out of the death in Brunei, of a citizen of Brunei
and that Brunei law applied. The court noted in particular that
Brunei law applied a principle known as damages for lost years
which the court described as a difficult concept even for experienced
judges.<SUP><A HREF="#78">78</A></SUP> It is noteworthy that the court seems to
be suggesting that it is preferable to have the law of the action
decided by the forum which normally applies that law. This is
an encouraging presumption to further. As noted earlier, the application
of foreign law is sometimes a bit of a fiction because courts
tend to apply foreign law in light of their own preconceptions
and values. It stands to reason that if a court ordinarily applies
strict liability principles it would not be as adept at applying
fault principles as would a court which applies fault principles
regularly. A further reason for preferring that the action be
tried by the court whose law governs, is that foreign law is usually
proved as a matter of fact. As a result, no appeal ordinarily
lies on the interpretation of foreign law. This effectively deprives
both parties of a juridical advantage which they reasonably expect
to enjoy.<BR>
<P>
With respect to the natural forum, the court also noted that the
plaintiff resided in Brunei as did the deceased, that the deceased
had a substantial income which depended on the rather volatile
oil industry and which would require expert evidence to prove.
Against this there was nothing to connect the action with Texas.<SUP><A HREF="#79">79</A></SUP>
Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale therefore succeeded on the first branch of the test.
<BR>
<P>
The second branch, establishing that the Texas proceeding was
vexatious and oppressive was more difficult. Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale argued that it sought contribution from the company
which maintained the helicopters. Under the relevant contributory
negligence legislation it was uncertain whether it could claim
indemnity from the maintenance company based on a Texas judgment.
Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale may have been required to bring a fresh action against
the maintenance company in Brunei and establish liability afresh.
The Privy Council found this to be vexatious and oppressive to
Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale even though the claim for contribution and indemnity
was made only after Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale had applied for the injunction in Brunei and failed.<SUP><A HREF="#80">80</A>
<BR>
</SUP>
<P>
Although the court referred to the difficulty of commencing an
action against the helicopter maintenance company, Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale might have been able to join them as a necessary
party to the Texas litigation.<SUP><A HREF="#81">81</A></SUP> Thus, even though
Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale might have had to commence a fresh action against
the maintenance company in Brunei to enforce the Texas judgment,
the liability issues would arguably be <I>res</I> <I>judicata</I>.
<BR>
<P>
It is also worth recalling that the House of Lords had stated
in <I>The Atlantic Star</I><SUP><A HREF="#82">82</A></SUP> that oppressive meant
morally delinquent and that vexatious referred to the irresponsible
pursuit of litigation. It is doubtful that the Texas action was
either morally delinquent or irresponsible. It is unclear from
the Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale case whether oppressive and vexatious meant morally
delinquent and irresponsible or whether the Privy Council meant
to refer to the more liberal interpretation advocated by the House
of Lords in <I>The Atlantic Star</I>.<SUP><A HREF="#83">83</A></SUP> It is submitted
that the Privy Council sensibly did not consider these issues
because they were in fact endeavouring to enforce the reasonable
expectations of the parties. The simple fact that Texas is prepared
to extend jurisdiction over Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>
Aerospatiale because it happens to sell helicopters to a subsidiary
in Texas does not give the plaintiff any reasonable expectation
that the damages she sustained as a result of the death in Brunei,
of a citizen of Brunei would be litigated in Texas. Most peoples<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>
reasonable expectation would be that Brunei is the natural forum.
Perhaps Malaysia (if the maintenance was carried out there); perhaps
France (if the instructions were flawed) but not Texas. <BR>
<P>
c) The Test in <I>Amchem<!--) The Test in Amchem--> <BR>
</I>
<P>
In <I>Amchem,<SUP><A HREF="#84">84</A></SUP></I> the Supreme Court of Canada had
occasion to review the Canadian test for anti-suit injunctions.
<BR>
<P>
Although, as noted above, <I>Amchem</I> explicitly recognized
reasonable expectations as a basis for determining whether a plaintiff
was entitled to claim the benefit of a juridical advantage, the
result of the case seems to defeat those expectations. <BR>
<P>
In<I> Amchem,</I> it will be recalled, the Workers<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>
Compensation Board of British Columbia brought a subrogated claim
in Texas against manufacturers and distributors of asbestos. The
claim was to recover payments which the Board had made to British
Columbian employees for asbestos related disabilities which arose
from employment in British Columbia. In addition, the Board claimed
general damages on behalf of the employees on a damage scale as
normally awarded by Texas courts.<BR>
<P>
The defendants sought to have the Texas action stayed but failed
in large part because Texas does not apply the doctrine of <I>forum
non conveniens</I>.<SUP><A HREF="#85">85</A></SUP> The defendants then sought an
anti-suit injunction in Canada to restrain the Board from proceeding
in Texas. The defendants succeeded at first instance and in the
British Columbia Court of Appeal but failed in the Supreme Court
of Canada.<BR>
<P>
The starting point of the analysis for the Supreme Court of Canada
was comity.<SUP><A HREF="#86">86</A></SUP> The court stated that an anti-suit injunction
should not even be entertained unless a suit has been commenced
in a foreign jurisdiction, the defendant has applied for a stay
in the foreign court and failed.<SUP><A HREF="#87">87</A></SUP> <BR>
<P>
Having failed to obtain a stay in the foreign jurisdiction, the
defendant may then apply to a Canadian court for an anti-suit
injunction. In considering the issue, a Canadian court should
grant the injunction only if: <BR>
<P>
i) the foreign court assumed jurisdiction on a basis which is
inconsistent with the Canadian principles of f<I>orum non conveniens;</I>
and<BR>
<P>
ii) an injustice would result if the foreign proceedings were
permitted to continue.<BR>
<P>
On a straight forward application, the two branch test in <I>Amchem</I>
makes anti-suit injunctions extremely difficult to obtain in Canada.
<BR>
<P>
As a condition precedent, the Court will not even entertain the
application unless there is a suit pending in a foreign jurisdiction
and that foreign jurisdiction has refused to stay the action.
This is presumably because a Canadian court should not interfere
with a foreign court<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
decision to accept or decline jurisdiction. It may be questioned
whether this is truly a requirement of comity. Would it offend
comity if a Canadian court directed a Canadian resident not to
commence an action in a foreign country? At that point, the Canadian
court arguably has complete jurisdiction over the Canadian resident.
While the situation may be different if the injunction seeks to
restrain a foreign resident from bringing an action in his place
of residence, it is difficult to understand why a Canadian court
should refuse to entertain an anti-suit injunction aimed at Canadian
resident simply because no foreign court has yet had an opportunity
to assume jurisdiction. At that point, a Canadian court arguably
has a greater claim to jurisdiction over its nationals than does
a foreign court.<BR>
<P>
The two branch test also accords at least as much deference to
foreign courts as does the condition precedent. On the first branch,
a Canadian court will grant an injunction only if the foreign
court assumed jurisdiction on a basis which is inconsistent with
Canadian principles of <I>forum</I> <I>non conveniens</I>. This
is noteworthy in two respects. First, the foreign court need not
have come to the correct decision about the appropriate forum,
but must merely have applied certain principles. The Supreme Court
specifically pointed out that a Canadian court should not grant
an injunction simply because it believes that Canada is the more
appropriate forum.<SUP><A HREF="#88">88</A></SUP> The foreign court is entitled
to make an erroneous decision about the appropriate forum provided
that it bases its decision on principles which are not inconsistent
with the doctrine of <I>forum non conveniens</I>. Second, the
foreign court need not actually apply the doctrine of <I>forum</I>
<I>non conveniens</I>. It may apply whatever doctrine it thinks
fit provided that it is not inconsistent with <I>forum non conveniens</I>.
The result of this is that, if the foreign court has assumed jurisdiction
on principles which are not inconsistent with <I>forum</I> <I>non
conveniens</I>, the inquiry of the Canadian court is at an end
and the injunction fails. This contrasts markedly with the test
established by the Privy Council in <I>Soci<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT>t<FONT FACE="WP MultinationalA Roman">J</FONT></I>
<I>Aerospatiale</I> where the first branch requires an English
court to conclude only that England is a natural forum. Thus,
even if an English court concludes that the foreign forum is also
natural it may continue its analysis. <BR>
<P>
On the facts of <I>Amchem,</I> Texas did not apply the principles
<I>of forum non conveniens. </I>The Supreme Court of Canada nevertheless
found that it exercised jurisdiction in a manner which was not
inconsistent with <I>forum non conveniens</I> because its exercise
of jurisdiction was subject to the limitations imposed by the
Fourteenth Amendment and its restrictions on long-arm jurisdiction.
The Fourteenth Amendment arguably differs from <I>forum non conveniens</I>
in that the amendment addresses the circumstances in which American
courts may assume jurisdiction over a defendant.<SUP><A HREF="#89">89</A></SUP>
The doctrine of <I>forum non conveniens</I>, however, only comes
into play once a court has accepted jurisdiction under its own
laws. Under the doctrine of <I>forum non conveniens</I> a court,
having accepted jurisdiction legally, then decides whether it
is equitable or appropriate to exercise that jurisdiction. <BR>
<P>
Under the second branch of the <I>Amchem</I> test, the court is
to determine whether an injustice would result if the foreign
proceeding were permitted to continue. In most cases, the injustice
will relate to the loss of a juridical advantage.<SUP><A HREF="#90">90</A></SUP>
The party<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s right to
the juridical advantage will be determined with reference to the
party<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s reasonable expectation
to enjoy that advantage in the event of litigation.<SUP><A HREF="#91">91</A></SUP>
It is critical, however, to recall that the Court will only enquire
whether an injustice will result if the foreign court has assumed
jurisdiction according to principles which are inconsistent with
the doctrine of <I>forum non conveniens</I>. Thus, on the <I>Amchem</I>
test, a Canadian court will refuse the injunction and permit an
injustice to occur in foreign proceedings provided that the forum
assumed jurisdiction in a manner which is not inconsistent with
principles of <I>forum</I> <I>non conveniens</I>. This is a curious
result especially since injunctions originate in the equitable
jurisdiction of the Courts. The concern of equity is with justice
and fairness not with technical adherence to legal rules. The
formulation of the <I>Amchem</I> test could produce the opposite.
<BR>
<P>
Perhaps more than anything, the <I>Amchem</I> decision demonstrates
the need for courts to state expressly what they are doing and
why they are doing it rather than simply applying legal rules.
On the one hand, the Supreme Court introduced the concept of reasonable
expectations in assessing juridical advantage and in doing so
stated what it was doing and why. On the other hand, the Supreme
Court then applied rules of comity without analysing why it was
doing so on the facts of the case. Given that the case involved
injuries arising in Canada, to Canadian residents which residents
were bringing an action in Texas, in part, for the purpose of
circumventing the Supreme Court<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
own limits on non-pecuniary damages, it is arguable that principles
of comity should not even have come into play.<BR>
<P>
The difficulties created by the <I>Amchem</I> test are perhaps
best demonstrated by a series of subsequent cases involving Lehndorff
Management Ltd. (<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>Lehndorff<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>),
a large property management company, and a syndicate of banks
headed by a Gentra Canada Investments Inc. (<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>Gentra<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>),
a large financial institution. <BR>
<P>
Lehndorff borrowed $110 million from the syndicate and defaulted
on the loan. As a result of a compromise agreement, Lehndorff
agreed to repurchase the loan for $78 million. The compromise
agreement was conditional on the approval of the Boards of Directors
of the syndicate members. Approval was not forthcoming, as a result
of which the syndicate demanded payment on the loan. When Lehndorff
failed to pay, the syndicate moved to enforce its security, a
large commercial shopping centre located in the province of Alberta,
by commencing an action in Alberta for payment of the loan and
by having a receiver appointed to manage the shopping centre.
<BR>
<P>
Lehndorff retaliated by seeking a declaration in the province
of Ontario that the compromise agreements were in full force,
as well as an injunction to restrain the syndicate from enforcing
on its security. The syndicate moved to stay the Ontario proceedings
on principles of <I>forum non conveniens.<BR>
</I>
<P>
The Ontario court<SUP><A HREF="#92">92</A></SUP> approached its analysis by applying
the checklist of connecting factors rather than by enforcing the
expectations of the parties and concluded that Ontario was the
more appropriate forum for Lehndorff's action because the compromise
agreement was negotiated and executed in Ontario and because all
but one of the parties to the action was based in Ontario.<BR>
<P>
The syndicate then returned to Alberta and obtained an anti-suit
injunction against Lehndorff prohibiting it from proceeding with
its Ontario action. The Alberta Court of Appeal upheld the injunction.
The decisions of the two Alberta courts demonstrate that courts
will strive to preserve the reasonable expectations of the parties
no matter what legal formula they are required to massage in order
to do so.<BR>
<P>
When dealing with the anti-suit injunction, the Alberta courts
were bound to apply the <I>Amchem</I> test which would only allow
the injunction if the Ontario court had assumed jurisdiction on
a basis which was inconsistent with Alberta's rules of <I>forum
non conveniens</I> and if an injustice would result if the Ontario
action were permitted to continue.<BR>
<P>
Both Alberta and Ontario apply identical principles of <I>forum
non conveniens</I>. The Ontario court had clearly applied the
principals of <I>forum non conveniens</I> and had reviewed a lengthy
checklist of factors which it concluded made Ontario the appropriate
forum. The Alberta Court of Queen Bench<SUP><A HREF="#93">93</A></SUP> then essentially
ignored the test in <I>Amchem </I>and came to its own conclusion
as to which of the two forums was more appropriate. The Alberta
court concluded that it was the more appropriate forum because
it had <I>in rem</I> jurisdiction over the security for the loan
(the shopping centre) and that such <I>in rem</I> jurisdiction
included jurisdiction over matters incidental to the security
such as personal actions on loan deficiencies. Moreover, it pointed
out that Lehndorff's request for specific performance of the compromise
agreement directly interfered with Alberta's <I>in rem</I> jurisdiction
and that by raising the compromise agreement as the basis for
a defence and counterclaim to the Alberta enforcement proceedings,
Lehndorff agreed to be bound by that result. Arguably these considerations
established that the reasonable expectations of the parties were
to have the dispute heard in Alberta. <BR>
<P>
The majority of the Alberta Court of Appeal upheld the injunction
and tried to fit it within the <I>Amchem</I> test by finding that
the Ontario court had been unreasonable in failing to consider
the fact that Lehndorff had incorporated its claim on the compromise
agreement in the Alberta action by raising it as a basis for a
defence and counterclaim.<SUP><A HREF="#94">94</A></SUP> This may well have been
unreasonable but it clearly was not <I>inconsistent</I> with the
principles of <I>forum non conveniens</I> it simply reflected
a different way, albeit more mechanical, of balancing the connecting
factors involved in applying the principles.<BR>
<P>
The court concluded that there was injustice in forcing the syndicate
to proceed in two jurisdictions because it in effect required
the syndicate to stay its foreclosure proceedings against the
security while the Ontario action was resolved.<BR>
<P>
The reaction of the Alberta court is understandable. The difficulty
arose because the Ontario court simply looked at a mechanical
checklist of factors and did not address the reasonable expectations
of the parties. An assessment of which, it is submitted, would
lead to Alberta as the proper forum. The land and the security
which were the subject of the action were located in Alberta.
The Alberta courts therefore clearly exercised <I>in rem</I> jurisdiction.
The compromise agreement under which Lehndorff claimed arose out
of its default under the Alberta mortgage. It was therefore directly
incidental to something over which Alberta courts exercised <I>in
rem</I> jurisdiction. Indeed, had Lehndorff not defaulted on the
mortgage, the compromise documents would never even have come
into existence. The presence of these factors arguably creates
a reasonable expectation on the part of any business person that
Alberta is the proper forum. The Alberta courts appeared to agree
and were prepared to massage the <I>Amchem</I> test as aggressively
as required to fulfill those expectations. <BR>
<P>
VI. NEGATIVE DECLARATIONS<BR>
<!--VI.  NEGATIVE DECLARATIONS-->
<P>
In many respects a negative declaration is the flip side of an
anti-suit injunction. In its most literal form, a negative declaration
is a declaration that a party is not subject to a particular form
of liability arising out of the circumstances of a particular
set of events. It is most commonly brought by a party who is or
who anticipates being a defendant in a foreign jurisdiction where
the foreign jurisdiction would have less favourable rules than
the jurisdiction in which the negative declaration is sought.
In cases where both parties to a transaction may have claims against
each other, the negative declaration need not take the formal
form of a declaration as such. A party may be able to achieve
the same result by simply commencing a lawsuit in a jurisdiction
which is more favourable to them.<BR>
<P>
Negative declarations are most useful if the defendant has assets
only in the jurisdiction in which he intends to seek a negative
declaration. In such cases, a foreign plaintiff would have to
come to the jurisdiction which granted the negative declaration
in order to enforce his judgment. It is unlikely that a court
would enforce a foreign judgment if it had previously granted
a negative declaration. Negative declarations may, however, also
have some value if the intended defendant has assets in the foreign
jurisdiction. If the negative declaration is obtained before a
judgment is granted in the foreign jurisdiction, it may well render
the issue in the foreign proceeding <I>res</I> <I>judicata</I>
or may raise an issue estoppel against the plaintiff in the foreign
proceeding. <BR>
<P>
Neither the British nor the Canadian courts appear to have formulated
well-developed tests with respect to negative declarations. British
courts have expressed their distaste for negative declarations
on numerous occasions because they involve possible conflicts
with other jurisdictions.<SUP><A HREF="#95">95</A></SUP> <BR>
<P>
English courts have tended to focus on the natural forum as the
basis for deciding whether to grant a negative declaration. In
<I>First National Bank of Boston</I> v. <I>Union Bank of Switzerland</I><SUP><A HREF="#96">96</A></SUP>
for example, an employee of First National had participated in
a scheme pursuant to which he caused a branch of the Union Bank
of Switzerland (<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>UBS<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>)
to be defrauded of $5 million. UBS commenced proceedings in Switzerland
and attached assets of First National in Geneva. First National
thereupon sought a declaration in England that it was not liable
to UBS. The court first analysed the connecting factors and concluded
that Switzerland was the appropriate forum. The court then asked
itself whether a negative declaration would <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">A</FONT>be
useful<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">@</FONT>.<SUP><A HREF="#97">97</A></SUP>
The court concluded that a declaration would not be useful in
light of the fact that Switzerland was an appropriate jurisdiction
and that UBS could proceed against the attached assets in Switzerland.
<BR>
<P>
The Canadian experience with negative declarations has been entirely
different, although as yet quite limited.<BR>
<P>
In <I>Guarantee Company of North America</I> v. <I>Gordon Capital,</I><SUP><A HREF="#98">98</A></SUP>
Guarantee Company had issued a fidelity bond to Gordon Capital
on which Gordon Capital was claiming $35 million. Guarantee Company
denied liability on the basis of misrepresentation. At first blush,
all connecting factors pointed to Ontario as the appropriate forum.
The bond had been negotiated and issued in Ontario. Gordon Capital
was based in Ontario. The circumstances giving rise to the loss
occurred in Ontario and the bond provided that Ontario law governed.
<BR>
<P>
Gordon Capital nevertheless commenced its action for a claim on
the bond in Quebec where Guarantee Company had its head office.
Quebec had a three year limitation period while Ontario would
have applied a two year limitation period which had already expired.
<BR>
<P>
Guarantee Company brought a motion to stay the Quebec action on
the basis of <I>forum non conveniens</I>. It failed at first instance
and appealed to the Quebec Court of Appeal.<BR>
<P>
While the appeal was underway, Guarantee Company commenced a second
proceeding in Ontario for a declaration that the bond was void
because of misrepresentations by Gordon Capital. Gordon Capital
then brought a motion to stay the Ontario proceedings in view
of the Quebec action. <BR>
<P>
The court treated the motion strictly as a motion to stay a proceeding
to which only principles of <I>forum non conveniens</I> applied.
It took pains to point out that comity did not arise as an issue
because it was only relevant to anti-suit injunctions where one
court was interfering with another jurisdiction. The court did
not address the issue of negative declarations nor did it refer
to English cases which had dealt with negative declarations before.
<BR>
<P>
The Ontario court implicity enforced the reasonable expectations
of the parties and concluded that Ontario was the appropriate
forum because all connecting factors pointed to it. It dismissed
the juridical advantage to Gordon of proceeding in Quebec by finding
that it was offset by the juridical advantage to Guarantee Company
by proceeding in Ontario. The court concluded that it knew of
no reason why the two actions could not proceed in different provinces
at the same time given that the courts of both provinces were
subject to the supervision of the Supreme Court of Canada.<BR>
<P>
While the result in the decision seems sensible and certainly
accords with the reasonable expectations of the parties, particularly
in light of the fact that they had contractually agreed that Ontario
law applied, the reasoning seems strained. It is arguably too
narrow a view to state that issues of comity do not apply by characterizing
the issue strictly as one of a stay of proceedings rather than
one which might interfere with another jurisdiction. An Ontario
judgment adverse to Gordon Capital could be raised in Quebec by
way of a <I>res</I> <I>judicata</I> argument or an issue estoppel
to prevent Gordon Capital from proceeding with its action in Quebec.
In that sense it would have deprived the Quebec court of the ability
to determine the matter. The court was, however, able to avoid
the more difficult issue of conflicts between jurisdictions by
pointing to the fact that both jurisdictions are subject to the
overriding authority of the Supreme Court of Canada.<BR>
<P>
In <I>Lehndorff v. Gentra<SUP><A HREF="#99">99</A></SUP> </I>the same judge of the
Ontario Court General Division had a second occasion to deal with
parallel proceedings. As described above, Gentra had commenced
an action in Alberta to enforce on its security against a shopping
centre in response to which Lehndorff brought an action in Ontario
claiming that a certain compromise agreement had been breached.
The Ontario Court refused Gentra <FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
motion to stay the Ontario action on the principles of <I>forum
non conveniens</I>. The Court concluded that having parallel proceedings
in Alberta and Ontario was not necessarily undesirable because
the decision of the first court would likely be binding on the
second.<BR>
<P>
Arguably, the courts should not be willing to accept parallel
proceedings. The danger is that they base outcomes on a race to
the quickest and not on any rational principles. To conclude that
the first decision would be binding on the second court, simply
means that the court system which operates the fastest will always
impose its juridical advantage on the parties even if they have
no reasonable expectations of enjoying it. This seems significantly
less principled than even the mechanical application of connecting
factors. An analysis of the reasonable expectations of the parties
and a decision based on them would, it is submitted, provide a
more principled basis for the resolution of the problem of parallel
proceedings created by requests for negative declarations. <BR>
<P>
VII. CONCLUSION<BR>
<!--VII.  CONCLUSION-->
<P>
This review of Anglo-Canadian law on forum shopping suggests that
courts have created needless difficulties by tying themselves
to legal tests developed for a different era. This has forced
courts at times to adopt strained logic in order to fit their
cases into older legal rules but still fulfill the reasonable
expectations of the parties. <BR>
<P>
The driving force behind most forum shopping is a desire to claim
a juridical advantage. In most cases, courts have failed to ask
why a party should even be entitled to a particular advantage.
The Supreme Court of Canada<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s
express link between juridical advantage and reasonable expectations
is a welcome development to providing a principled basis for analysing
a party<FONT FACE="WP TypographicSymbols">=</FONT>s right to such
an advantage.<BR>
<P>
While juridical advantage is likely to remain the focus of most
forum shopping cases, reasonable expectations should be applied
to the overall determination of the appropriate forum and not
be restricted to the right to a juridical advantage. Personal
advantages or disadvantages should be decided on the same basis:
what reasonable expectation did a party have to claim the benefit
of a particular advantage?<BR>
<P>
The enforcement of reasonable expectations is a fundamental cornerstone
of most secular legal systems. As such, it is an approach which
is unlikely to create conflicts between jurisdictions. Indeed,
the enforcement of reasonable expectations inherently acknowledges
and enforces international comity by recognizing that the juridical
advantages or disadvantages of a particular forum are part of
a more complex series of trade-offs which ought to be respected.
A plaintiff ought not to be able to claim a juridical advantage
from a forum which does not correspond to the reasonable expectations
of the parties merely because the forum which does correspond
to those expectations denies him the advantage. That forum presumably
has good policy reasons for denying the advantage and will frequently
compensate for that denial in some other way. The use of reasonable
expectations analysis acknowledges and respects these differences
and recognizes that they are part of a more complex social contract
which the parties have helped shape. <BR>
<BR>
