<HEAD>

<TITLE>Pulling Up the Drawbridge: New Proposals on Taxpayer Migration</TITLE>

<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>Pulling Up the Drawbridge: New Proposals on Taxpayer Migration </FONT></B></CENTER>

<BR>
<P>
The annual report of the federal Auditor General released earlier
this year created a furor in Parliament and the media by disclosing
the substance of an advance income tax ruling issued in 1991 in
connection with the emigration of a personal trust and its sole
beneficiary. The report levelled criticisms both at the operation
of Revenue Canada's tax ruling process in that case and, more
importantly, the adoption by Revenue Canada of a statutory interpretation
that permitted assets to be transferred out of Canada in circumstances
where substantial capital gains tax was deferred and potentially
avoided entirely.  
<P>
In response, the House of Commons Finance Committee examined the
issues and prepared a report, and on October 2 the Minister of
Finance tabled a Notice of Ways and Means Motion in the House
of Commons proposing amendments to the <I>Income Tax Act </I>(Canada)
(the &quot;Act&quot;) that not only address the technical issues
raised by the Auditor General, but also, among other things, tighten
the application of the so-called &quot;departure tax&quot; rules.
These proposals will significantly affect the tax treatment of
persons who cease to be Canadian residents. The package also proposes
that persons ceasing to be resident in Canada at any time after
1995 provide a report listing each property they owned at the
time they ceased to be resident, subject to certain minimum thresholds
and exemptions. <BR>
<P>
<B><U>Departure Tax Exclusions</B></U>
<P>
The Minister proposes that there be a significant expansion of
the range of assets that are subject to the statutory deemed disposition
on ceasing to be resident in Canada.  Commencing October 2, 1996,
an individual will be deemed, prior to ceasing to be resident
in Canada, to have disposed of all of his or her property for
proceeds equal to its fair market value. This deemed disposition
will not apply to:
<UL>
<LI>real property situated in Canada
<LI>capital property used in, or property described in an inventory
of, a business carried on by the individual through a permanent
establishment in Canada immediately before that time,
<LI>a right to receive certain payments such as annuities and
rights under pensions, RRSPs and other deferred income arrangements
or a right to receive any payment of a benefit under the <I>Canada
Pension Plan</I> or a provincial pension plan,
<LI>where the individual is not a trust, and was resident in Canada
for a period or periods totalling not more than 60 months during
the 10 years immediately before emigration, property that was
owned by the individual at the time he or she last became a Canadian
resident or acquired by the individual by inheritance or bequest
after he or she last became a Canadian resident, and
<LI>a right to acquire shares of the capital stock of a corporation
where certain employee stock option rules would apply. 
</UL>
<P>
This amendment will have a dramatic effect on many individuals
considering emigration from Canada if these proposals are enacted
as currently proposed. Prior to October 2, the deemed disposition
did not apply to shares of private corporations, certain interests
in partnerships and Canadian-resident trusts, and a number of
other properties.
<P>
<B><U>Providing Security</B></U>
<P>
The proposals indicate that taxpayers will be permitted to provide
security acceptable to the Minister of National Revenue for the
payment of any tax liability that may arise as a result of a deemed
disposition described above. The background material released
by the Minister of Finance indicates that where the proposals
permit security to be provided in lieu of payment of tax, the
tax liability triggered by emigration will not bear interest.
It appears, therefore, that although the technical liability for
tax will be created at the time of the departure, there will be
no disincentive to delay payment until a subsequent sale or other
disposition occurs, apart from the cost of providing security.
In this fashion, the liability for tax will be crystallized before
the individual terminates Canadian residency and before any bilateral
income tax treaties come into play.   However, the actual collection
of the tax may be deferred. Because there is no interest cost
for taxpayers electing to provide security, the real effect of
the proposals in many cases will simply be to protect Canada's
ability to collect the taxes that were intended to be caught under
the prior rules. <BR>
<P>
<B><U>Planning Issues: Private Corporations</B></U>
<P>
The impact of the proposal is illustrated through the example
of an individual holding assets through a private corporation.
<P>
Until October 2, the individual could leave Canada without departure
tax in respect of the accrued gains on the shares or the accrued
gains or income attributable to the assets of the corporation.
If the former resident subsequently wished to draw assets from
the corporation, or wind it up, the tax consequences for both
the individual and the corporation would be determined at the
time of such a transaction. Typically, there would be recognition
of gains, income and losses in the corporation and withholding
tax on the distribution to the individual to the extent the amount
distributed exceeded any return of paid-up capital. A capital
gain would arise in the hands of the individual only if the transaction
involved a disposition of shares in circumstances where the paid-up
capital of the shares exceeded their adjusted cost base in the
hands of the individual. The application of Canadian deemed dividend
and capital gains rules would be subject to any reductions in
withholding tax rates or other relief available under any applicable
tax treaty between Canada and the former resident's new country
of residence.  The individual would of course, be subject to taxes
imposed by the new jurisdiction of residence, as well as the local
foreign tax credit rules.
<P>
The same individual holding such shares and now contemplating
emigration will have to deal with a mandatory deemed disposition
of the corporation's shares immediately before departure. The
potential for double tax may be significant, since tax triggered
before departure from Canada by the fair market value deemed disposition
will not necessarily give rise to foreign tax credits in the new
jurisdiction to shelter any local tax that may arise when the
underlying assets are eventually disposed of and distributed to
the individual. 
<P>
In any particular case the analysis may be difficult and subject
to Canadian and foreign uncertainties. On the Canadian side, the
deemed disposition will cause a step-up in the tax cost of the
shares and depending on the circumstances this may, on a future
disposition, give rise to a capital loss which in turn may be
available to reduce taxes on other capital gains in the year of
disposition or in other years, subject to loss carryover limitations.
<P>
Additional issues will arise in the new country of residence and
advisors there will have to be consulted to determine whether
the payment of current or deferred departure tax will qualify
for foreign tax credits in that country in the year of payment
(not necessarily a simple question since the actual liability
for tax will have arisen prior to departure).
<P>
Careful planning will be required to minimize these risks and
in certain cases taxpayers may be forced to change their emigration
plans or actually sell or wind-up their Canadian assets before
departure. For many, the prospect of an immediate sale or winding-up
may raise insurmountable liquidity problems. Unfortunately, there
is no suggestion that the right to defer tax and provide security
would extend to tax liabilities arising under other sections of
the Act even where such liabilities arise as a result of steps
taken in connection with departure planning.<BR>
<P>
<B><U>Asset Reporting</B></U> 
<P>
It appears the Department of Finance is becoming increasingly
enamoured of enhanced information reporting with respect to assets
owned by Canadian taxpayers. The February 27, 1995 Budget proposed
extensive new reporting requirements with respect to certain foreign
assets held by Canadian taxpayers and transactions involving foreign
corporations and trusts. Details of these reporting requirements
were released for public discussion on March 5, 1996 (and are
discussed in our March 12, 1996 Private Client Update). The October
2 proposals contain additional information reporting requirements.
<P>
Specifically, all individuals who cease at any time after 1995
to be Canadian residents and who own at that time property the
total fair market value of which is greater than $25,000 will
be required to provide a report in prescribed form listing each
property that they owned at that time (other than a personal-use
property _ e.g. residences and motor vehicles used primarily for
personal use or enjoyment _ that has a fair market value of less
than $10,000). <BR>
<P>
While such information reporting does not go to the heart of the
taxpayer's tax liabilities, such asset reporting represents a
significant departure from the manner in which the Canadian tax
system has applied to individuals since its inception. The Act
has required reporting of income, gains and dispositions of capital
property, but comprehensive reporting of assets owned by a taxpayer
has not been required of individuals. The February 1995 Budget
proposals and the October 2 proposals break with this tradition
and require individuals to report certain assets regardless of
whether or not such assets give rise to any income or loss, or
have been disposed of for the purposes of the Act.<BR>
<P>
<B><U>Concluding Observations</B></U>
<P>
The Minister of Finance has invited comments on the October 2
proposals. At present it is unclear whether any of the specific
proposals are likely to change in any material way. There is no
indication as to when draft legislation will be released or when
enactment of legislative proposals might be expected.
<P>
Regardless of any tinkering that may take place, it seems clear
that the departure tax rules will be substantially tightened.
Revenue losses arising from a variety of creative tax planning
opportunities will be curtailed. For many taxpayers considering
emigration, the potential burden of Canadian tax will become considerably
greater than it may have been up until October 2.
<P>
<I>For further information or elaboration on any aspect of the
material contained in this Update, please contact any of the following
individuals:</I>
<P>
<I><A HREF="mailto:sbowman@mcbinch.com">Stephen W. Bowman</A> (416) 865-7200</I>
<P>
<I><A HREF="mailto:lgoldstein@mcbinch.com">D. Lisa Goldstein</A> (416) 865-7885</I>
<P>
<I><A HREF="mailto:croberts@mcbinch.com">Catherine A. Roberts</A> (416) 865-7202<BR>
</I>
<P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="WNew.pb.gif">

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=right HSPACE=12 VSPACE=10 BORDER=1 SRC="Link3.gif" ALT="McMillan Binch Home Page"></A>
