<HEAD>

<TITLE>REGULATION OF OVER-THE-COUNTER DERIVATIVES BY THE ONTARIO SECURITIES COMMISSION</TITLE>

<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>REGULATION OF OVER-THE-COUNTER DERIVATIVES
BY </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>THE ONTARIO SECURITIES COMMISSION<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<I><B>This bulletin is for informational purposes only and summarizes
current developments and issues of interest in the field of finance
and insolvency law.  It does not offer legal advice.  Persons
requiring advice relating to matters discussed in this bulletin
should contact their professional advisors.<BR>
<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
<B>The Ontario Securities Commission (the </B>&quot;<B>Commission</B>&quot;<B>)
has released a proposed rule (the </B>&quot;<B>Rule</B>&quot;<B>)
accompanied by a statement of policy (the </B>&quot;<B>Policy</B>&quot;<B>)
regarding the regulation of over-the-counter (</B>&quot;<B>OTC</B>&quot;<B>)
derivatives in Ontario.  The purpose of the Rule is to remove
uncertainty as to the applicability of the<I> Securities Act</I>
(the </B>&quot;<B>Act</B>&quot;<B>) to OTC derivatives transactions.
 The new Rule will replace the draft ruling and policy statement
(the </B>&quot;<B>Draft Ruling</B>&quot;<B>) published by the
Commission in January, 1994.  Parties interested in making written
submissions with respect to the Rule and Policy must provide them
by March 3, 1997.  <BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>The Rule is substantially the same as the Draft Ruling except
for the following changes:  <BR>
<OL>
<LI type="i">The Commission has interpreted Bill 190 such that it permits
the Commission to regulate OTC derivatives without the need to
consider whether an OTC derivatives transaction constitutes a
trade in securities.<BR><BR>
<LI>The definition of qualified party has been expanded as
a result of comments received following the publication of the
Draft Ruling.<BR><BR>
<LI>The definition of OTC derivatives in the Rule has been
expanded by eliminating the narrow list of underlying interests
to which a financial contract must be tied.  The Rule, therefore,
applies to all OTC derivatives transactions regardless of the
nature or type of its underlying interests.<BR><BR>
<LI>Under the Rule, all specified commodity derivatives transactions
involving only qualified parties are exempt transactions, regardless
of whether the purpose of the derivatives transaction is for risk
management or hedging.  Specified commodity is defined to include,
among other categories, grains, metals, oils, exotics (such as
electricity/pollutant emission) along with any other derivatives
designated by the Commission from time to time. </B>
</OL>
<P>
<P>
<B>The definitions determine the applicability of the Rule and,
arguably, are its most important aspect.  OTC derivatives means
an option, a forward contract or a contract for differences in
which the material terms of the agreement must be customized for
the purposes of the user, the instrument must not be entered into
or traded on an organized exchange and the creditworthiness of
a party must be an important factor in deciding the terms of the
instrument or whether to enter into the agreement.  The Policy
confirms that master agreements, such as the ISDA master agreement,
would not be considered standardized agreements.<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>Another determinative issue concerning the application of the
Act is whether the parties to an OTC derivatives transaction fit
within the definition of qualified party (</B>&quot;<B>Qualified
Party</B>&quot;<B>).  An appendix to the Rule lists numerous entities
including financial institutions, governments, funds, brokers/dealers,
charities, commercial users, certain individuals and other sophisticated
parties, each of which is a Qualified Party under the Rule.  It
is important to note that according to the Policy, a party is
able to rely on the representations made by a counterparty that
it is a Qualified Party.  (For more detailed descriptions of Qualified
Parties, please see Appendix A attached). <BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>The Rule establishes three categories of OTC derivatives transactions,
each of which is subject to differing degrees of regulation under
the Act<I>.</I>  The first category consists of the following
OTC derivatives transactions which will be exempt from the application
of the Act (</B>&quot;<B>Exempt Transactions</B>&quot;<B>):<BR>

<OL>
<LI type="i">an interest rate/foreign exchange derivatives transaction
where each party is a Qualified Party or a party entering the
transaction for OTC derivatives hedging purposes, or<BR><BR>
<LI>specified commodity derivatives where all parties are Qualified
Parties.  </B>
</OL>
<P>
<P>
<B>The Commission is satisfied that Exempt Transactions do not
require regulation because of the sophistication of the parties
and because of the nature of the transactions.  <BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>Transactions which are not Exempt Transactions are afforded
unconditional prospectus and registration exemptions if each party
to the transaction is a Qualified Party (</B>&quot;<B>Qualified
Party Transactions</B>&quot;<B>).  It should be noted that unlike
Exempt Transactions, Qualified Party Transactions are subject
to other aspects of the Act such as insider trading rules.  <BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>The third category consists of all other OTC derivatives transactions
(</B>&quot;<B>Other Transactions</B>&quot;<B>).  The Commission
is of the view that parties other than Qualified Parties do require
the protection offered under the Act.  For Other Transactions
to be exempt from the registration and prospectus requirements
of the Act, the non-Qualified Party must have entered into the
transaction through an OTC derivatives dealer and must have been
given a generic risk disclosure statement in the form set out
in Appendix B of the Rule.  The statement is intended to educate
the counterparty about the risks posed by OTC derivatives.  The
risks discussed include credit, currency, leveraging and other
factors.<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>Like Qualified Party Transactions, Other Transactions, which
may be exempt from the prospectus and registration requirements
of the Act because the parties have complied with this Rule, remain
subject to the Act</B>'<B>s other components such as insider trading
rules.<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>The Policy makes clear that parties whose transactions do not
fit within the exemptions provided under the Rule continue to
be able to make use of the prospectus and registration exemptions
in the Act.  The Policy also clarifies that the $150,000 exemption
can only be used in OTC derivatives transactions where the $150,000
is a premium or purchase price.  The exemption cannot be used
where it is only the underlying interest that exceeds $150,000.
 Therefore, the $150,000 exemption would not normally be available
for swaps, forwards and other such transactions.<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>It should also be noted that where an exemption under the Act
which requires the filing of a Form 20 is relied on in an OTC
derivatives transaction, a Form 20 must be filed with the Commission
and the requisite fee paid within ten days of the closing of the
transaction.<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>For more information on the draft Rule and Policy please contact
Gary Ostoich (865-7802), Scott Hyman (865-7912), Richard Higa
(865-7864) or Tim Baron (865-7096).<BR>
</B><P>
<IMG SRC="WNew.pb.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><B> APPENDIX A<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>DEFINITION OF QUALIFIED PARTY<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
<B>The applicability of the Rule to a transaction depends, to
a great extent, on whether a party meets the definition of Qualified
Party.  The Appendix to the Rule lists numerous organizations
that are classified as qualified parties.  The term encompasses
a broad range of entities.<BR>
</B>
<UL>
<LI><B>Financial institutions and insurance companies including
those foreign organizations that are regulated by a member country
to the Basle Accord.  Foreign institutions and companies who wish
to qualify must have paid up capital and surplus of at least $150
million.  Any wholly owned subsidiary of one of these organizations
is also a Qualified Party.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Sophisticated entities who have previous experience in
OTC derivatives transactions with non-affiliates where the gross
total dollar value of these transactions is at least $1 billion
and at least one of the contracts was outstanding within the last
15 months.  In the alternative, the entity must have a gross marked-to
market position of $100 million with non-affiliate counterparties
involving OTC derivatives on any day within the past 15 months.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Governments including federal, provincial and territorial
governments, agencies, crown corporations, municipalities with
populations exceeding 50 000, any capital city of a province or
territory, and the national governments of member countries of
the Basle Accord.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Individuals with a net worth of greater than $5 million
excluding the value of their principal residence.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Company, partnership, unincorporated organization, or trust
with total assets greater than $100 million or any wholly-owned
subsidiary thereof.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Pension fund including federally or provincially regulated
and with total net assets of greater than $100 million not including
liability for future pension payments.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Mutual fund or non-redeemable investment fund if:
<P>
<OL>
<LI type="i">each investor in the fund is a Qualified Party;<BR><BR>
<LI>for a mutual fund company, the management company of the
mutual fund must be registered as an adviser under securities
legislation other than a securities adviser; and<BR><BR>
<LI>for a non-redeemable investment fund, the person giving
investment advice must be registered under securities legislation
in Canada as an adviser other than a securities adviser.</B>
</OL>
<P>
<LI><B>Broker or investment dealer registered as such under securities
legislation in Canada or as  an international dealer under the
Act if the international dealer has total assets of greater than
$100 million.  Any wholly-owned subsidiary of these organizations
is also a Qualified Party.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>A futures commission merchant registered as such under
the <I>Commodity Futures Act </I>or any wholly-owned subsidiary
thereof.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>A registered charity under the <I>Income Tax Act</I> with
assets of $5 million or more that are not used directly in charitable
activities or administration.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Commercial user, defined in the Rule as a party that enters
a physical commodity derivatives transaction who deals in business
with a physical commodity and whose underlying interest for the
OTC derivatives meets the test set out in the Rule.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>A party whose obligations are guaranteed by a Qualified
Party.</B>
</UL>
<P>
<P>
