<HEAD>

<TITLE>DERIVATIVES - RECENT CASE REGARDING SET-OFF</TITLE>

<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>DERIVATIVES - RECENT CASE REGARDING SET-OFF
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<I><B>This bulletin is for informational purposes only and summarizes
current developments and issues of interest in the field of finance
and insolvency law. It does not offer legal advice. Persons requiring
advice relating to matters discussed in this bulletin should contact
their professional advisors.<BR>
<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
A recent decision of the Ontario Court<A HREF="#footnote" ><SUP><FONT SIZE=2>1</FONT></A></SUP>
concerning derivatives transactions may have a subtle, yet important,
impact on ISDA documented derivatives transactions. The case concerned
an attempt by Citibank Canada to set off amounts owing from The
Confederation Life Insurance Company and Confederation Treasury
Services Limited under swap agreements and a bond option agreement
against an unrelated bank deposit they held on behalf of Confederation
Life. As a result of Confederation Life encountering severe financial
difficulties and subsequently entering the process of being wound
up, Citibank treated the swap transactions as having been terminated.
Citibank claimed an amount owing under the swap transactions based
on the &quot;market quotation&quot; formula provided in a standard
ISDA master agreement. Justice Blair, speaking for the court,
held that Citibank was not entitled to succeed in law or in equity
in its efforts to set off the bond option agreement and swap transaction
claims against the amount owing to Confederation Life under the
deposit.<BR>
<P>
The court stated that the claim did not meet the test for legal
set-off because the claims under the swap transactions were not
&quot;debts&quot; in the context they were put forward nor were
they &quot;liquidated&quot; debts at the date of the commencement
of the winding up proceedings with respect to Confederation Life.
The court focused on Citibank's contention that they were entitled
to go into the market in order to re-establish the positions that
had been lost as a result of the termination of the swap transactions.
In the court's opinion, these claims sounded in damages and the
fact that the parties had provided a formula for determining such
damages did not alter the nature of the claim. As a result, the
court held that Confederation Life's obligation to reimburse Citibank
for the cost of replacing the swap transactions gave rise to a
claim for damages, not a liquidated debt. <BR>
<P>
The court also rejected a claim for equitable set-off since the
cross claims were not &quot;connected or interrelated in some
manner which would make it unjust to permit one party to enforce
payment without accounting for the existence of the other claim.&quot;
The court noted that the deposit transaction had been entered
into at a different time and for a different purpose than the
swap agreements and option agreement. As a result of the swap
transactions having been entered into separately with no connecting
link, the court held that equitable set-off.<BR>
<P>
This case underscores the limits that may be placed on the ability
of a counterparty to set-off in insolvency proceedings claims
arising from derivatives transactions against other claims arising
from unrelated agreements that the parties may have entered into.
As a result of this case, unless appealed successfully, counterparties
to derivatives transactions should consider and review contractual
rights of set-off included in existing derivatives transaction
documentation to determine what effect, if any, those additional
rights would have with respect to other dealings between counterparties
to transactions.<BR>
<P>
For more information, please contact Gary Ostoich at (416) 865-7802,
Andy&nbsp;Kent at (416) 865-7160 or Scott Hyman at (416) 865-7912.
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="footnote">
<TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=37><I><B>1</B></I></TD><TD WIDTH=601><I><B>Citibank Canada v. Confederation Life Insurance Company et. al.,</B></I><B> (1996) Ont. Ct. of Justice (General Division), Court File No. B13/96.</B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="WNew.pb.gif">

