<HEAD>

<TITLE>Rules for Properly Using Your Trade-Marks</TITLE>

<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Rules for Properly Using Your Trade-Marks<BR></CENTER>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Protecting a valuable trade&#173;mark requires more than just
registering it. Whether or not you register your trade&#173;mark,
you should observe the following 7 main rules for correct trade&#173;mark
use in Canada: 
<P>
1. Use your trade&#173;mark as an adjective
<P>
2. Emphasize your trade&#173;mark in such a way that it is readily
distinguishable from any accompanying text
<P>
3. Do not vary your trade&#173;mark in any way
<P>
4. Use a trade&#173;mark notice
<P>
5. Continue to use your trade&#173;mark
<P>
6. Be careful about authorized use by third parties, and
<P>
7. Be vigilant with respect to unauthorized use by third parties
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>1. Use your trade&#173;mark as an Adjective</B></I>
<P>
It has been said that, &quot;Proper trade&#173;mark use would
be automatic if we would remember that a trade&#173;mark is an
adjective and not a noun&quot;. Trade&#173;marks should never
be used as nouns, verbs, possessives or in the plural. A trade&#173;mark
identifies a particular brand of a product. It is not the name
of the product. The public must recognize the trade&#173;mark,
not as an identification of the product alone, but as the identification
of a particular manufacturer's version of that product.
<P>
Since a trade&#173;mark is an adjective there must be a noun for
it to modify. That noun is the generic name of the product. For
example, in the case of the trade&#173;mark HIDE&#173;A&#173;BED,
you should not say &quot;Sleep well on your HIDE&#173;A&#173;BED&quot;.
Instead, you should say &quot;Sleep well on your HIDE&#173;A&#173;BED
convertible sofa&quot;.
<P>
If a trade&#173;mark is used as a noun and the public uses it
as the name of the product in question, then it ceases to be a
trade&#173;mark and the trade&#173;mark is said to have become
a &quot;generic&quot; term. That means the term is available for
anyone to use and that the owner has lost all of its exclusive
rights. Aspirin, thermos, cellophane and escalator are all common
descriptive names which at one time were trade&#173;marks in the
United States but lost that status because they were used as nouns.
When a trade&#173;mark is lost by conversion into a generic term
it is often the manufacturer's own advertising or labelling which
is at fault.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>2. Emphasize your trade&#173;mark</B></I>
<P>
Your trade&#173;mark should be emphasized or given &quot;special
treatment&quot; so that it is easily distinguishable from any
accompanying text. 
<P>
It is a good idea to display a trade&#173;mark entirely in capital
letters. However if a trade&#173;mark is used in copy which is
itself all in capital letters, then it is advisable to display
the trade&#173;mark in bolder face type, to underline it or to
put it in quotation marks or in larger size letters or in a different
colour so that it stands out. Several of these techniques may
be used together.
<P>
The objective is to emphasize the trade&#173;mark. Naturally the
common descriptive name of the product or service should not receive
the special treatment given to the trade&#173;mark.
<BR><P>
<I><B>3. Do not vary your trade&#173;mark</B></I>
<P>
You should not change the spelling of a word mark in even a minor
way. For example, you should not add or delete a hyphen. Similarly,
if your trade&#173;mark consists of two separate words then the
words should not be combined. The converse is also true. Your
trade&#173;mark should never be abbreviated. Your trade&#173;mark
should not be broken at the end of a line of print. 
<P>
You should never coin any other word from a trade&#173;mark, either
by changing the spelling of a trade&#173;mark or by adding a prefix
or a suffix to it, whether with or without a hyphen, or by any
other method.
<P>
You should use a design mark (a logo) in exactly the form in which
it was registered. For example, a design should not be reversed.
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>4. Use a trade&#173;mark notice</B></I>
<P>
You should indicate in advertising and labelling that your trade&#173;mark
is registered or, if it is not, that you regard it as being a
trade&#173;mark and that you claim exclusive rights to the mark.
<P>
In the case of a <I>registered</I> trade&#173;mark it is common
practice to employ the symbol 7 in close proximity to the trade&#173;mark
in at least one place in the text. It is also recommended that
you use a legend such as &quot;XYZ is a registered trade&#173;mark
of ABC Corporation&quot;. As an alternative to an 7 placed near
the trade&#173;mark, an asterisk may be placed near the trade&#173;mark
and then the legend in the form &quot;*XYZ is a registered trade&#173;mark
of ABC Corporation&quot; may be used somewhere else on the ad
copy or packaging.
<P>
In the case of a trade&#173;mark that has <I>not been registered,</I>
instead of the 7 symbol the letters TM may be used, whether or
not an application to register the trade&#173;mark has been filed.
In that case the legend should read: &quot;XYZ is a trade&#173;mark
of ABC Corporation&quot;.
<P>
In the case of a trade&#173;mark used in Canada under licence
from the trade&#173;mark owner, there should be a written licence
agreement between the parties. When there is a licence arrangement
in place the notice could read: &quot;XYZ is a registered trade&#173;mark
of ABC Corporation, used under licence&quot;.
<P>
Pursuant to recent amendments to the Trade&#173;marks Act in Canada,
if public notice is given of the identity of the trade&#173;mark
owner, and the fact that the use is under licence, then the use
by the licensee will be presumed to be under the control of the
trade&#173;mark owner. Public notice is not defined in the Trade&#173;marks
Act but presumably means notice which is made apparent to the
public, such as notices on labels and in advertising. You will
note that the Act does not require that the name of the licensee
be given, although the licensee's name would often appear for
other reasons &#173; for example, to comply with packaging and
labelling laws.
<P>
If your copy or packaging contains the same trade&#173;mark several
times, such as might occur in a brochure, you need to use the
legend only once, preferably on the page on which the trade&#173;mark
first appears.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>5. Continue to use your trade&#173;mark</B></I>
<P>
It is a basic principle of trade&#173;mark law in Canada that
an owner which stops using its trade&#173;mark loses its rights
in that trade&#173;mark.
<P>
Most often a company which owns a trade&#173;mark which it has
stopped using will lose its rights in that trade&#173;mark as
a result of proceedings initiated by an interested party (usually
a competitor). A competitor may initiate these proceedings because
it wishes to register the same or a similar mark and the presence
on the Trade&#173;marks Register of the trade&#173;mark which
is no longer in use is blocking its application in the Trade&#173;marks
Office.
<P>
Pursuant to the <I>Trade&#173;marks Act</I>, a party which suspects
that a trade&#173;mark is not in use may, after 3 years from the
date of registration of the trade&#173;mark, pay a prescribed
fee and request the Registrar to issue a notice to the owner of
the mark requiring that company to file within 3 months an affidavit
or statutory declaration showing, with respect to each of the
wares or services specified in the registration, whether the trade&#173;mark
is in use in Canada and, if not, the date when it was last so
in use and the reason for the absence of use since that date.
<P>
Unless the Registrar regards this request as frivolous, or a similar
Notice has recently been issued against the same trade&#173;mark
or similar proceedings are already in progress against that trade&#173;mark,
the Registrar will issue the Notice. There is then a set procedure
which is followed. The registrant files an affidavit showing that
its trade&#173;mark was in use at any time during the 2&#173;year
period immediately preceding the date of the notice or that there
are special circumstances that excuse the absence of use, the
requesting party makes a submission, the registrant replies, a
hearing is held and the Registrar makes his decision.
<P>
It should be noted that an affidavit which simply recites that
a trade&#173;mark was in use at any time during the 2&#173;year
period immediately preceding the date of the notice is not satisfactory.
The affidavit must establish sales of the product or providing
of the services in the ordinary course of business and have attached
to it sample labels, letterhead and so on so that the Registrar
is in a position to make his own determination that the trade&#173;mark
was, in fact, being used in the ordinary course of business at
some point during the 2&#173;year period immediately preceding
the date of the notice.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>6. Be careful about authorized use by third parties</B></I>
<P>
It is important that an infringer who is confronted with your
trade&#173;mark owner's rights should not be able to establish
that you are not entitled to exclusive rights in the trade&#173;mark.
<P>
While there are a number of ways in which your trade&#173;mark
rights may be lost, one of the most common of these is the use
of the same or a confusing trade&#173;mark or trade&#173;name
by an entity other than you when such use is not controlled by
you through an appropriate license arrangement. Trade&#173;mark
rights may be lost through either deliberate or inadvertent concurrent
use by parties other than the owner of the trade&#173;mark.
<P>
In Canada, a trade&#173;mark will not be valid if it is used in
Canada by any company other than its owner or by more than one
company unless each company (other than the owner of the mark)
using the mark is licensed by or with the authority of the owner
of the trade&#173;mark to use the trade&#173;mark and the owner
has, under the licence, direct or indirect control of the character
or quality of the wares or services.
<P>
As a trade&#173;mark owner, you should not assume that you have
no responsibilities other than ensuring that a written licence
agreement is in place. Instead, you should take steps to put yourself
in a position where you can establish that you actually do control
the character and quality of the goods and/or services. It would
be wise for you to make periodic inspections of premises, goods,
written materials displaying the trade&#173;mark, advertisements
etc., so that you can demonstrate actual control of the goods
sold and services performed under licence.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>7. Be vigilant about unauthorized use by third parties</B></I>
<P>
The Trade&#173;marks Act gives you, as the owner of a registered
trade&#173;mark, the exclusive right to the use throughout Canada
of the trade&#173;mark in respect of the wares or services covered
by the registration. As well, design trade&#173;marks can often
be protected under copyright law. It should be noted that the
product or service in association with which the third party mark
is used (for example a T&#173;shirt or mug) doesn't necessarily
have to be a product or service which you sell in association
with your trade&#173;mark before liability for trade&#173;mark
or copyright infringement will be found.
<P>
If you do nothing which will damage your trade&#173;mark, that
is half the battle. However, the other half is to ensure that
your trade&#173;mark is not damaged by the activities of others.
Education is needed to prevent innocent misuse. Aggressive legal
action is required to stop intentional misuse.<BR>

<P>
If third parties use the same or a similar trade&#173;mark in
association with the same or similar goods and you do not use
your legal rights to stop them, then eventually your rights in
your trade&#173;mark may be lost because the public won't be receiving
a clear message as to the source of the goods. For that reason,
it is important to watch the marketplace for any use of confusing
marks and to pursue such problems.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
When you properly use and maintain your trade&#173;mark, you have
the exclusive right to use it on and in connection with products
or services of the type that it identifies, and this right will
be protected by law indefinitely so long as the trade&#173;mark
remains in use and is used properly and the registration is kept
in force. Since trade&#173;marks are very valuable assets it is
well worth the effort to take all the steps which are necessary
to maintain them as a valuable marketing tool.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I>Copyright 1994 McMillan Binch</I>
<P>
