<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch: Chairs and Chief Executives: Why and How the Functions
Should be Separated</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<P><CENTER>
<B><H2>Chairs and Chief Executives:<BR></H2><H3> Why and How the Functions
Should be Separated<BR></CENTER>
</H3></B>
<P>
<I>by</I>
<P>
<B>Simon Chester
</B><P>
<B><I>McMillan Bull Casgrain, Toronto
</B></I><P>
<I>and</I>
<P>
<B>J William Rowley QC
<P>
<I>McMillan Bull Casgrain, Toronto; Vice-Chairman, IBA Section on
Business Law<BR>
</I></B>
<P>
Over the past few years, major studies in the US, UK, Canada and
South Africa have come to remarkably similar conclusions on the
issue of separating the roles of CEO and Chairman.  Each study
looked specifically at corporate governance, and each identified
the separation of the roles and responsibilities of the Chairman
and Chief Executive Officer as a key factor in promoting effective
corporate governance.<BR>

<P>
If the advice to divide the functions is easily stated, it is
harder to implement.  How exactly are the new Chairman and the
Chief Executive to work together?  What are the safeguards against
the Chairman assuming so many of the Chief Executive's
roles as to weaken his or her authority?  What balance of responsibility
is appropriate?<BR>

<P>
Despite such challenges, corporations and boards which think through
these issues carefully cannot fail to improve their corporate
governance awareness, no matter what the outcome.  The right outcome
will also yield increased business effectiveness.<BR>

<P>
To help them in this process, this article provides a set of practical
guidelines on how to deal, on a day-to-day basis, with the separation
of functions.<BR>

<P>
In approaching the question of separating these functions, it
must always be borne in mind that they oversee.   This means that
there is no single right answer as boards and corporation grapple
with this issue.  As the recent Toronto Stock Exchange Committee
Report on Corporate Governance noted, there are 'many
roads to Rome'.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Trends on both side of the Atlantic<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
In England, the report of the Committee on the Financial Aspects
of Corporate Governance (the Cadbury Report) was issued in December
1992 with the Financial Reporting Council announcing a follow-up
study in June 1995.  The Cadbury Report was unequivocal -- there
should be a 'clearly
accepted division of responsibilities at the head of a company,
which will ensure a balance of power and authority, such that
no individual has unfettered powers of decision'.
 This follows the standard English practice where the Chief Executive's
position and Chair's
position are historically held by two individuals.  In some English
corporations, this model has been taken as far as making the Chairman
responsible for all outside communications.  Thus, the Chairman
would be responsible for meeting with significant investors, communicating
with government and the media, and presenting the public profile
of the corporation.<BR>

<P>
In South Africa developments have been similar.  The Institute
of Directors in Southern Africa formed the King Committee in 1994
to look into corporate governance reform, financial oversight,
and developing a code of ethical practice for business.  In addition
to recommending a balance between management and outside directors,
the Report recommends that corporations be chaired by outside
directors unless the Board considers that this will not be in
the corporation's best
interests.<BR>

<P>
In Canada, the TSE Committee Report on Corporate Governance of
December 1994, stopped just short of mandating a split between
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer, although the Committee expressed
strong preference for such a separation.  Because all companies
listed on the largest Canadian Stock Exchange are now required
to report on how far their corporate governance practices conform
to the TSE recommendations.  The largest Canadian companies are
now faced squarely with the split Chair/CEO issue as an immediate
agenda item.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>A Changing North American Model<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
If the separate roles of the Chairman and Chief Executive can
be said to have been the English model, in North America, the
model of a single strong person combining both roles has tended
to prevail.  Until recently, more than 80 percent of major public
corporations in North America followed this pattern.  But this
is changing and the currently held view in an increasing number
of senior corporate governance circles strongly favours a separation
of roles.  A number of major corporations are taking this tack.
 General Motors, TWA and Morrison Knudsen have each split off
the Chairman's role
from that of the CEO.<BR>

<P>
The most recent Korn/Ferry International Board of Directors survey
shows that in 23 percent of North America's
major corporations, the roles are already split, with a further
10 percent having the split issue on the board's
working agenda.<BR>

<P>
In the United States, while there has been less consideration
of the issues by institutional studies such as the Cadbury Report
or the TSE Report, there has been strong support for the idea
in the business press, from shareholder activists and from professional
and academic commentators.  Most notably in May 1994, General
Motors unveiled a 'Magna
Carta' for directors,
which argue that board power should be vested primarily in the
board's non-executive
directors, rather than in management.  In reflection of this deliberate
shift in power, it was felt that the group's
Chief Executive Officer should not have plenary powers over the
board.<BR>

<P>
The GM Guidelines recommended a separation of the Chairman's
position from that of Chief Executive Officer, in order to maintain
board independence from management.  Following the GM lead, major
corporations across the world are re-evaluating governance structures,
many of them by reference to the GM Guidelines and all considering
whether the company's
corporate governance would be strengthened by a separation of
powers at top levels.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Lack of precedents in North America<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
In North America, few precedents exist to guide corporations making
the split.  This is likely because the benefits of separating
the Chairman's and Chief
Executive responsibilities have only been recognised relatively
recently as the corporate governance debate has intensified over
the past decade.  It will be important for all involved to come
to terms with their respective roles and responsibilities, and
for due consideration to be given to planning for change.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Legal and business principles to be applied<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
It is fundamental that any division of responsibilities between
Chairman and Chief Executive must respect both the legal and pragmatic
requirements of corporate governance.  In the common law jurisdictions
the board is responsible under law for the management of the corporation
(in the sense of overseeing management) and answers to its shareholders.
 This, it is management's
role to manage, while the board's
job is to ensure there is good management.  This points to the
vital distinction between the two jobs:<BR>

<P>
<UL><LI> the Chairman and the board is chosen by and is accountable to
the board.  His job is to run the business of the board, not to
run the company;<BR>
<BR><BR>
<LI> the board delegates to management the authority to run the company's
business.  The Chief Executive's
job is to do just that, but not the business of the board, which
oversees him and his management team;<BR>

<BR><BR><LI>
 the Chief Executive is appoint by and reports to the board.
<BR>
</UL>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Decision to separate the function -- what to do?
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
In our experience, when a decision is made to split the functions,
it is helpful for the Chairman and Chief Executive to meet formally
to discuss a workable division of responsibilities, possibly assisted
by a neutral experienced advisor.  Such discussions should be
designed to lead to job descriptions and a corporate protocol
defining respective responsibilities and patterns of interaction.
 At the very least, the participants will gain an understanding
of the boundaries of their roles.  If documents do result from
the discussions -- and they should -- they should be discussed
with and eventually approved by the board, with Chairman and Chief
Executive accepting responsibility to be so bound.<BR>

<P>
It is the key to the process that the separation of the two roles
does not undermine the Chief Executive's
day-to-day authority over the company's
business or lead to uncertainty of roles for either Chairman or
Chief Executive.  Equally, the Chief Executive must come away
with an understanding of the limits of his or her role and of
the reality of the Chairman's
responsibilities.<BR>

<P>
The topics discussed below will provide useful heads for the agenda
of the suggested meetings.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Chief Executive's
roles<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
In every sense the Chief Executive runs the corporation.  He is
ultimately responsible for every detail of its day-to-day operation.
 Accordingly, it would be a vast task to list the working responsibilities
of any particular Chief Executive, let alone to generalise from
the itemised responsibilities of particular individuals.<BR>

<P>
Instead, the proper functioning of the Chief Executive can best
be shown by highlighting those roles which we suggest should be
more properly the responsibilities of the Chairman.  A number
of these responsibilities are much easier to carry out if a different
individual holds the Chairman's
job.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Chairman's
roles</FONT></B>
<P>
<I><B>Representing the Corporation<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
One question to be addressed is how far the Chairman's
role should be extended beyond the Board's
business, and chairing shareholder's
meetings, to present a public face to the corporation.  In England,
for example, it is common for a non-executive Chairman to take
on the role of corporate spokesman to broadly based constituencies
such as the general public, the financial community, employees,
government and the like.<BR>

<P>
While this division of responsibilities has apparently worked
well in the business culture of the UK, it is likely to be problematic
in North America.  In the United States and Canada, this aspect
of the UK approach would run the risk of diminishing the effectiveness
of a chief executive's
management, and weakening management must be avoided at all costs.
<BR>

<P>
This means the chief executive should be spokesman for the company,
in charge of its day-to-day operations and its dealings with all
outsiders.  It also implies that the Chairman's
external role will be limited to public visibility at the annual
meeting, where it is strictly necessary for the Chairman to carry
out his or her duty of running the business of the board, or where
he or she acts at the express request of the chief executive.
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Making sure that information flows<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
To run the business of the board, the Chairman must never be surprised
by developments in the company's
business or operations.  This suggests intimate, ongoing dealings
between the Chief Executive and the Chairman.  In some cases,
this may mean daily communications by telephone.  In all cases,
such informed discussions must be supplemented by agreed information
flows and briefings.<BR>

<P>
The Chairman, as with any member of the board, needs relatively
open access to senior management but absent extraordinary circumstances
this access should tend to be exercised at the request -- or with
the knowledge of -- the Chief Executive; to do otherwise could
be destabilising.  This means a Chairman should not, except in
extraordinary circumstances, have direct dealings with senior
management behind the back of the Chief Executive.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>Meetings of the board<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
Since it is the Chairman's
job to run the business of the board, the form and substance of
board meetings are his responsibility.  The Chairman should set
the board agenda.  This is pivotal to splitting the two roles
-- a CEO who also acts as Chairman can avoid issues, simply by
keeping them off the agenda.<BR>

<P>
The Chairman must ensure that the board agenda is properly paced,
with an appropriate split between strategy and monitoring how
successful management has been in achieving that strategy.  The
board should previously have set benchmarks against which to measure
whether objectives have been met.<BR>

<P>
All of this suggests that a properly functioning Chairman/Chief
Executive partnership will imply that there will always be discussions
(and probably meetings) concerning the nature, process and content
of board meetings including the quality, nature and timing of
information flow to the board in advance of scheduled meetings.
 The Chairman should also participate in dress rehearsals of board
and annual meetings, which should be held sufficiently in advance
of such meetings to permit necessary changes.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>Assessing management<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
The board must establish an effective management review process.
 Given the board's responsibility
to ensure that the corporation has good management, an attentive
Chairman will want to ensure that the board spends appropriate
time in assessing and determining what management should accomplish
over time.  This will require detailed interaction between the
Chairman and Chief Executive.  Once the board has determined what
management needs to accomplish and sets a time frame, it will
be responsible, under the Chairman's
leadership, for establishing benchmarks against which management's
success in achieving its agreed objectives can be measured.<BR>

<P>
The Chairman and Chief Executive may also wish to agree on the
selection of senior management to attend at board meetings, to
serve as 'resource
persons', available
to the Chief Executive to help him give board members a better
working knowledge of the Corporation's
operations.  Management, including the Chief Executive, would
be excluded when the board moved into an in camera session, which
many corporations are scheduling one or two times a year.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>Planning for succession: keeping the board fresh<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
The Chairman has key responsibility for ensuring appropriate succession
planning.  In addition to planning the succession of the Chief
Executive, he will also have the responsibility of facilitating
and ensuring an appropriate succession process for board membership
and, in particular, the Chairmanship.  Consideration should be
given to establishing a formal procedure (perhaps involving outside
directors only) for the appointment of the next Chairman.<BR>

<P>
The Chairman, and not the Chief Executive, should manage the process
for the search and selection of directors for the board. A necessary
part of this process will involve consideration of the terms of
appointment of board members, and how the board can be kept fresh.
 To ensure that the board does not become stale, it may be necessary
to consider limits on service or the mandatory submission of resignation
by any board member who retires from or changes current external
responsibilities, where the holding of that responsibility has
been a consideration in his initial appointment to the board.
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>Splitting the top jobs -- fix or fad<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Proposals to split the functions of Chief Executive and Chairman
have come from many quarters in recent years, with the increasing
focus on Corporate Governance Reform.  In North America, the pattern
of a single unified leadership has prevailed for so long that
some question whether splitting the top jobs is a fad or a fix,
whether the split is truly likely to yield long term benefits
to the functioning of the Board and the overall welfare of the
Corporation.<BR>

<P>
In a recent New York Times article on the subject, splitting the
roles was described as a transitional or temporary remedy for
Corporations with serious structural or financial problems.  The
examples of American Express and K-Mart which quickly reunited
the posts of Chief Executive and Chairman once they had gone through
business crises, were identified.<BR>

<P>
For our part, we believe that North American corporations have
for too long been enthralled with the concept of the single military
leader, unchallenged in his or her management of the corporation.
 The increasing demands of institutional investors and other stakeholders
has fuelled the corporate governance movement.  The belief is
now widespread that there is value in splitting the roles, and
that this reinforces the proper and effective functioning of the
Board.  At General Motors, splitting the top jobs was not -- and
is not seen as -- a fad.  In this, General Motors is clearly showing
the way.  And, as many say, what is good for General Motors is
good for America -- and beyond.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>A Chairman's
Checklist</FONT></B>
<P>
<I><B>Expectations of Chairmen Under the New Model of Corporate
Governance?<BR>
</B></I>
<UL><LI> The Chairman's principal
role is to lead the board in the conduct of its business.  In
today's context an effective
board will be a strong and independent board capable of fulfilling
its corporate, legal and fiduciary duties and responsibilities.
<BR>
<BR><LI> The Chairman must provide leadership to the boards.  A board
will only be as effective as its Chairman wants it to be or is
capable of making it.

<BR><BR><LI> If the Chairman's
and Chief Executive's
roles are separated, each must work with the other with understanding
and respect.  Their separate roles and responsibilities -- running
the board and running the company respectively -- must be tightly
coordinated.  But it should go without saying that the Chairman
(and indeed other board members) must resist the temptation to
become involved in operational management.

<BR><BR><LI> The Chairman is not the Chief Executive's
boss; the board has that responsibility.  However, as a matter
of practice the Chairman is the board member who has the most
direct and intimate contact with the Chief Executive, who in turn
will coordinate his activities and have day-to-day communications
and dealings with the Chairman.

<BR><BR><LI> The Chairman presides over the board's
deliberations and controls their substance.  He must ensure all
relevant and material issues surface at the board level in a timely
manner.

<BR><BR><LI> The Chairman will need to ensure the effective functioning of
the board's sub-committees.
 He should review board committee membership with the full board,
and meet regularly with all board committee Chairman.  He should
see that committees have proper terms of reference and are suitably
and adequately peopled by non-executive directors, with management
present to provide necessary background information and support,
and to carry out any instructions or projects such as additional
research.<BR>

<BR><LI> The Chairman must ensure that there is good information flow
among directors, managers and shareholders.<BR>

<BR><LI> The Chairman must play a leadership role in assessing the board's
performance.  This could perhaps be done by leading the nominating
committee.
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="WNew.pb.gif">

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=right HSPACE=12 VSPACE=10 BORDER=1 SRC="Link3.gif" ALT="McMillan Binch Home Page"></A>
