<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch: What's New: Canadian and U.S. "Cuba" Laws</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif">
<CENTER><H2>Canadian and U.S. "Cuba" Laws:<BR> 
	The Risks of Getting Caught in the Crossfire </H2></CENTER>

<P><DD>		U.S. "Cuba" laws and Canadian countermeasures have created a high risk situation for Canadian companies in general, and for the Canadian subsidiaries of U.S. parents, in particular.  The point-counterpoint escalation of U.S. and Canadian measures relating to trade with Cuba has put many businesses in an almost impossible position where compliance with one country's laws will constitute a violation of the other country's laws.  </P>

<P><DD>		While this conflict can provide interesting insights into the role that foreign policy plays in U.S. trade policy, and brings to the surface long-standing Canadian sensitivities concerning the extraterritorial application of U.S. laws, the practical truth is that it is the members of the Canadian and U.S. business communities that are likely to pay for the politics, as both countries will likely be looking to strict enforcement in order to show constituents that their laws have teeth.   

<P><DD>		While there still are some ways for businesses to legally structure their transactions and communications to avoid getting caught in this crossfire, recent amendments to both countries' laws have narrowed the range of planning possibilities and significantly increased the risk of exposure.

<P><B>THE U.S. LEGISLATION</B>

<P><DD>		The prohibitions and restrictions in the <I>Cuban Democracy Act of 1992 </I>and the <I>Cuban Liberty and Democratic Solidarity (Libertad) Act of 1995 ("Helms-Burton")</I>, expose Canadian companies that carry on business in or with Cuba to liability in the U.S.  The <I>Cuban Democracy Act</I>, re-affirmed by <I>Helms-Burton</I>, prohibits trade between Cuba and the Canadian subsidiaries of U.S. corporations, and provides civil penalties for violations, including fines and the forfeiture of property. <I> Helms-Burton</I> also urges the full enforcement of the <I>Cuban Assets Control Regulations</I> which permit the blacklisting of Canadians who enter into joint ventures with Cuban companies, and the <I>Trading with the Enemy Act</I>, which also provides for criminal and civil penalties.</P>

<P><DD>		<I>Helms-Burton</I> gives U.S. citizens with claims to Cuban property confiscated by the Castro regime the right to sue any person or entity that traffics in confiscated property.  "Traffic" is broadly defined to encompass most business activities involving confiscated property such as carrying on business on confiscated lands.  Treble damages are available where the defendant had prior notice of the ownership claim.  There is, however, no possibility that Canadian courts would allow any such judgment to be enforced against assets in Canada. 

<P><I>Helms-Burton</I> also directs the U.S. government to deny entry to a non-U.S. citizen and his or her spouse, minor child or agent, if the non-U.S. citizen converts or  traffics in confiscated property or is an officer, principal or controlling shareholder of an entity that converts or traffics in confiscated property.

<P><B>CANADIAN LEGISLATION</B>

<P><DD>		Canada's <I>Foreign Extraterritorial Measures (United States) Order, 1992</I> was issued to stop Canadian businesses from complying with the 1992 <I>Cuban Democracy Act</I>.  Under the Order, Canadian corporations are required to report in detail to the Attorney General any directive, intimation of policy or other communication ("foreign directive") received from a person in a position to direct or influence the policies of the Canadian corporation with respect to a U.S. measure involving trade with Cuba.  The Order also prohibits compliance, by act or omission, with any such foreign directive even if compliance was not the only reason for the act or omission.  Therefore, a Canadian company that terminates trade with Cuba for various reasons, only one of which may have been compliance with a foreign directive, risks violating the Order and being exposed to criminal penalties.

<P><DD>		The Order was recently amended to broaden its scope.  It now applies to trade in services and technology, as well as in goods; covers any future U.S. laws, as well as existing laws; expands the definition of "trade or commerce between Canada and Cuba"; encompasses virtually all business entities, as well as their directors, officers, managers and senior employees; and requires that the Attorney General be notified "forthwith" upon the receipt of a foreign directive.

<P><B>CONCERNS</B>

<P><DD>		While Canadian-owned businesses are not likely to be exposed to the "foreign directive" liability in the Canadian Order, their U.S. subsidiaries remain at risk under U.S. laws if the related companies continue to do business with Cuba.  Those at highest risk under the Canadian law are U.S. owned or foreign-owned Canadian subsidiaries where the parent is not aware of the Canadian countermeasures.  For example, a typical scenario would be for a U.S. parent's corporate counsel to tell its international affiliates that dealings with Cuba would expose the parent to U.S. liabilities and direct that all such dealings should cease. This, of course, would run directly contrary to the Canadian Order, and require not only that the subsidiary report the receipt of the communication to Ottawa, but presumably also notify the parent of its refusal to comply with the directive.  That kind of reply might in turn be treated as evidence that exposed the parent to liabilities under the U.S. laws.</P>

<P><DD>		Canadian businesses must now also account for <I>Helms-Burton</I> lawsuits by U.S. citizens in U.S. courts.  Given the political sensitivity of the issue, the large Cuban expatriate population and that country's aggressive plaintiff bar, Canadian entities carrying on business in Cuba that have assets in the U.S. will be at substantial risk.  Furthermore, Canadian citizens who are officers, principals, or controlling shareholders of Canadian businesses may find themselves and their spouses, children and agents denied entry into the U.S.

<P><DD>		Many companies have taken, and will continue to take action to plan their way around or out of this crossfire, but given the likelihood that the next step in this political conflict will likely see both Canada and the U.S. looking for enforcement "examples" instead of taking further symbolic legislative initiatives, there is a very real risk that companies and their directors and officers who are not fully informed about both the U.S. and the Canadian laws will find themselves subject to proceedings in one country or the other.

<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT>March 13, 1996</DIV><BR><BR><CENTER>
