<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch: What's New: Canadian Private Sector Is/It Outsourcing</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>

<P><CENTER><H1>CANADIAN PRIVATE SECTOR<BR>IS/IT OUTSOURCING</H1>
<I>By John Kazanjian, McMillan Binch<BR>
and</BR>
Robert Zahler, Shaw, Pittman, Potts & Trowbridge</I></CENTER>


<P>The business process re-engineering trend has lent momentum to the rising
wave of U.S. private sector IS/IT outsourcing transactions.  The value of these deals
is estimated to be approximately US$10 billion in 1995 - and that number is projected
to double within three years.  This wave is now reaching Canadian shores with major
private sector outsourcing transactions being completed this year in the financial
services and airlines industries, and several other large deals now moving beyond the
planning stages. While IS/IT outsourcing transactions have been, and will continue to
be, relied upon by the cash pressed Canadian public sector - particularly provincial
and municipal governments and agencies -  it is the rapid growth of interest in the
Canadian private sector that is catching attention. </P>


<P>While IS/IT outsourcing transactions can take a variety of forms and cover a
broad range of a company's internal information services (data centre, back office,
client/server, network management), they essentially involve the up-front transfer of
all or part of a company's information services facilities, technology and personnel
to an outsourcing "vendor", and the medium to long term supply of those services back
to the  company by the vendor.  Variations include "co-sourcing" relationships where
the customer takes an equity interest in a special purpose entity providing the
service.  Viewed from a legal perspective, outsourcing contracts are highly complex,
relationship-based arrangements that borrow from elements normally found in asset
purchase agreements, joint venture arrangements, management contracts and technology
licences, and contain lengthy and technical schedules of assets and performance
standards. </P>
<BR>
<H3>Rationale</H3>

<P>The strategic rationale for the customer is to focus on core competencies
and  leave the job of managing information system support functions to such
specialists as ISM (IBM), Bell Sygma, EDS and others whose ability to realize
efficiencies and secure access to new technologies can reduce the company's overall
information services costs and ensure that its IS/IT capabilities are kept
up-to-date.   The financial rationale is to reduce ongoing information service costs,
possibly receive an up-front payment for IS/IT assets, and remove non-income
producing assets from the balance sheet.  Other advantages to the "buy" vs. "make"
alternative include relieving the company of employee responsibilities and related
costs, creating an alliance with a leading information technology company and helping
to redefine the corporate culture to one that is more focussed on doing only what it
does best. </P>

<P>Canadian private sector IS/IT outsourcing is still in an early growth stage,
notwithstanding the strong marketing efforts of a highly capable vendor community. 
But, as  the U.S. experience demonstrated, dramatic market growth occurs only after a
sufficient number of credible customers have been seen to have successfully entered
into these kinds of deals.  It is for this reason that the recent Canadian financial
services and airline transactions are so significant.  The financial services sector
transaction involved the National Bank of Canada outsourcing back office and related
functions. If the U.S. experience that saw banks and insurance companies at the
forefront of IS/IT outsourcing transactions is representative, other Canadian
financial institutions can be expected to build on the National Bank of Canada
experience. </P>
<BR>
<H3>Air Canada</H3>

<P>In the airline transaction, we worked together to represent Air Canada in
what is to date the largest Canadian private sector IS/IT outsourcing transaction. 
In a long and complex negotiation with IBM and DMR, Air Canada transferred over 900
people and most of its, and its Gemini affiliate's, IS/IT systems to a new IBM
subsidiary, Advantis Canada. The transfers involved 2 data centres, private WANs,
LANs, PBX's, terminals, help desks and end-user support and applications maintenance
and development. </P>

<P>At an IS/IT outsourcing conference held by DCI in Toronto last month, Andre
Villeneuve, Manager, Outsourcing Performance Management, of Air Canada detailed his
company's experience and explained how Air Canada approached the negotiation of the
transactions, what it saw as the benefits and success factors, and what, with the
benefit of hindsight, others might see as areas for possible improvement.  He
identified the value of thorough preparation before approaching the negotiation
including understanding and documenting all existing IS/IT costs and system needs. 
Mr. Villeneuve also stressed the importance of taking human resource issues into
account at all stages of the process. </P>
<BR>
<H3>Strategic and Legal Factors</H3>

<P>At the same conference we offered our observations on the strategic and
legal considerations that potential outsourcing customers need to address.  Bob
Zahler addressed the significant level of change going on within the outsourcing
marketplace and the opportunities and risks that this change presents for potential
IS/IT outsourcing customers.  There have been changes in vendors, such as the recent
acquisitions of DMR and SHL System-House,  new and varied product offerings, and new
business structures such as vendor consortiums that need to be factored into a
customer's analysis.  Zahler explained the importance of following a comprehensive
and disciplined process in the face of these changes.  For example, customers should
closely analyze their existing IS/IT facilities and come to a view as to their future
needs well before entering into discussions with potential vendors.  This not only
positions the company for meaningful comparisons of vendor proposals and ultimately
for negotiations, but it also can simplify what many find to be an intrusive and
lengthy vendor due diligence process.  His bottomline observation based on his
extensive U.S. experience was that the successful IT/IS outsourcing transactions were
the ones that identified  the objectives of both vendors and customers early on and
built-in incentives for all parties to achieve their desired aims. </P>
<BR>
<H3>Canadian Legal Issues</H3>

<P>John Kazanjian explained why the relationship component in these contracts
cannot be underestimated given the stresses that will inevitably arise from
unforeseeable future changes in technology, business objectives and the
tax/regulatory landscape during the course of the contract.  No less important is a
fair and effective exit mechanism to preserve customer leverage and to ensure that
intellectual property and related rights can be transferred to another vendor or be
brought back in house on a tax effective functional basis should the relationship not
succeed.  </P>

<P>Kazanjian went on to address the distinct Canadian legal and business issues
that need to be addressed in private sector IS/IT outsourcing transactions. These
include confidentiality, tax (income, GST, PST), employee transfers (seniority,
unions, pensions, benefits, severance, relocation etc.), dispute resolution, software
licensing, intellectual property rights, personal property security interests,
financing arrangements and corporate and management structures, and what many
potential customers may see as unnecessarily lengthy and thorough vendor due
diligence. </P>
<BR>
<H3>Growing Interest</H3>

<P>Canadian private sector IS/IT outsourcing arrangements, particularly in the
information dependent financial services sector, are likely to become far more common
in the coming years. For those considering such transactions, there may be an initial
inclination to work out the terms of a business "partnership" with a highly
experienced vendor and wait until the negotiations are nearing completion before
seeking legal input, and then only to review the vendor's "usual" terms and
conditions.  Such an approach carries very significant risks that could be eliminated
if advice were sought at the conception stages of a possible transaction.  A well
briefed customer will not buy into such "myths" as outsourcing contracts having to be
for the long term, or that a "successful" contract will not need to be referenced on
an ongoing basis by the parties after it is signed. </P>

<P>There are no "garden variety" outsourcing transactions as each must be
tailored to the customer's needs and circumstances, particularly where reliable,
timely and accurate information is business critical.  Potential customers must think
through in advance and position themselves for the negotiation and due diligence
stages, strive to preserve their bargaining leverage and ensure that potential
problem areas are addressed in the contract and not left to be resolved during the
term of the agreement.</P>


<BR>
<H3>About the Authors</H3>

<P>John Kazanuian is a business law partner at McMillan Binch in Toronto. 
Robert Zahler is a business law partner in the Wasington D.C. offices of Shaw,
Pittman, Potts & Trowbridge, a firm with extensive experience in IS/IT outsourcing
transactions.  The authors worked together to represent Air Canada in connection with
the outsourcing of Air Canada's, and its wholly-owned subsidiary Galileo Canada's,
IS/IT functions to Advantis Canada. </P>

