<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="masthead.gif"><P>
<A HREF="../About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="../IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="../Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="../Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="../IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="../Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="../WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
<P><H1> </H1>
<P><TABLE width=100% BORDER=0><TR><TD width=25% VALIGN=TOP>
<IMG border=0 SRC="img00001.gif"></TD>
<TD width=75% VALION=TOP>
<CENTER>100 Sheppard Avenue West, Suite 105
<BR>
North York (Toronto), Canada M2N 1M6

<BR>
(416) 226-6768 FAX 226-6769
<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:copylaw@interlog.com">copylaw@interlog.com</A>
<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.mcgrawhill.ca/copyrightlaw">http://www.mcgrawhill.ca/copyrightlaw</A>
</TD></TR></TABLE><P>
<B>CANADIAN BAR ASSOCIATION (ONT.) MEDIA &amp; COMMUNICATIONS
SECTION</B>
<P>
<B>NOVEMBER 7, 1996 MEETING TOPIC: ALL THE LATEST IN INTERNET
LAW<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>SUMMARY OF PRESENTATION ON COPYRIGHT LAW<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<P>
For the most part, the Canadian copyright law is flexible (and
technology neutral) enough to deal with new media including media
never contemplated by the drafters of the legislation.<BR>
<P>
For example, the 1924 Copyright Act protects computer programs,
CD-ROMs, web sites, and interactive games (case law in the U.S.
states that interactive games meet the requirement of fixation).
And the rules concerning the ownership and duration of copyright
equally pertain to digital works. Further, licensing and contractual
issues can be adapted to the &quot;new technology&quot; fact situations,
and remedies can apply to digital media.<BR>
<P>
In other words, it is not so much the provisions of the Copyright
Act or the cases interpreting them where the Internet and on-line
community are challenging current copyright laws, rather on the
administrative and enforcement side and in contractual relationships
governing copyright works.<BR>
<P>
On the administrative side, the major issue is rights clearances.
A single CD-ROM can store over 650 megabytes of information, roughly
equivalent to 250,000 pages of text. How many copyright works
is that -- hence, the rights clearance nightmare. And a multimedia
developer/producer/publisher requires rights not only to use copyright
works in the multimedia project itself, but because of the end-use
of multimedia works, they may want to sub-license these rights
to end users for such things as on-line use, making hard copies,
interactive use, etc.<BR>
<P>
Rights can be cleared directly from rights holders and often from
copyright collectives and other licensing agencies who represent
them. But do the copyright collectives like SOCAN and CANCOPY
play a role in such clearances? And what about the exceptions
in the Copyright Act and the fair dealing provision -- are they
of help?<BR>
<P>
Perhaps the greatest hurdle which the publisher/developer faces
is the quantity of different copyright works used in a multimedia
new work. For instance, in the first twenty seconds of a CD-ROM,
there may be music, text from a periodical article, graphics such
as a painting or photograph, and clips from a film. The publisher/developer
of the CD-ROM must obtain copyright permission from each of the
appropriate rights holders for each of the necessary rights. Written
material must be cleared from the author, publisher (newspaper
or periodical), or possibly from a reprography (copyright) collective.
For music, three different rights must be cleared, the reproduction
right, the synchronization right (combining music with visuals)
and the right to publicly perform the music. Further, rights must
be cleared for the graphics and use of the film clips.<BR>
<P>
Moral rights are also an important issue in digital works because
such works can be so easily manipulated.<BR>
<P>
Although the law guides publishers/developers as to when they
need to clear copyright permission, they nonetheless face a number
of administrative problems. For instance, they have to contact
every copyright holder or his or her representative to obtain
copyright permission. This can be time-consuming in sending out
letters, faxes, making phone calls, etc., and copyright holders
may not reply as quickly as the publisher/developer may need and
can stall the progress of a project. Also, it is costly in obtaining
all of these rights and confusing as industry standards regarding
the details of licensing works to be used in an electronic format
and fair compensation to copyright holders have not yet been established.
<BR>
<P>
Once cleared, there are a number of licensing issues to consider,
and then the issue of policing of copyright works on the 'net.
<BR>
<P>
Another important question in this area is who is responsible
for works on the 'net that infringe copyright -- the publisher/developer
of the website, the distributor (e.g., internet service provider)
or the consumer who uses the work?<BR>
<P>
Although the Canadian government currently has a copyright bill
in the House of Commons, it does not specifically deal with 'net
issues and the government is waiting until the next phase (at
an undetermined time) to deal with such issues. In the meantime,
a Diplomatic Conference is taking place in early December 1996
where the Canadian government as well as governments around the
world will meet at the World Intellectual Property Organization
(WIPO) in Geneva to deal with copyright law issues as they affect
the internet and other digital media. Depending on the results
of the Conference, international documents may guide us to revising
the Canadian Copyright Act to meet some of the concerns of the
digital age that can be addressed by legislation. And as the digital
media industry matures, we will experience many applications of
copyright law to the newer technology, and industry standards,
for example in the situation of licensing works for digital media,
will also mature.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<I>Lesley Ellen Harris is a Copyright &amp; New Media Lawyer and
author of &quot;Canadian Copyright Law&quot; (2nd ed., 1995, McGraw-Hill
Ryerson -- see <A HREF="http://www.mcgrawhill.ca/copyrightlaw">http://www.mcgrawhill.ca/copyrightlaw</A>.)</I>




<p><img src="tribunal.gif" align=bottom width=498 height=33><P><P>

<p align=right>
