<IMG SRC="AboutH.gif"><BR>

<H2>THE KNOW<I>law</I>&#153; GROUP BREAKS NEW GROUND</H2>

  <BR>
<BR>
Although Doug Barrett is a Toronto lawyer, his typical daily schedule
smacks more of Hollywood than of Bay Street.  On any given morning,
he might be working on an application to the Canadian Radio-Television
and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) for a new television
station license, negotiating the financing and production of a
new Canadian comedy series or representing a Hollywood studio
in its negotiations with the Canadian producer of a children's
television series. <BR>
<BR>
Doug is one of the founding members of McMillan Binch's KNOW<I>law</I>&#153;
Group, a team of lawyers who center their practice around knowledge-based
industries such as media, entertainment, technology and telecommunications.
 The KNOW<I>law</I>&#153; Group was formed in the early '90s when it
became apparent that the firm could best serve its knowledge-based
industry clients with a consolidated, service team made up of
lawyers completely immersed in this expanding world.         
   <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are very much a part of our clients' environment.  We
know the players, the issues, the sensitivities; and we participate
actively on many levels,&quot; says Doug.  &quot;For instance,
Ron Hay, another member of the KNOW<I>law</I>&#153; Group, is the editor
of Binchmarks, our legal column that has appeared for eight years
in Playback, Canada's broadcast and production journal.  We also
sit on many industry boards and travel to events across the country
to meet our clients on their home turf.   The fact that members
of our group worked on 9 of the 20 Canadian feature films in this
September's Toronto International Film Festival is indicative
of our group's deep involvement in our client's industry.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Another reason for the group's success is its ability to work
with client companies who are rapidly changing and branching out
into new ventures.  Notes Diana Cafazzo, another KNOW<I>law</I>&#153;
lawyer, &quot;Our clients often find themselves evolving into
multi-industry concerns as they develop and grow.  A film producer
may move into multi-media or broadcasting or into the music business.
 Our KNOW<I>law</I>&#153; team can help them to cross these bridges successfully.&quot;
     <BR>
<BR>
In fact, the KNOW<I>law</I>&#153; lawyers enjoy the proliferation of
leading edge projects that constantly come their way.  &quot;In
this business, there are no cookie-cutter deals, and there are
few precedents,&quot; reflects Doug.  &quot;Everyday, our job
is to find creative solutions to business or legal problems that
have never been faced before.   That challenge is what really
makes us tick.&quot;       <BR>
  <BR>
