<H2>Information
Services and Technology Outsourcing</H2>

<P>The business process re-engineering trend has resulted in an increase in private-sector information services and technology
outsourcing transactions in the United States in the last three years. These deals are estimated to be worth approximately
US$10 billion in 1995, and that number has been projected to double in the next three years. Information Services/Information
Technology (IS/IT) private-sector outsourcing transactions have also increased in Canada and major outsourcing transactions
were completed in the last year in the financial services and airlines sectors. As well, several other large deals are now
moving beyond the planning stages. While IS/IT outsourcing transactions have been, and will continue to be, relied upon by the
cash-pressed Canadian public sector, it is the rapid growth of Canadian private-sector interest that has become noteworthy.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>What is IS/IT Outsourcing</B></FONT><BR>
Information services and technology outsourcing transactions take a variety of forms and can cover a
broad range of a company's internal information services including data centre, back office, client/server and network
management. Essentially, however, they involve the up-front transfer of all or part of a company's information services
facilities, technology and personnel to an outsourcing vendor and the medium to long-term supply of those services back to the
company by the vendor. Variations include co-sourcing relationships, where the customer takes an equity interest in a special
purpose entity providing the service. Outsourcing contracts are highly complex, relationship-based arrangements that borrow
from elements normally found in asset-purchase agreements, joint-venture arrangements, management contracts and technology
licences, and contain lengthy and technical schedules of assets and performance standards.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Rationale for IS/IT</B></FONT><BR>
The strategic rationale for the customer is to focus on core competencies and leave the job of managing
information system support functions to specialists such as ISM (IBM), CGI, EDS and others whose ability to realize
efficiencies and secure access to new technologies can reduce the company's overall information services costs and ensure that
its IS/IT capabilities are kept up-to-date. The financial rationale is the potentially significant up-front payment for the IS/IT
assets, the removal of non-income producing assets from its balance sheet, and the reduction of ongoing information service
costs. Other advantages to outsourcing include relieving the company of employee responsibilities and related costs, creating
alliances with leading information technology companies, and redefining the corporate culture to one that is more focused on
doing only what the company does best.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>IS/IT Outsourcing Growing in Canada</B></FONT><BR>
Canadian private sector IS/IT outsourcing is still in an early growth stage,
notwithstanding the strong market efforts of a highly capable vendor community. But, as the U.S. experience demonstrated,
dramatic market growth occurs only after a sufficient number of credible customers have been seen to have successfully entered
into such deals. It is probably for this reason that the recent Canadian financial services and airline transactions have been
attracting much attention.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Airline Transaction</B></FONT><BR>
In the airline transaction, McMillan Binch worked with the leading U.S. outsourcing law firm of Shaw
Pittman, representing Air Canada in what is to date the largest Canadian private-sector IS/IT outsourcing transaction. In a
long and complex negotiation with IBM and DMR, Air Canada transferred more than 900 people and most of its, and its Gemini
affiliate's, IS/IT systems to new IBM subsidiary, Advantis Canada. The transfer involved two data centres, private WANs, LANs,
PBXs, terminals, help desks and end-user support and applications maintenance and development.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Financial Services Sector Transaction</B></FONT><BR>
An equally important financial services sector transaction involved the National Bank of
Canada outsourcing its back office and related functions. If the U.S. experience that saw banks and insurance companies at the
forefront of IS/IT outsourcing transactions is representative, other Canadian financial institutions can be expected to build
on the National Bank of Canada initiative.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>IS/IT Outsourcing Conference</B></FONT><BR>
At an IS/IT outsourcing conference which DCI held in Toronto last month, Michael Labont&eacute;, Senior
Vice President of the National Bank of Canada and Andre Villeneuve, Manager, Outsourcing Performance Management of Air Canada
detailed their companies' experiences with these Canadian IS/IT outsourcing deals. They explained how they approached the
negotiation of the transactions, what they saw as the benefits and success factors, and what their experience demonstrated
were areas for improvement.</P>

<P>John Kazanjian of McMillan Binch, speaking at the same conference, provided his observations on how a potential customer who
is approaching a highly complex outsourcing transaction for the first time can help offset the advantages in experience and
bargaining power that the major vendors bring to the table. He explained the importance of the relationship component in these
contracts and identified techniques for addressing, in the contract, unforeseeable but inevitable future changes in
technology, business objectives, and the tax/regulatory landscape.</P>

<P>Equally important is a fair and effective exit mechanism to preserve customer leverage and to ensure that intellectual
property and related rights can be transferred to another vendor or be brought back in-house on a tax-effective functional basis
should the relationship not succeed. While the input of highly experienced U.S. experts can contribute significantly, there
are distinct Canadian legal and business issues that need to be addressed, particularly with respect to confidentiality, tax
(income, GST, PST), employee transfers (seniority, unions, pensions, benefits, severance, relocation, etc.), dispute
resolution, software licensing, intellectual property rights, personal property security interests, financing arrangements and
corporate and management structures, and what many potential customers may see as unnecessary, lengthy and thorough vendor due
diligence.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>IS/IT Outsourcing Arrangements</B></FONT><BR>
Private sector IS/IT outsourcing arrangements, particularly in the information-dependent
financial services sector, are likely to become far more common in Canada in the coming years. For those considering such
transactions, there may be an initial inclination to work out the terms of a business partnership with a highly experienced
vendor and wait until the negotiations are nearing completion before seeking legal input, and then only to review the vendor's
usual terms and conditions. Such an approach carries very significant risks that could be eliminated if advice were sought at
the conception stages of a possible transaction. There are no garden variety outsourcing transactions as each must be tailored
to the customer's needs and circumstances, particularly for financial services industry participants where reliable, timely
and accurate information is critical. Experienced advisers can assist in positioning the company for the negotiation and due
diligence stages, preserving the customer's bargaining leverage, offsetting the customer's relative lack of experience with
key outsourcing agreement protections, and ensuring that potential problem areas are addressed in the contract and not left to
be resolved during the term of the agreement. John Kazanjian 416 865-7071</P>

<H2>More Changes to the Ontario Laws on Powers of Attorney</H2>

<P>The <I>Substitute Decisions Act, 1992 (SDA)</I> was introduced in Ontario in April of 1995. It made profound changes to the law
governing powers of attorney governed by Ontario law or given by persons residing in Ontario or covering assets located in
Ontario. As a result of the introduction of the SDA, most financial institutions revised their forms and the procedures they
followed in connection with powers of attorney.</P>

<P>On November 15, 1995, less than a year after the SDA became law, Ontario's new Government introduced Bill 19 which proposes
further sweeping changes, including changes with respect to the witnessing requirements applicable to powers of attorney. 
These and the other changes proposed by Bill 19 may again require financial institutions to review their forms and procedures.</P>

<P>A Standing Committee is expected to hold public hearings on Bill 19 during the month of February with a view to submitting a
report to the House this spring. Subject to the Standing Committee's report, it is likely that Bill 19 will become law
sometime in late 1996.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><I><B>Carmen Th&eacute;riault</B> &nbsp;416 865-7129</I></P><BR>

<H2>Proposed OSC Rule Assists Pledges<BR>of Public Company Securities</H2>

<P>The Ontario Securities Commission published notice on October 20, 1995 of a proposed rule which, if implemented, will assist
persons who take pledges of public company securities. At present there is uncertainty about the ability of a pledgee to sell
pledged securities if the securities are part of block of securities which together affect control of a public company. Sales
of control blocks of securities can only be made in reliance on a prospectus or a prospectus exemption. Sellers usually rely
on the prospectus exemption which permits such sales if certain conditions are met including if the <I>seller</I> has held the
securities for at least six months. However, in the context of a security arrangement, the issue is who is the seller: the
borrower who pledged the securities or the pledgee? There is also some uncertainty about when a pledgee of a block of 10% or
more of securities of a public company must issue an "early warning report" on the pledgee's power to exercise control or
direction over the pledged securities. The issue is: must the report be issued at the time of default or when the pledgee
registers the securities in its own name? The Proposed Rule seeks to clarify these issues. But a financial institution may
need to amend its pledge agreement to take advantage of some of the clarifications.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Realizations</B></FONT><BR>
The Proposed Rule provides that the prospectus exemption available to a pledgee on the sale of securities pledged
from the control block of a public company will be available so long as the securities have been held by the pledgor or the
pledgee or a combination of them in the aggregate for six months from the date the securities were acquired by the pledgor.
The exemption is available irrespective of additional acquisitions of securities of the same class by the pledgee unless the
pledgee has acquired securities of the same class under a prospectus exemption after deciding to dispose of the securities.
The pledgee may take pledges of additional securities of the same class without offending the provision restricting further
acquisitions.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Early Warning Reports</B></FONT><BR>
Ontario securities legislation requires persons who acquire ownership of, or the power to exercise
control or direction over, voting or equity securities of a public company that, together with the securities already held by
the person, would constitute 10% or more of the outstanding securities of that class to make public disclosure of the
acquisition (an early warning report). Depending on the terms of the pledge agreement, an early warning report may technically
be required on default. However, many financial institution pledgees have declined to make an early warning report in respect
of pledged securities until the securities are registered in the name of the pledgee (or its nominee) following default and
the pledgee has taken steps to realize on the securities (for example, by sending out notices of its rights to dispose of the
pledged shares in accordance with the PPSA).</P>

The Proposed Rule provides that, where a pledgee has the power to exercise control or direction over securities of a public
company pledged from a control block under a written pledge agreement and in the ordinary course of the pledgee's business,
the pledgee is exempt from the requirement to make an early warning report until the earlier of the time when the pledgee has:
<OL TYPE="a">
<LI>formally declared a default and determined that the power to vote or direct the voting or to dispose or direct
the disposition of the securities will be exercised; and<BR><BR>

<LI>determined that the power to dispose or to direct the disposition of the securities will be exercised because
the pledgee believes the securities have depreciated in value.<BR>
</UL>
This exemption from early warning reporting is only available if the pledge agreement:
<OL TYPE="a">
<LI>was not entered into with the purpose or with the effect of changing or materially affecting the control of
the issuer of the pledged securities; and<BR><BR>

<LI>unless entered into on or before March 31, 1996 (assuming the Proposed Rule is finalized on schedule) does not grant
the pledgee before default the power to vote or direct the voting of the pledged securities or the power to dispose or
direct the disposition of the pledged securities (except where they have depreciated in value).
</UL>
<P>Assuming that the Proposed Rule will be finalized on schedule (or even if finalization is delayed), financial institutions
should review their pledge agreements to ensure that they will contain the terms described above after March 31, 1996 (or
later date specified) so that the financial institutions can take advantage of this clarification of the early warning
requirement.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><I><B>Margaret C. McNee</B> &nbsp;416 865-7284</I></P>

<CITE>Proposed Rule under the Securities Act (Ontario) "Early Warning System and Related Take-Over Bid, Insider Trading and Control
Block Distribution Issues" (1995) 18 OSCB 4887.</CITE><BR><BR><BR>

<H2>Class Actions Against Financial Institutions:<BR>Maintaining the Institution's Defences.<BR>Examples From Early Warning Report</H2>

The <I>Class Proceedings Act</I> (CPA) became law in Ontario in January of 1993. Since that time, the CPA has been used in
actions involving breast implants and HIV transmitted through blood to permit a small number of persons to bring actions on
behalf of many other persons with similar claims. Recently, the CPA has been used by investors in a law suit against a
financial institution that provided financing to a failed construction project. McMillan Binch acted on behalf of the
financial institution in a precedent setting motion to divide the investors into subclasses of plaintiffs. The division into
subclasses was based on the facts relating to the different legal claims made by the investors against the financial
institution. The advantage of having divided the plaintiffs into subclasses is that the financial institution can now better
defend against the investors' claims.

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>The CPA</B></FONT><BR>
The CPA creates a procedural regime which enables persons to sue as a "class" (where one or more persons sue on behalf
of numerous persons having a similar or common interest). If an action is certified under the CPA as a class proceeding, one
or a small number of persons are designated as the representative plaintiff(s). Usually only the representative plaintiff(s)
will be actively involved in the litigation from that time forward. This reduction in the number of active plaintiffs
effectively reduces the costs of litigation for all plaintiffs. However, a class proceeding can oversimplify a case by
preventing a full examination of defences which may apply to members of the class other than the representative plaintiff(s).

<P><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Decertification and Division into Subclasses under the CPA</FONT></B><BR>
In a law suit that is initially certified as a class proceeding,
any defendant can later ask the court to decertify the proceeding, or divide the plaintiffs into smaller groups of subclasses.
McMillan Binch recently brought the first decertification motion under the CPA on behalf of one of its financial institution
clients.</P>

<P>The financial institution and others were sued by over 150 investors in a construction project. The investors were represented
in the class action by three representative plaintiffs. The allegations made against the financial institution included breach
of contract, misrepresentation, breach of fiduciary duty and breach of trust. In view of the many individual factual and legal
issues raised by these allegations, McMillan Binch asked the court to decertify the proceeding or divide the group of
plaintiffs into more meaningful subclasses.</P>

<P>In the first decision of its kind, the court did not decertify the action but instead divided the plaintiffs into 15
subclasses based in part upon the various legal and factual defences available to the financial institution. In doing so, the
court observed that the objectives of the CPA should not be permitted to override the ultimate goal of a just determination of
the issues between the parties. The financial institution will now be able to examine for discovery the representative
plaintiff(s) of each subclass, and raise defences in a way which would not have been possible if the court had permitted the
investors to advance their claims through only three representative plaintiffs.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><I><B>W. Brad Hanna &nbsp;</B>416 865-7276</I></P>

