<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 ALIGN=left SRC="PrintH.gif"><BR><BR><A HREF="#FOOT"><IMG HSPACE=10 BORDER=1 SRC="FootBut.gif" ALIGN=right></A>
<BR CLEAR=all><CENTER>
<H1>Competition Law Bulletin</H1>

<H2>Unilateral Minimum Advertised Price Programs</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>Unilateral Minimum Advertised Price Programs ("UMAPs") have recently been explored by a number
of firms in the United States.  This bulletin discusses the legality of UMAPs in Canada, legal
alternatives for achieving the underlying business objectives, and related Canada-U.S. cross-border
considerations.</P><BR>

<H2>BACKGROUND</H2>

Many manufacturers have been revising distribution channel strategies in recent years in
response to the emergence of powerful warehouse and category killer chains. UMAPs are one of several
responses by manufacturers to increasingly sophisticated and powerful resellers.  

<BLOCKQUOTE>A typical UMAP has three fundamental elements:
<UL>
<LI>The manufacturer will refuse to sell products covered by the UMAP to resellers which advertise
the product for sale at less than a minimum advertised price established by the manufacturer.
<BR><BR>
<LI>The manufacturer will not enter into any negotiations or discussions with resellers regarding
the UMAP or violations thereof.
<BR><BR>
<LI>The reseller will remain free to establish its own selling prices, which may be above or below
the minimum advertised price.
</UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<H2>CANADIAN LEGAL FRAMEWORK</H2>

<P>The main legal issue raised by the UMAP concept in Canada is compliance with the price
maintenance rules in the <I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp;.<A NAME="1A"><A HREF="#1"><SUP>1</SUP></A></A>  Price maintenance is one of the areas in which there are
important differences between Canadian and foreign competition laws.  It is a criminal provision of
the <I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp; with two main branches, each of which is potentially applicable to a UMAP:
<FONT SIZE="-1">
<BLOCKQUOTE>61(1)No person who is engaged in the business of producing or supplying a product, ... shall,
directly or indirectly,
<OL TYPE="a">
<LI>by agreement, threat, promise or any like means, attempt to influence upward, or to
discourage the reduction of, the price at which any other person engaged in business in Canada
supplies or offers to supply or advertises a product within Canada; or
<BR><BR>
<LI>refuse to supply a product to or otherwise discriminate against any other person engaged in
business in Canada because of the low pricing policy of that other person.
</OL></BLOCKQUOTE></P></FONT>
<P>We preface the discussion of the two branches with an overview of the penalties and enforcement
practices applicable to this offence, and conclude by reviewing possible defences.</P>

<H3>Penalties and Enforcement</H3>

<P>Price maintenance is a provision of the <I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp; which is enforced actively by the
competition authorities - particularly when complaints are brought to their attention, as often
occurs when a supplier terminates a relationship with a reseller.  The maximum penalty is a fine in
the discretion of the court (no maximum) and/or five years' imprisonment.  Parties injured by price
maintenance activity also have standing to bring a civil action for damages (single, not treble as in
the U.S.), regardless of whether a criminal prosecution has occurred.</P>

<P>Corporate fines in high profile price maintenance cases have been in the $100,000-$250,000
(Cdn.) range.  However, in recent years the Canadian competition authorities have been attempting to
obtain higher fines for competition law offences in order to enhance deterrence.  They have, for the
same reason, increasingly been charging individual executives in addition to corporations.  In a
recent price maintenance case in the real estate industry, two executives were fined a total of
$30,000 (Cdn.).<A NAME="2A"><A HREF="#2"><SUP>2</SUP></A></A></P>

<H3>Attempting to Influence</H3>

The "attempting to influence" branch of the price maintenance offence involves the use of
certain prohibited methods to attempt to achieve a specific type of anti-competitive effect -
influencing a reseller to raise, or refrain from lowering, its prices.  The offence explicitly
applies to advertised as well as selling prices.

<H3><I>Prohibited Methods</I></H3>

<P>The prohibited methods of attempting to influence a reseller's pricing are agreements, threats,
promises and "any like means."  The phrase "any like means" has been given a narrow interpretation by
the courts.<A NAME="3A"><A HREF="#3"><SUP>3</SUP></A></A>  Moreover, if a UMAP is indeed administered unilaterally - and is not incorporated by
reference as a term of a manufacturer's contracts with its resellers (eg. through a general clause
requiring the reseller to comply with standard terms and conditions established by the manufacturer)
- then there may not be any "agreement".<A NAME="4A"><A HREF="#4"><SUP>4</SUP></A></A>  However, Canadian competition authorities and courts would
almost certainly perceive a UMAP as implying either a threat or a promise.  The clear threat is that
the reseller will immediately be cut off if it reduces advertised prices below the minimum price
specified by the manufacturer.<A NAME="5A"><A HREF="#5"><SUP>5</SUP></A></A>  The implicit promise is that the reseller will continue to be
supplied by the manufacturer if advertised prices remain at or above the specified level.</P>

<P>Section 61(3) of the <I>Act</I>&nbsp; contains a reverse onus provision which confirms the sensitive nature
of manufacturer communications to resellers about their pricing:
<FONT SIZE="-1">
<BLOCKQUOTE>61(3)  For the purposes of this section, a suggestion by a producer or supplier of a product of a
resale price or minimum resale price in respect thereof, however arrived at, is, in the absence of
proof that the person making the suggestion, in so doing, also made it clear to the person to whom
the suggestion was made that he was under no obligation to accept the suggestion and would in no way
suffer in his business relations with the person making the suggestion or with any other person if he
failed to accept the suggestion, proof of an attempt to influence the person to whom the suggestion
is made in accordance with the suggestion.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT></P>

<P>In the UMAPs we have seen, the manufacturer would be doing more than making a "suggestion" - a
reseller would clearly "suffer in his business relations" by not accepting the minimum advertised
price.</P>

<H3><I>Anti-Competitive Effects</I></H3>

<P>The price maintenance offence is intended to prevent manufacturers from putting upward pressure
on resellers' advertised or selling prices.  However, it is not necessary that any such effects occur
or be proved - it is the <B>attempt</B> to do so which constitutes the offence.  Similarly, no actual injury
to competition need be shown - it is essentially a <I>"per se"</I>&nbsp; offence.  Pro-competitive or
efficiency-enhancing effects are not considered.</P>

<P><I>R. v. Epson Canada Ltd.</I>&nbsp; is a noteworthy illustration.<A NAME="6A"><A HREF="#6"><SUP>6</SUP></A></A>  Epson was charged with price
maintenance after inserting a clause into its standard dealer agreements which prohibited advertising
of (but not sales at) prices below Epson's suggested retail price.  Epson argued that the policy was
necessary because its products required high pre-sale service which would not be provided by full
service dealers unless they were shielded from the advertising of discounted prices by other dealers.
 An economic expert testified about the efficiency-enhancing rationale for such a policy (<I>eg.</I>,
avoiding free rider problems). Nevertheless, the court concluded that the offence was committed by
the insertion of the clause into the dealer agreements and that possible beneficial marketplace
effects were not a defence.</P>

<P>The likely practical effect of imposing a UMAP on resellers will be to discourage them from
reducing their advertised prices below the minimum advertised price specified by the manufacturer. 
Moreover, many Canadian resellers with aggressive pricing policies are familiar with section 61 of
the <I>Act</I>&nbsp;.  Thus there is a real possibility that complaints would be made to the competition
authorities.</P>

<H3><I>Intent</I>&nbsp;</H3>

<P>Under Canadian law, persons may be presumed to have intended the likely consequences of their
actions, and intent may be inferred from circumstantial evidence. Absent compelling internal
documentation of some other business rationale for a UMAP, Canadian competition authorities and
courts would almost certainly conclude that such a program was an attempt to discourage resellers
from lowering advertised prices below the levels prescribed by the manufacturer.</P>

<H3>Refusal to Supply</H3>

<P>The "refusal to supply" branch of the price maintenance offence applies where a current or
potential customer is refused supply (or otherwise discriminated against) because of its "low pricing
policy."  As with the "attempting to influence" branch, intent is required but anti-competitive
effects in the marketplace need not be shown.   </P>

<P>The adoption of a UMAP arguably does not involve any discrimination if the program applies
equally to all resellers of the manufacturer's products.  However, any termination of a reseller (or
other discriminatory action short of termination, such as denying a cooperative advertising
reimbursements) for violation of a UMAP would be illegal unless it was based on something other than
the "low pricing policy" of the reseller.<A NAME="7A"><A HREF="#7"><SUP>7</SUP></A></A></P>

<P>Terminations of business relationships may, of course, be initiated for valid commercial
reasons;  however, such commercial reasons cannot be used as a pretext for terminations which are in
fact motivated by concerns about a reseller's low pricing.</P>

<H3>Defences</H3>

<P>The <I>Act</I>&nbsp; provides limited defences for affiliated entities and principal-agent situations. 
These will generally not be applicable to UMAPs.</P>

<P>The <I>Act</I>&nbsp; also contains partial defences in situations where a reseller appears to be engaging in
loss-leadering, bait-and-switch selling or misleading advertising of the manufacturer's products, or
not providing the level of servicing that purchasers of the products might reasonably expect.  While
these provisions might become relevant in dealings with specific resellers, they do not provide a
general basis for validating a UMAP.</P>

<H3>Summary</H3>

<P>There is a high risk that Canadian competition authorities and courts would conclude that the
adoption of a UMAP contravenes the attempting to influence branch of the price maintenance offence
(section 61(1)(a) of the <I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp;).  In addition, there is a high risk that any reliance upon
a UMAP to terminate an individual reseller would be found by the competition authorities and courts
to be a violation of the refusal to supply branch of the offence (section 61(1)(b) of the <I>Act</I>&nbsp;).</P>
<BR>

<H2>ALTERNATIVE APPROACHES</H2>

<P>The Canadian price maintenance law has broad application and limited flexibility.  Thus, there
are no obvious minor modifications to a UMAP which would ensure compliance with section 61 of the
<I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp;.  However, there may be other appropriate legal strategies available to achieve a
manufacturer's underlying business objectives.  These include:  using the <I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp; to resist
pressure from competing resellers; agency or consignment selling; alternative advertising strategies;
and, at the broadest level, other approaches for increasing reseller profitability.</P>

<H3>Resisting Reseller Pressure</H3>

<P>Complaints from resellers about the advertised prices of their competitors are often the
trigger which prompts a manufacturer to seek to exert some influence over downstream prices.  In
Canada, one possible response is to rely on the broad wording of section 61(1) of the <I>Act</I>&nbsp; as the
reason that the manufacturer is not legally able to take the requested action.  In addition, a
manufacturer may wish to consider reminding insistent resellers that they may be committing an
offence:
<FONT SIZE="-1">
<BLOCKQUOTE>61(6) No person shall, by threat, promise or any like means, attempt to induce a supplier, whether
within or outside Canada, as a condition of his doing business with the supplier, to refuse to supply
a product to a particular person or class of persons because of the low pricing policy of that person
or class of persons.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT></P>

<P>In short, both manufacturer and reseller have a common interest in avoiding the legal exposure
involved in attempting to discipline price-aggressive competing resellers.</P>

<H3>Agency or Consignment Selling</H3>

<P>It is possible for a manufacturer to control downstream selling and advertised prices by
supplying its products to distribution channel participants on an agency or consignment basis.  As
mentioned above, principal-agent relationships are specifically exempted from the criminal price
maintenance rules.<A NAME="8A"><A HREF="#8"><SUP>8</SUP></A></A>  While consignment selling is a non-criminal "reviewable practice" under the
<I>Act</I>&nbsp;,<A NAME="9A"><A HREF="#9"><SUP>9</SUP></A></A> such practices are entirely legal unless and until prohibited by an order of the Competition
Tribunal (which may only be made if specified anti-competitive effects are established). 
Notwithstanding the greater scope for control of resale prices using these distribution strategies,
they also raise other commercial and legal issues which need to be carefully assessed in any specific
situation.</P>

<H3>Advertising Strategies</H3>

<P>Conditioning cooperative advertising allowances on compliance with minimum selling or
advertised prices runs a high risk of violating the price maintenance rules in the <I>Act</I>&nbsp;.<A NAME="10A"><A HREF="#10"><SUP>10</SUP></A></A>  A
cooperative advertising program which prohibited any references to prices in advertisements funded in
part by the supplier could also raise issues under the price maintenance provisions of the <I>Act</I>&nbsp;. 
However, informal communications with the competition authorities suggest there may be some room for
flexibility in this area.</P>

<P>A further alternative would be to reduce or eliminate cooperative advertising and spend such
funds on direct advertising instead.  A manufacturer may safely refer to suggested retail prices in
its own advertisements, provided it is made clear that individual resellers may sell for less.<A NAME="11A"><A HREF="#11"><SUP>11</SUP></A></A> 
However, it would be necessary to consider the effectiveness and cost of direct manufacturer
advertising relative to cooperative advertising initiated by various resellers in their local market
areas.  Moreover, this approach would not prevent resellers from advertising lower prices on their
own.</P>

<H3>Other Approaches for Increasing Reseller Profitability</H3>

<P>Addressing reseller concerns over profitability is often said to be the underlying rationale
for a UMAP.  This presumably is of concern to a manufacturer because resellers' satisfaction and
motivation affect the manufacturer's sales and profits.  From a general marketing strategy
perspective, there are numerous variables which a manufacturer can use to influence reseller
profitability.  These include the number and types of direct and indirect channel members it sells
to, the prices charged to such resellers, cooperative advertising and other marketing support
programs, etc.</P><BR>


<H2>RELATED ISSUES</H2>

<P>Manufacturers selling into the Canadian market should be aware of two possible cross-border
implications of adopting a UMAP in the United States.</P>

<H3>"Spillover" Offences</H3>

<P>Many U.S. resellers have Canadian operations or are trans-shipping into Canada.  If a UMAP is
applied to such resellers' Canadian as well as U.S. activities, it is possible that the Canadian
competition authorities and courts would consider the <I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp; to have been violated.<A NAME="12A"><A HREF="#12"><SUP>12</SUP></A></A>  To
safeguard against this possibility, manufacturers should:

<UL>
<LI>consider including a provision in the UMAP documentation which explicitly states that the
policy is not applicable to resellers' Canadian sales; and
<BR><BR>
<LI>develop appropriate control systems and procedures to ensure that the UMAP is not enforced
against the Canadian activities of U.S. resellers.
</UL></P>
<H3>Enforcement Agency Cooperation</H3>

<P>If a manufacturer decides to implement its U.S. UMAP or a variation thereof in Canada, it
should recognize that the Canadian competition authorities may seek access to relevant documentation
and other evidence located in the United States (<I>eg.</I>&nbsp; regarding the rationale for, development of and
implementation of the UMAP).  If such information was not forthcoming, it is possible that the
Canadian authorities would attempt to enlist the assistance of the U.S. Department of Justice
pursuant to the <I>Canada-United States Mutual Legal Assistance in Criminal Matters Treaty</I>&nbsp;.  Under the
treaty, the two countries' competition law enforcement agencies have broad scope for gathering and
exchanging evidence relevant to possible violations of the criminal provisions of their competition
laws.  (Similarly, should there be a reason for doing so, U.S. enforcement officials could seek
assistance from the Canadian authorities.)</P><BR>

<H2>CONCLUSIONS</H2>

<P>There is a high risk that UMAP's would be found by Canadian competition authorities and courts
to violate the price maintenance rules in the <I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp;.  Minor modifications are unlikely to
reduce materially the legal risks associated with the UMAP concept in Canada.</P>

<P>Alternatives for achieving the business objectives underlying a UMAP include: resisting
reseller pressure, agency or consignment selling, advertising strategies and other approaches for
increasing reseller profitability.
Firms which implement UMAP's in the U.S. should be aware of the possibility that application of
the UMAP to a U.S. reseller's Canadian operations or export sales could violate the Canadian
<I>Competition Act</I>&nbsp;.  Risks in this area are increased by the fact that Canadian and U.S. competition law
authorities have begun routinely assisting each other by gathering and exchanging evidence relevant
to proceedings under each other's criminal competition laws.</P>

<P>Firms with cross-border operations should therefore consider adding a provision to their U.S.
UMAP documentation which clarifies that the policy is not applicable to resellers' Canadian sales. 
In addition, it would be prudent to develop control systems and procedures to ensure that the UMAP is
not enforced against the Canadian activities of U.S. resellers.</P>

<IMG SRC="WNew.pb.gif"></TD></TR>
<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=right HSPACE=12 VSPACE=10 BORDER=1 SRC="Link3.gif"></A>
<BR><BR><BR><BR>
<CENTER>
