<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif">

<H2 ALIGN=center>Toronto Stock Exchange Seeks<BR>Improved Disclosure -<BR>A Search for Balance</H2>
<H4 ALIGN=center>by<BR>J. William Rowley QC</H4>

<P>In mid-December 1995, following a process begun almost a year and a
half before, the Toronto Stock Exchange's Committee on Corporate Disclosure delivered
its interim report on needed initiatives to improve the effectiveness of corporate
disclosure in Canada.</P>

<P>If implemented, company directors, officers and advisers could soon face liability of
$25,000 - it could go much higher - if they issue misleading information about their
company. Companies themselves would be subject to damage claims (capped at $1 million
or 5% of market cap., whichever is greater) for any material misinformation and major
shareholders would be liable to heavy sanctions for knowingly influencing company
officials to release inaccurate information (see box for details). In addition, the
Committee envisions a significantly upgraded disclosure regime with mandatory annual
information form filings at prospectus-level disclosure, and with material change
disclosure being raised to the same standard.</P>

<BR><H3>The TSE Initiative</H3>

<P>The TSE's initiative to establish a Committee to address the issue of continuous
disclosure grew out of complaints from investors, responses to the TSE's regular
surveys of institutions on their confidence in the market, and the experience of the
TSE's own staff in dealing with disclosure issues, all of which revealed a level of
concern about the timeliness and thoroughness of ongoing disclosure by public
companies. Many of these concerns arose when companies were faced with financial
distress or other "bad news" situations.</P>

<P>For the TSE, with its cornerstone policy that all persons investing in securities
listed on the Exchange should have equal access to information, the fundamental issue
was whether there are practical and cost-efficient ways to improve continuous
disclosure that will increase the credibility of the TSE market?</P>

<P>Continuous disclosure is defined by the Committee to include all documents that public
companies are required to send to their shareholders, documents that they are required
to file with securities regulators, documents that they voluntarily send to their
shareholders and oral statements. All of these documents and statements inform markets
and constitute a continuous flow of information about the company to investors.</P>

<BR><H3>Committee's Process</H3>

<P>The interim report follows a consultative process which included commissioned surveys,
multiple hearings, and a myriad of briefs and presentations from members of the
financial community, including its regulators, in Canada, the United States and the
United Kingdom.</P>

<P>As part of the process retail investors were asked for their opinion of the timeliness
of disclosure. Nearly 70% indicated that they believed that companies release positive
information in a timely manner almost all or most of the time. Their opinion as to the
timely release of negative information differed markedly. More than 65% indicated that
companies release negative information in a timely manner only some of the time or
almost never. Only 3% believed that negative information is released in a timely manner
almost all the time. Nearly 90% of the analysts surveyed responded that disclosure was
better in the United States.</P>

<BR><H3>Underlying Conclusions of the Committee</H3>

<P>In its interim report, the Committee states its belief not only that there is a
perception that problems exist with the adequacy of disclosure, but that there is
evidence of a significant number of incidents of non-compliance with disclosure
requirements. Its fundamental conclusions, upon which its extensive set of
recommendations are based, are:
<UL>
<LI>There is a sufficient degree of non-compliance with the current continuous
disclosure rules in Canada to cause concern.
<BR><BR><LI>The current sanctions and funding available to regulators charged with the task of
monitoring and enforcing compliance with Canada's continuous disclosure rules are
inadequate.
<BR><BR><LI>The remedies available to investors in secondary trading markets who are injured by
misleading disclosure are so difficul to pursue and to establish that they are, as a
practical matter, largely academic.
<BR><BR><LI>Civil liability should attach to issuers and others for their continuous disclosure
to investors in secondary markets, subject to reasonable limitations.
<BR><BR><LI>In designing recommendations for improvement in disclosure, the balance should be
struck in favour of strengthened deterrence rather than creating a route to meaningful
compensation of injured investors. The belief of the majority was that effective
deterrence should reduce the need for investor compensation.

<BR><BR><LI>The rules by which class actions are conducted in those provinces where class
actions are permitted are sufficiently different from those in the United States. There
is no practical risk that the establishment of statutory civil liability in Canada will
give rise to "strike suit" litigation in Canada comparable to that in the United
States.

<BR><BR><LI>The cost to Canada's capital markets of implementing the Committee's
recommendations, while impossible to quantify, was felt to be warranted and will be at
least counter-balanced by the gains arising from enhanced credibility of disclosure by
issuers accessing Canada's capital markets, and their resulting reduced cost of
capital. Providing full, accurate and timely information to the investment community is
an acceptable cost of accessing one of the world's most efficient capital markets.
</UL>

<BR><H3>Next Steps, Future Actions</H3>

<P>In embarking on the direction it took, the Committee was frank enough to admit that
concerns from issuers - legitimate concerns - were to be expected.
Nevertheless, because of what it viewed to be a material degree of non-compliance, it
concluded that a new deterrence based model, with penalties large enough to get
corporate Canada's attention, was warranted.</P>

<P>In issuing the interim report, the TSE's Board of Governors has not adopted a position
on the merits of either the conclusions reached or the recommendations made by the
Committee. Like the Committee itself, the immediate objective is to stimulate informed
debate and reaction. The interim report is open for comment until late Spring
(originally until March, but now extended at least until April) when Committee members
will begin preparing a final version to be ready for summer.</P>

<BR><H3>Comparisons with the United States</H3>

<P>Interestingly, the TSE Committee's recommendations that civil liability should be
broadened for continuous disclosure breaches were made public less than two weeks
before passage by the U.S. Congress of contrversial legislation designed to reduce the
mountain of frivolous securities litigation which had become a feature of the U.S.
corporate landscape.</P>

<P>Vetoed by President Clinton, who was overridden by both the House and the Senate, the
Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995 is part of the "common sense"
law reforms which were included in the Republican's Contract with America.
Opponents of the law, including President Clinton, fear that it goes too far and will
immunize corporate America against making false statements designed to bolster stock
prices and protect corporate officers employment.</P>

<P>Its proponents regard the Act as an essential constraint in the face of abusive
contingent fee class actions (so-called "strike suits") which are often filed within
hours of a drop in a company's stock price and are based on the fact that corporate
predictions have not been realized. The main features of the new law are:
<UL>
<LI>creation of a safe harbour for forward-looking statements, which must be labelled
expressly and accompanied by "meaningful cautionary statements" identifying important
factors that could cause actual results to differ materially;
<BR><BR><LI>class action procedure reforms, including tough plaintiff certification
requirements and restrictions on professional plaintiffs;
<BR><BR><LI>where fraud is alleged, a requirement for plaintiffs to plead specific facts which
give rise to a strong inference of fraudulent intent;
<BR><BR><LI>replacement of the old joint and several liability rule with "fair share"
proportionate liability for non-knowing breaches of the securities laws; and
<BR><BR><LI>a two-way cost rule, requiring the losing plaintiff to pay the defendant's costs if
a suit is found to have been frivolous - a daunting risk to contingent fee counsel and
nominal plaintiffs.
</UL></P>
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>THE RECOMMENDATIONS</H2></CENTER>
<BR><H3>A Statutory Civil Liability Scheme</H3>

1. &nbsp; Who should have a cause of action?
<UL><LI>any person who acquires or disposes of a security of an issuer in a secondary
market transaction during the period between the date when misleading disclosure was
made and the date when it was corrected, or, in the case of untimely disclosure,
between the date when the disclosure ought to have been made and the date when it was
in fact made.</UL>

2. &nbsp; What disclsure should companies be liable for?
<UL><LI>all documents filed, or required to be filed, with a Securities Regulatory
Authority (an "SRA");
<BR><BR><LI>any other document, such as a press release, voluntarily issued by the company, the
contents of which may reasonably be foreseen as likely to affect the market price of a
security;
<BR><BR><LI>any statement, made by a person with actual, implied or apparent authority to speak
on behalf of a company, made publicly, or privately under circumstances where the
making of such statement might reasonably be foreseen as likely to affect the market
price of a security; and 
<BR><BR><LI>any statement made by a controlling person, promoter or director or officer of the
controlling person or promoter, about a corporation with respect to which the
controlling or promoting relationship exists.
</UL>
3. &nbsp; Should the general level of disclosure be improved?
<UL>
<LI>Yes. All public companies should be obliged to file annually an Annual Information
Form ("AIF") that meets prospectus disclosure standards.
<BR><BR><LI>Material change disclosure should also be upgraded to prospectus disclosure
standards.
</UL><DL><DT>
4. &nbsp; Who should be liable for misleading disclosure<DD>(disclosure that is late, or that
contains a misrepresentation)?</DL>
<UL>
<LI>the issuer;
<BR><BR><LI>each director of the issuer;
<BR><BR><LI>the CEO of the issuer;
<BR><BR><LI>any other officer of the issuer who actively participates in the decision to
publish the disclosure, or in the preparation of the portion of the disclosure
containing the misrepresentation, or in the decision to delay disclosure beyond the
time when it should have been published;
<BR><BR><LI>
any officer of he issuer who, because of such person's position with the issuer, should
reasonably have been expected to have actively participated in such decision or
preparation;
<BR><BR><LI>any controlling person or promoter, or director or officer of a controlling person
or promoter, who knowingly influenced the issuer, or any of its directors or officers
(a) to publish the disclosure in question and who was also aware, or ought reasonably
to have been aware, that the disclosure in question contained a misrepresentation; or
(b) to delay publishing the disclosure in question beyond the time when it ought to
have been published and who was aware, or ought reasonably to have been aware, that the
delay caused the disclosure to be made later than it should have been made;
<BR><BR><LI>
experts, with respect to reports, opinions or statements attributed to them; and
<BR><BR><LI>
influential persons, that is, any director or officer of a controlling person or
promoter who makes disclosure containing a misrepresentation, or any controlling person
or promoter (if the person who made the misrepresentation was a director or officer of
the controlling person or promoter and another director or officer thereof authorized
or acquiesced in the misrepresentation) and any director or officer of the issuer,
controlling person or promoter who authorized or acquiesced in the
misrepresentation.
</UL>
5. &nbsp; What should the nature of the liability be?
<UL>
<LI>Liability should not be joint and several but should be in proportion to the
relative fault of each defendant.
<BR><BR><LI>However, any defendant who knowingly was responsible for a misrepresentation or
delay would be jointly and severally liable with all other such defendants.
</UL>
6. &nbsp; What should the burden of proof be and what defences should be available?
<UL>
<LI>Plaintiffs should not be obliged to prove that they read the misrepresentation or
that they relied upon the misrepresentation in making their investment decision.
Reliance should be deemed to have occurred. With respect to delayed disclosure,
reliance upon the continuous disclosure record being up to date should also be deemed
to have occurred.
<BR><BR><LI>No person, including the issuer, should be liable if that person establishes that the
plaintiff traded with knowledge of the misrepresentation or of the undisclosed
information.
<BR><BR><LI>No person, including the issuer, should be liable if that person satisfies, under all
the circumstances, a "due diligence" defence and if that person was not aware that
there was a misrepresentation or a requirement to disclose the information in question
before it was disclosed.
<BR><BR><LI>No outside director (a director who is not an officer) should be liable for any	
misrepresentation (other than a misrepresentation in core documents - AIF, management
proxy circular, annual and quarterly financial statements, MD&A) or for any delay in
disclosure, unless the director was either aware of the misrepresentation or delay or
was reckless in authorizing or permitting the disclosure or delay to occur.
<BR><BR><LI>No person, other than the issuer, should be liable for any misrepresentation or delay
in disclosure if the document or statement containing the misrepresentation was issued
without his or her knowledge or consent and if, on becoming aware of the
misrepresentation or the delay, the person gave reasonable general notice thereof.
<BR><BR><LI>Experts should have available the same defences, as to expertised portions of
disclosure documents, as they do in connection with expertised parts of a
prospectus.
<BR><BR><LI>These defences go beyond the defences available in connection with prospectus
liability in important respects. First, it is recommended that the due diligence
defence be extended to the issuer. The Committee does not believe that the issuer
should be liable for damages if the officers acted with due diligence. Second, the
Committee does not wish to give rise to a greater degree of outside director
participation in continuous disclosure documents (other than core documents referred to
above). Thus, outside directors should only be held to a recklessness standard for such
documents, not to a due diligence standard.
</UL>
7. &nbsp; Should special provision be made to encourage forward-looking
information?
<UL>
<LI>The Committee believes it is important not to stifle forward-looking information.
Such information will, by its very nature, often prove inaccurate, but if it is
genuinely beleved by management to be a probable prediction of the company's prospects,
liability should not attach to it, provided it is accompanied by cautionary language
and, where the nature of the forward-looking information makes it reasonably
practicable to do so, a sensitivity analysis outlining the effect of variations in key
assumptions.
</UL>
8. &nbsp; How should damages be calculated?
<UL>
<LI>The Committee would not oblige plaintiffs to trade in securities in order to
crystallize the amount of their damages. To do so would place pressure on the buy or
sell side of the market and exacerbate the damages for which defendants are potentially
liable. Accordingly, while plaintiffs are clearly free to trade, their damages would be
limited to the lesser of:
<BR><BR><LI>their actual damages; and
<BR><BR><LI>the difference between the price at which they purchased or sold securities during the
period of misleading disclosure and a "benchmark price" that will be determined as
the weighted average trading price of the securities in question over the ten trading
days after disclosure is corrected, or in such other fashion as a court deems
appropriate in the circumstances.
</UL>

<P>9. &nbsp; Should liability for damages be unlimited?</P>

<P>It is unnecessary to expose defendants to unlimited liability in order to accomplish
the goal of effective deterrence. The Committee believes that the goal of compensating
injured investors must be balanced against the goal of permitting corporations to
continue in business as an important part of the communities in which they operate and
as an important part of the Canadian economy. It is recommended that:
<UL>
<LI>the total liability of an issuer for a particular misrepresentation should not
exceed the greater of $1 million and 5% of its market capitalization calculated prior
to the date of the misrepresentation or delay in disclosure.
<BR><BR><LI>the liability of an officer or director of the issuer should, unless such person
proceeded knowingly, be limited in respect of a particular misrepresentation or delay
to the greater of $25,000 and 50% of such person's total compensation from the issuer
and its affiliates during the preceding 12 months, including the fair market value of
options, potential pension benefits and other deferred compensation held at the time of
the misrepresentation or disclosure delay; and
<BR><BR><LI>the liability of an expert should, unless such expert proceeded knowingly, be
limited in respect of a particular misrepresentation to the greater of $1 million and
three times the fees earned by such expert from the issuer and its affiliates during
the preceding 12 months.
</UL>

<BR><H3>Ontario Securities Commission</H3>

<P>The Committee recommends that the user-pay system currently in force be permitted to
function without diversion of funds so that the Commission is adequately funded. It
believes that the current situation in which the Ontario Securities Commission finds itself,
where it is a source of net revenue to the Ontario government and yet is said to have
inadequate funding to perform the task that the capital markets expect of it, and which
its legislative mandate imposes upon it, cannot be permitted to continue.</P>

<BR><H3>Market Participant Advisory Committee</H3>

<P>The Committee recommends that a committee be established to represent the private
sector to provide advice, when asked and on its own initiative, to the SRAs with
respect to continuous disclosure rules, to comment on disclosure expectations of the
investment community, and to identify and alert the SRAs to disclosure violations and
inadequacies. Such a committee, to be designated the Market Participant Advisory
Committee, should be broadly constituted and be composed of representatives of private
and public sector pension funds, mutual fund managers and investment counsellors,
Canadian societies of financial analysts, The Canadian Institute of Chartered
Accountants, the Canadian Shareowners Association (or other comparable organizations),
and Canadian university faculties.</P>

<BR><H3>Integrated Disclosure System</H3>

<P>The Committee recommends that the quality of disclosure be upgraded significantly by
stipulating that every public company/reporting issuer be obliged to file an annual information form, the content of
which would be obliged to meet prospectus-level disclosure. Further, material change
disclosure should also satisfy prospectus-level disclosure. Finally, SRAs should
consider moving toward a system in which all reporting issuers are eligible to use the
POP system. In view of the recommendation that corporations and management be liable to
injured third parties for misleading continuous disclosure, the Committee was of the
view that selected scrutiny of documents by SRAs would be sufficient.</P>

<BR><H3>Analyst Meetings</H3>

<P>The Committee recommends that issuers adopt the practice of holding information
meetings quarterly, after their quarterly report has been published, such meetings to
be notified in advance and to be available to all analysts.</P>

<BR><H3>Educational Programs</H3>

<P>The Committee recommends that the Exchange take a greater role in the education of
issuers and their officers with respect to the practical application of continuous
disclosure rules. Specifically, the Exchange should develop educational programs, to be
held at regular intervals, aimed at improving awareness of and compliance with
continuous disclosure obligations and that the Exchange publish semi-annually a "TSE
Speaks" publication dealing with disclosure failures by listed companies as well as
disclosure dilemmas that have been faced, together with the resolution of those
dilemmas by collaboration between the issuer and the staff of the Exchange.</P>

<DL>
<DD><B>J. William Rowley QC
<DD>5 February 1996</B>

