<H2>Reforming The Canada Business Corporations Act:<BR>Our Update on Phase II</H2>

<P>The <I>Canada Business Corporations Act</I> ("CBCA") was a state-of-the-art business corporations statute
when it became law in 1975. But the Act has not kept pace with new developments, and the time was
right for a much-needed overhaul when Industry Canada last year commenced a two-phase process for
updating and reforming the CBCA, which governs 190,000 Canadian companies.</P>

<P>The 1994 Phase I amendments involved mostly technical reforms intended to reduce red tape, resolve
ambiguities and contribute to the efficient administration of the Act. The more ambitious Phase II
initiative, now well under way, will lead to reommendations from the Minister to Parliament for far
more substantive changes to the Act. Over the coming months the Phase II consultations will be the
subject of significant public discussion and should be closely monitored by those in the corporate
community whose interests might be affected. This bulletin describes the more important issues on the
reform agenda.</P>

<P><B>The Consultation Process</B><BR>
Industry Canada and the Corporations Directorate have identified the following key issues for the
Phase II reform initiative:
<UL>
<LI>shareholder communications and proxy solicitation;
<LI>going-private transactions;
<LI>directors' residency and other corporate residency requirements;
<LI>various "technical amendments";
<LI>unanimous shareholder agreements;
<LI>directors' liability;
<LI>financial assistance to shareholders, officers and others; 
<LI>insider trading; and
<LI>takeover bids.
</UL></P>

<P>The discussion papers and business consultation questionnaires on these issues are being released in
stages through to December, 1995 and Industry Canada's public consultations will commence shortly
thereafter. Written responses to the background papers and questionnaires should be in the
government's hands by March, 1996.</P>

<P>In addition, the Senate Standing Committee on Banking, Trade and Commerce, chaired by Senator Michael
Kirby, will hold hearings in Vancouver, Calgary, Winnipeg, Halifax, and Montreal in February, 1996
seeking input on the discussion papers and related issues of corporate governance.</P>

<P>The target date for draft legislation is the fall of 1996 with final passage of the amending package
scheduled for the spring of 1997.</P><BR>

<P><FONT SIZE="+2"><B>The Issues</B></FONT></P>

<P><B>Shareholder Communications</B><BR>
The Industry Canada discussion paper raises a number of important issues relating to communications
from corporations to their shareholders and by shareholders to each other. With most shares now held
through brokers or other intermediaries, identifying and communicating with non-registered beneficial
shareholders is still slow, expensive and uncertain. Issuers find they cannot communicate directly
with their beneficial shareholders on topics of vital interest to the corporation's future; and
shareholders who want to exchange views with other shareholders can find themselves stymied by the
need to comply with complex and sometimes onerous proxy solicitation rules. Adding to the problems
are the proliferation of new financial products and the increasing use of borrowed shares. </P>

<P>The Canadian Securities Commissioners' National Policy 41 ("NP 41") adopted by most provincial
regulators addresses some of the issues relating to communications between issuers and their
non-objecting beneficial owners ("NOBOs"), but it currently is under revision with no final consensus
yet having been reached.</P>

<P>The Industry Canada paper suggests a number of possible solutions, including requiring registrants to
furnish NOBO lists to issuers on request, harmonizing the CBCA with NP 41 (in its draft amended
form), adopting fixed record dates for voting shares, changing the timing for notices of annual
meetings, adopting new rules for voting borrowed shares and implementing various means of direct
communication with NOBOs. </P>

<P>As for communications among shareholders, the paper follows the lead of recent U.S. SEC reforms that
exempt from the dissident proxy solicitation rules communications by shareholders whose ownership
interests fall below certain thresholds and those who wish to state in the media how they will vote
without soliciting proxies. Industry Canada's final views on these issues will presumably have to
await finalization of NP 41.</P>

<P><B>Going Private Transactions</B><BR>
Going-private transactions (or "GPTs") refer to a variety of techniques designed to eliminate
minority shareholder interests with compensation, but without the consent of all those who are
affected. GPTs can enhance corporate efficiency and streamline decision making; but there i
resistance to these kinds of transactions in the investment community. </P>

<P>Unlike Ontario's <I>Business Corporations Act</I> , the CBCA does not expressly permit GPTs (except for "90%
squeezeouts" under s. 206), but there is a 1994 policy statement by the CBCA Director explaining that
GPTs are permitted so long as fairness is assured, with the s. 241 oppression remedy providing the
yardstick. </P>

<P>The discussion paper recommends that the CBCA codify the 1994 Director's policy by expressly
permitting GPTs in certain circumstances so long as the acquiror abides by standards of fairness,
which would be prescribed by regulation. Leaving the fairness standards to the "regs" rather than
enshrining them in the Act would balance the need for certainty and predictability against the need
for flexibility as standards evolve. The paper does not recommend specific standards, but suggests
that three protections mandated by most provincial securities rules  approval by a majority of the
minority, independent valuations and enhanced disclosure  would likely be a base minimum. To protect
minority shareholders of private companies, the proposals would hold an acquiror to public company
standards or require unanimous shareholder consent.</P>

<P><B>Directors' Residency</B><BR>
Under the CBCA a majority of the board and its committees must be resident Canadians, and directors
may not transact business at board meetings unless such a majority is present. These requirements
were adopted in the 1970's in response to nationalistic concerns that foreign direct investors would
not adequately take into account Canadian interests.</P>

<P>The residency requirements may have outlived their usefulness. They have been criticized for limiting
board flexibility, discouraging foreign investment and inhibiting Canadian owned transnational
corporations from accessing the international board expertise they need to compete effectively in
world markets. Most other OECD jurisdictions that had such policies have long since abandoned them.
Moreover, a corporation can easily avoid the requirements by incorporating in one of the four
provinces that do not have such constraints, by using a unanimous shareholder agreement that strips
all but token powers from the board or by various other means. </P>


<P>The Industry Canada paper considers ten possible options for reform ranging from maintaining the
status quo to repealing the directors' residency requirements altogether, but requiring an agent for
service of legal documents.</P>

<P><B>Technical Amendments</B><BR>
Under the heading "Technical Amendments" Industry Canada has assembled a diverse grab-bag of
proposals, some of which raise important substantive issues that might otherwise warrant full
discussion papers. Among the more important are:
<UL>
<LI>whether a subsidiary should be permitted to acquire shares in its parent;
<LI>whether beneficial (but unregistered) shareholders should be permitted to submit  shareholder
proposals;
<LI>whether meetings that may be requisitioned by shareholders be restricted to      matters within the
powers of shareholders;
<LI>how directors should be permitted to appoint additional directors between        shareholders'
meetings; 
<LI>the range of matters that may be delegated by directors; and
<LI>strengthening auditors' rights to information.</UL></P>

<P><B>Directors' Liability</B><BR>
Discussion concerning directors' liability, especially under federal and provincial statutes, has
mushroomed in recent years. Some commentators have suggested that easing the burden on directors
would encourage more qualified people to participate in the governance of Canadian corporations.
While Industry Canada will be looking at this possibility, it is also considering various ways to
expand liability. For example, the adequacy of the current "good faith" reliance defence in s. 123(4)
is being questioned and the imposition of a more stringent "full due diligence" standard is being
considered. Industry Canada is also looking at expanding the requirement for the disclosure of
conflicts of interest and at clarifying the indemification and insurance provisions. </P>

<P>The issue of broadening the scope of the board's duty from acting in the best interests of
shareholders as a whole to acting in the best interests of other stakeholders as well is not
expressly on the reform agenda, but it will likely become a subject of discussion during the
consultation period. 
One directors' liability issue, which for jurisdictional reasons cannot be entirely resolved by the
federal government but still deserves close study, is the proliferation of federal and provincial
statutory provisions that impose personal criminal and civil liability on directors for acts and
omissions of the corporation in such areas as environmental law, taxation, occupational health and
safety, pay equity and a large number of others. There are at least 200 such statutes, and the TSE
Committee on Corporate Governance in Canada  recently urged the review of this growing body of
legislation.</P>

<P><B>Insider Trading</B><BR>
The most straightforward insider trading reform option would be the harmonization of federal
provisions with provincial securities regulations. While harmonization is on the table, Industry
Canada is also looking at updating the definition of insider, extending the limitation period for
civil actions from two to three years, adding to the list of speculative instruments that insiders
are prohibited from trading in, facilitating the compensation of investors at whose expense an
insider trade takes place, and establishing a reporting period by regulation. Insider trading
proposals that go beyond "de facto" harmonization with provincial standards are likely to encounter
significant resistance.</P>

<P><B>Takeover Bids</B><BR>
As with insider trading, any consideration of takeover bids will have to take place against a
backdrop of provincial securities laws and stock exchange rules. The issues Industry Canada is
considering include raising the bid threshold from 10 to 20 %, introducing new rules for issuer bids,
requiring that bid materials be sent to non-residents, clarifying the duties of a target company's
directors, creating new rules for changing the terms of a bid, updating several exemptions and giving
the CBCA Director the power to exempt specific transactions.</P>

<P><B>Unanimous Shareholder Agreements</B><BR>
For closely-held corporations (which make up 99% of the CBCA's companies) the most significant Phase
II issue may well be the possible expansion of the unanimous shareholder agreement provisions that
permit shareholders to assume some or all of the powers of the board. Industry Canada has studied a
report prepared by McMillan Binch which recommends that provisions similar to recent U.S. legislation
be enacted to give shareholders of private companies the flexibility to contract out of provisions in
the governing statute and allow them to better shape their corporate legal form to their business
needs and internal relationships.</P>

<P>Expanding the unanimous shareholder agreement provisions would be consistent with the government's
deregulation and small and medium business agendas: it would help small businesses, joint venture
corporations and the wholly-owned subsidiaries of large public companies to develop more flexible and
responsive organizational structures and avoid unnecessary formalities. </P>

<P><B>Financial Assistance</B><BR>
The complex restrictions in s. 44 of the CBCA on a corporation's ability to provide financial
assistance by way of loans, guarantees or other means to its shareholders, directors, officers and
other related parties, or in connection with purchases of its shares, have been often criticized for
hindering effective corporate reorganizations and throwing up needless roadblocks to intra-group
financings. The statutory language raises a host of interpretive problems; the policy behind the
prohibitions is obscure; and prac-titioners are often driven to dubious avoidance techniques before
they will bless otherwise blameless transactions. </P>

<P>Industry Canada is considering various alternatives, including the Alberta Law Reform Institute's
recommendation to simply repeal the equivalent provisions in the Alberta statute, and the recent
amendments in Saskatchewan that substituted disclosure requirements for solvency and asset value
tests. Other alternatives include narrowing the reach of the section, simplifying its wording and
fine tuning the standards for its application. </P>

<P><B>Conclusion</B><BR>
In addition to updating the substance of the CBCA, the reform initiative may also point the way to
more responsive and flexible ways to keep the Act more current and in some greater measure of harmony
with provincial securities laws. It is too early to tell just how far reaching the Phase II
legislation will be, but those with an interest in the reform issues should review the discussion
papers in the coming months and make their views known to Industry Canada or the Senate Finance
Committee.</P>

<P>For more information or to obtain copies of the Industry Canada discussion papers, contact: 
<A HREF="mailto:jkazanjian@mcbinch.com">John Kazanjian</A> at (416) 865-7071 or 
<A HREF="mailto:rscavone@mcbinch.com">Robert Scavone</A> at (416) 865-7901.</P>

