<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch: Greenmail - Environmental Brief</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="PrintH.gif"><BR>

<H2>Bata Directors Win On Environmental Indemnification</H2>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Introduction</B></FONT><BR>
On September 18, 1995, the Ontario Court of Appeal wrote the final chapter of the legal
saga of Bata Industries. The case involved the release of chemical wastes from the Bata
shoe manufacturing facility in Batawa, Ontario. Since the trial in 1992, it has driven
directors' liabilities and environmental matters to the top of every corporate agenda.
One doubts that Bata will be sad to see its name disappear from Canadian law reports.</P>

<BR><P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Background</B></FONT><BR>
Bata Industries Ltd. and two of its directors were found guilty of offences under
Ontario's environmental statutes. The charges related to the storage of liquid wastes
generated by the manufacturing facility. Bata stored the wastes for a long period of
time in an exposed area so that the metal drums rusted or corroded and eventually
deteriorated to the point where the wastes spilled. The court said this was negligent.</P>

<P>Ontario's environmental legislation imposes an obligation on corporate directors and
officers to take all reasonable care to prevent a discharge of pollutants. Two of the
directors, Douglas Marchant and Keith Weston, were charged with breaching the
<I>Environmental Protection Act&nbsp;</I> in their capacity as Bata directors, and were found
guilty. The directors knew about, or should have known about the problem. Either way,
they failed to address it diligently. The trial court sentenced each director to a fine
of $12,000, which was reduced on appeal to $6,000 each.</P>

<P>The court also issued a probation order against Bata that tried to prevent the
corporation from indemnifying the individual defendants. After an appeal before an
intermediate court, Bata appealed a single issue  - the validity of this probation
order - to the Court of Appeal.</P>

<UL>
<LI>In Ontario, probation orders are authorized by the <I>Provincial Offences Act&nbsp;</I>. They
are deemed to contain standard conditions including one that the defendant not commit
the same or any related or similar offence. 
<LI>The Court of Appeal indicated probation terms are rooted "in deterrence and the
rehabilitation of the defendant."
<LI>The Court of Appeal found the indemnification prohibition improper because, although
by its terms it bound the corporate defendant, Bata Industries, it was in substance
aimed at the individual directors.
<LI>The probation order was used against Bata for a collateral purpose - to ensure that
two other parties not subject to the order were punished correctly by receiving no
indemnification.
<LI>The Court of Appeal referred to the indemnification provisions in the Ontario <I>Business
Corporations Act&nbsp;</I> which sets out the circumstances under which a corporation may
indemnify directors or officers and the narrower circumstances when a corporation must
indemnify them. The Court of Appeal stated that the indemnification provisions
constitute a:

<BLOCKQUOTE><I>"comprehensive code of general application by which the indemnification of
officers and directors and former officers and directors is regulated."&nbsp;</I></BLOCKQUOTE>

<LI>If Bata was to be prohibited from indemnifying the directors, the Court of Appeal
said that the prohibition should be contained in the <I>Business Corporations Act&nbsp;</I>, not
imposed by virtue of a probation order under the <I>Provincial Offences Act&nbsp;</I>. 
<LI>According to the Business Corporations Act, indemnification is permitted if the
directors acted honestly, in good faith, and in a reasonable belief that their conduct
was lawful. If the directors failed to meet these requirements, the probation order is
superfluous because the law prevents Bata from indemnifying them. If they did act
honestly, the probation order contradicts the scheme set out in the <I>Business
Corporations Act&nbsp;</I>.
<LI>The Court of Appeal held that it was not appropriate to impose a term of probation
that denies directors access to general legislation concerning indemnification, like
the <I>Business Corporations Act&nbsp;</I>.
</UL>

<P>The bottom line is that directors can rest easier, knowing that - if they meet the
legal standards of acting honestly, in good faith and believing they were acting
lawfully - corporations will not be prohibited from indemnifying them.</P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1 WIDTH=495 ALIGN=left>
<DL>
<DD><FONT SIZE="-1">For further information, please contact:</FONT><DD><A HREF="mailto:mpeterson@mcbinch.com">Michael Peterson</A> at (416) 865-7839 or
<DD><A HREF="mailto:schester@mcbinch.com">Simon Chester</A> at (416) 865-7278.
<DT><IMG SRC="WNew.pb.gif"></DL>

<H2>Appeal Rights Under the Ontario EPA - A Short Fuse!</H2>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>A Trap for the Unwary</B></FONT><BR>
Environmental regulation in Ontario involves a great deal of bureaucratic discretion.
Specific emission levels or pollution controls are often found in a certificate of
approval or an order issued to an individual plant or facility by the Ministry of
Environment and Energy (MOEE) rather than in a statute or regulation which applies to
everyone. The result of the certificate of approval, or order, is site-specific
regulation. This may give bureaucrats more flexibility than a province-wide scheme but
it also opens the door to decisions by local regulators that can be inconsistent or
downright arbitrary. If you get such an order or approval, you do have a right to
appeal under Ontario's <I>Environmental Protection Act&nbsp;</I> but the time permitted for
exercising those rights is so tight that the opportunity is frequently lost. To avoid
losing your rights, you mustbe prepared for a very short fuse. </P>

<BR><P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>The MOEE's Tool-Kit</B></FONT><BR>
If you apply for a certificate of approval for pollution control or abatement measures,
the certificate you receive will generally come with a long list of conditions
attached. Orders are issued by the Ministry to compel an action that the subject will
not do willingly - they too can have strings attached in the form of terms and
conditions. In the past, the Ministry issued such orders only occasionally, since it
has preferred to achieve pollution abate- ment through negotiation. When it did
exercise this power, its own internal processes were cumbersome and grindingly slow.
But a recent policy decision to use an accelerated version called a "field order" will
result in more frequent resort to the use of orders. </P>

<BR><P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>The Environmental Appeal Board</B></FONT><BR>
You can generally appeal an MOEE order or approval to the Environmental Appeal Board
(EAB). Ontario's <I>Environmental Protection Act&nbsp;</I> set up the EAB to deal with the nuts and
bolts of environmental regulation. It hears appeals involving orders, certificates of
approval, licenses and permits under Ontario's environmental legislation. The EAB may
be the only protection against an arbitrary call by the MOEE. </P>

<P>As a specialist administrative tribunal, its members are chosen for their expertise in
various environmental disciplines. In some ways, it is more powerful than a court since
it has the power to alter, revoke or confirm the action of the MOEE. But  as discussed
below, the EAB is powerless if the person appealing misses the 15 day cut-off.</P>

<BR><P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>What Can Be Appealed?</B></FONT><BR>
If you are an applicant for an approval or a person to whom an order is directed, you
can appeal on matters such as:
<UL>
<LI>a refusal to issue or renew a certificate of approval or permit;
<LI>the imposition of particular terms or conditions in a certificate of approval or
permit
<LI>the revocation or suspension of a certificate of approval;
<LI>the imposition of an order or a specific portion of an order;</P>
</UL>
<P>The EAB has a general power to order the MOEE to take whatever action the EAB considers
appropriate. In effect, it can overrule the MOEE on large strategy or on the small
details of environmental regulation. </P>

<BR><P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Appeal Period</B></FONT><BR>
Unfortunately, the time frame for appeal is ridiculously short - only 15 days from the
date when you are served with the certificate, order, or permit. When manufacturers
change equipment or even alter rates of production, the Ministry requires them to amend
or update certificates of approval. The MOEE Approvals Branch knows all about the magic
of the 15 day period. They are careful in issuing new or amended certificates of
approval not to reopen contentious issues that are already locked in by the lapsing of
the 15 day period previously. </P>

<P>It is not complicated to launch an appeal. The details are generally provided by the
MOEE when they deliver the approval documents. Simply fill in a notice of appeal form
setting out the details of the approval or order that you object to. Then serve the
form on the MOEE and the EAB.</P>

<P>But subject to one minor exception, your right to appeal is completely lost if you do
not act within 15 days. In one reported case, the EAB concluded it could not extend the
15 days, even where there was an obvious injustice and where the MOEE was happy to
consent to an extension.</P>


<BR><P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Protecting Your Interests</B></FONT><BR>
In some cases, where the MOEE proposes to isue an order, it must give a written notice
of its intentions to the parties involved. A business receiving such a notice has time
to respond and has an effective warning of what may occur. But a "field order" will not
generally be preceded by notice and the recipient has only 15 days to make its appeal. </P>

<P>Likewise, the approvals process does not lend itself to strict time delays. Despite
recent improvements, an application for an approval can sit with the Approvals Branch
for several months. Where an applicant for approval has heard nothing about its request
after a three month period, it is natural to regard the certificate of approval as
something that is less than pressing. </P>

<P>Where there is a problem with a particular MOEE approval,  legal counsel is frequently
consulted after - in many cases long after - the expiry of the time period. All too
often legal counsel are asked to correct a problem in a certificate of approval three
and even six months after it is issued. Generally, the technical experts have wrestled
with it for a month or so before confirming to themselves that it needs to be
rectified. </P>

<P>Environmental managers must be aware of the 15 day period. They should be ready to move
swiftly to review an approval or order as soon as it is issued and to decide
immediately if it is acceptable. If it may be problematic, consult your legal advisers
without delay. You can file a notice of appeal while further studies are performed.</P>

<P>The time and expense involved in preparing a notice of appeal is not large. Filing the
notice of appeal is not a commitment to ongoing expense. You can negotiate with the
MOEE and abandon an appeal at any time. But if the initial step isn't taken, you are
stuck with the order or approval for good.</P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1 WIDTH=495 ALIGN=left>
<DL>
<DD><FONT SIZE="-1">For further information, please contact:</FONT><DD><A HREF="mailto:mpeterson@mcbinch.com">Michael Peterson</A> at (416) 865-7839.

