<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch: Nova Scotia Unlimcos</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="PrintH.gif"><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>Nova Scotia Unlimcos:</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><B>A Planning Opportunity for Cross Border Leasing</B></FONT>

<P>Unlimited liability companies (Unlimcos) incorporated in Nova Scotia are becoming increasingly popular
as a vehicle in structuring cross-border leasing transactions. As a hybrid entity that may be
considered a corporation for Canadian tax and corporate law purposes and as a partnership for U.S. tax
purposes, Unlimcos can serve a useful purpose in the role of lessor in leasing transactions involving
a U.S. equity investor and a Canadian lessee.</P>

<BR><H3>Overcoming the Withholding Tax Hurdle</H3>

<P>Historically, the major hurdle to be overcome in structuring a lease into Canada has been, and
continues to be, the Canadian withholding tax that would be payable by the Canadian lessee on lease
payments to a non-resident lessor. Inbound leasing transactions have been difficult to structure, and
the few that have been done have generally relied on complex two-tiered "converter structures"
involving a lease outside Canada followed by a conditional sale into Canada. Except for the airline
industry which was successful in persuading the Department of Finance to exempt aircraft lease
payments from Canadian withholding tax, most other industries that are users of capital equipment are
faced with this hurdle. Canadian railways, for example, have for the most part been limited to
domestic leases when seeking lease financing for the acquisition of rolling stock.</P>

<P>Unlimcos may open the door forinbound leases from the United States and provide Canadian companies
with access to the U.S. leasing market. This development could result in lower lease rates for
Canadian companies able to conclude cross-border leasing transactions that take advantage of U.S. tax
benefits which may be available to the owner/lessor of certain types of equipment.</P>

<P>How do Unlimcos accomplish this objective? &nbsp;By virtue of the hybrid nature of the entity. If an
Unlimco is the owner/lessor of the leased assets, Canadian withholding tax becomes a non-issue since
the lease payments pass from a Canadian lessee to a Canadian lessor (Unlimco) without crossing the
border. However, for U.S. tax purposes, the Unlimco lessor may qualify as a partnership thereby
entitling the U.S. members to flow-through treatment. A U.S. equity investor that becomes a member of
an Unlimco lessor may, subject to the "Pickle-Dole" rules in the U.S. for foreign use property, obtain
favourable tax treatment as a partnership that is akin to the tax treatment it could have obtained if
the lessor were a U.S. entity. Alternatively, a U.S. equity investor could incorporate an Unlimco into
a "leasehold interest" structure in lieu of the more traditional U.S. leveraged leasing structure.</P>

<BR><H3>Establishing an Unlimco</H3>

<P>Unlimcos are not "off-the-shelf" corporations and must be tailored to each transaction. Structuring a
suitable Unlimco requires careful attention to the Unlimco's charter documents in order to meet the
objectives of U.S. tax counsel, provide for bankruptcy remoteness given the special purpose nature of
the entity, and comply with Nova Scotia corporate law. Once the form of the charter documents has been
settled, it is a simple matter for Nova Scotia counsel to establish the Unlimco by filing the
necessary documents in the ordinary course with the Registrar of Joint Stock Companies. Nova Scotia is
the only jurisdiction in Canada which allows the incorporation of Unlimcos.</P>

<P>In structuring the Unlimco lessor, U.S. tax counsel will be guided by U.S. tax rules that provide an
association will be taxed as a "corporation" if it satisfies any three of four tests. In order to
avoid being characterized as a corporation, the Canadian entity must "fail" at least two of the
following tests:  limited liability; shares freely transferable; centralized management; and unlimited
life. It is possible to structure an Unlimco in a leasing transaction so it fails three and perhaps
all of the tests set out by the IRS. The resulting flow-through treatment as a partnership would
enable a U.S. equity investor to claim favourable U.S. tax benefits. Part of these tax benefits may,
subject to negotiation between the parties, be passed back to the Canadian lessee.</P>

<BR><H3>Dealing with Unlimited Liability</H3>

<P>As unlimited liability is not a particularly attractive feature to potential investors, a limited
liability entity may be interposed as a buffer between the U.S. equity investor and the Unlimco. Such
a buffer with limited liability would preclude a creditor, who must first exhaust its recourse against
the Unlimco before proceeding against its members, from pursuing the U.S. equity investor. Limited
liability protection can be achieved without sacrificing the investor's access to U.S. tax benefits by
using a corporation that is consolidated with the investor for U.S. tax purposes, or by using a
limited partnership or limited liability company structured as a flow-through vehicle for U.S. tax
purposes.</P>

<P>Certain other aspects of Nova Scotia company law may make the incorporation of an Unlimco attractive
to U.S. investors. Unlike the Business Corporations Act (Ontario) which requires that a majority of
directors be resident Canadians, the Companies Act (Nova Scotia) imposes no such restriction on the
composition of an Unlimco's board of directors.</P>

<BR><H3>Canadian Tax Considerations</H3>

<P>Although withholding tax on lease payments is addressed through the use of an Unlimco in a cross
border lease, there are other Canadian taxes to be considered. As a full-fledged Canadian taxpayer,
the Unlimco is taxed as a corporation in Canada and would be required to file Canadian income tax
returns as would any other Canadian corporation. It would also have to be operated with a view to
profit, and may not be structured to "run flat" as would most other special purpose entities. The
deductions that would be available to an Unlimco in computing its taxable income may not be sufficient
to offset the leasing income earned by it, thereby causing the Unlimco to incur Canadian income tax
liability, particularly in the later years of the lease when the interest expense on its indebtedness
may be lower than in the early years.</P>

<P>Like other corporations, the Unlimco would also be subject to liability for federal large corporations
tax on its' taxable capital employed in Canada. It may also be subject to provincial capital taxes,
although Nova Scotia does not at present impose such taxes on non-financial institutions and the
Unlimco's liability for such taxes in other provinces would depend on the nature of its assets, the
manner in which it conducts its business and the specific rules applicable in the other relevant
provinces.</P>

<P>Canadian withholding tax on payments by the Unlimco in respect of interest and dividends should also
be considered. In a leveraged leasing transaction, when the debt is provided by a U.S. lender, the
interest paid by the Unlimco to te U.S. lender may attract Canadian withholding tax unless the debt is
structured in a manner that qualifies for the long-term debt exemption set out in section
212(1)(b)(vii) of the <I>Income Tax Act</I>. Dividend payments made by Unlimco to its U.S. members would
attract Canadian withholding tax, but generally the preferential treaty rate of 5% (6% in 1996) would
apply.</P>

<BR><H3>Providing for Sufficient Canadian Dollars</H3>

<P>Currency exchange risk is another risk to be considered in structuring a cross-border lease involving
an Unlimco when the lease payments and/or debt funding are payable in U.S. dollars. Care must be taken
to address the hedging or funding of any cash shortfalls that may arise as a result of mismatches in
the tax characterization of currency gains or losses or the potential insufficiency of cash receipts
to fund obligations that may be denominated in another currency. The U.S. equity investor may be
required to fund any shortfall in Canadian dollars.</P>

<BR><H3>Protecting Against Lessor Insolvency</H3>

<P>A Canadian lessee involved in a lease with an Unlimco would be concerned that the special purpose
nature of the lessor be maintained throughout the lease term and that the lessor be contractually
restricted from undertaking any activities apart from the single leasing transaction. Such
restrictions, which may also be included in the Unlimco's charter documents, are intended to reduce
the risk of a lessor insolvency. In order to secure its option to purchase the leased equipment from
Unlimco at the end of the lease, the lessee may also take security over the equipment. As there would
be no other assets in Unlimco apart from the leased equipment, the lessee may also require certain
covenants from the U.S. equity investor, such as a covenant that all Canadian taxes incurred by
Unlimco will be paid.</P>

<P>In summary, the Unlimco is a hybrid entity that provides a unique planning opportunity to Canadian
lessees interested in seeking U.S. lease financing for their equipment. When properly structured, an
Unlimco could facilitate a domestic leasing transaction that has many of the features and benefits of
a U.S. leveraged lease. A carefully designed economic model would be required in order to ensure that
the cash flows in the leasing transaction meet the tax and financial objectives of the parties on both
sides of the border.</P>

<P>The foregoing is for general informational purposes only and is not to be considered as legal advice
on matters of Nova Scotia or U.S. law. Readers are cautioned that counsel in those jurisdictions
should be consulted when establishing an Unlimco.</P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<DL>
<DD>For more information, contact <B>Vern Kakoschke</B> at (416) 865-7847 or<DL><DD><B>Stephen Bowman</B> at (416) 865-7200.</DL>

