<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch: Government Procurement Rules</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="PrintH.gif"><BR>

<H2>Government Procurement Rules have Teeth</H2>

<P>Our International Trade and Commodity Tax Group recently achieved precedent setting
success when the Canadian International Trade Tribunal recommended that an unsuccessful
bidder to a federal government contract be compensated for its profit opportunity lost
as a result of a breach of the NAFTA Government Procurement Rules by a federal government
Department.  The amount of compensation is currently being negotiated and is in the
millionsof dollars.</P>

<P>We determined that the NAFTA Rules applied to the Request for Proposals ("RFP") and
filed a procurement review complaint with the Tribunal pointing out the non-compliant
elements of the awardee's bid proposal and alleging various acts of discrimination
contrary to the NAFTA.  The Tribunal determined that the NAFTA Rules were breached when the
government Department accepted a proposal which, at the time of bid opening, failed to
comply with essential requirements of the RFP.  The Tribunal agreed with our
submissionsthat so called "clarifications" to the awardee's bid after bid opening amounted to
substantive modifications, revisions or alterations of the contents of the bid proposal in respect
of a number of essential requirements in the RFP.</P>

<P>The Tribunal therefore recommended that the contract with the awardee be terminated and
awarded to the Complainant or, in the alternative, that compensation be paid "that
recognizes the prejudice suffered by the Complainant in being deprived of the contract and of the
opportunity to profit therefrom."   The Tribunal also awarded the Complainant its costs
in bringing the complaint and, if the contract was not awarded to the Complainant, its
reasonable costs incurred in preparing the bid.</P>

<P>In addition to the precedent setting nature and amount of the compensation award, the
case also establishes principles to be applied when a government entity does not play by the
new NAFTA Procurement Rules.  These Rules force the federal government to change the way it
does business; a government entity cannot steer bids and cannot work with a
non-compliant preferred bidder to modify the bid proposal to an acceptable level of compliancy.  </P>

<P>Unsuccessful bidders in federal government tenders should consider seeking redress
under the NAFTA regarding unfair or non-competitive bidding practices.  A complaint must be filed
with the CITT within 10 working days after the day on which the basis for the complaint
became known or reasonably should have become known.  Dalton Albrecht (416) 865-7171
or Cyndee Todgham (416) 865-7125 can be contacted for more information.</P>

<IMG SRC="PrintP.gif">
