<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch: What's New: Technology &amp; Trade Report</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="About.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar1.gif" ALT="About McMillan Binch"></A><A HREF="IPTOC.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar2.gif" ALT="In Print"></A><A HREF="Feature.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar3.gif" ALT="Legal Feature"></A><A HREF="Student.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar4.gif" ALT="Law Career"></A><A HREF="IntLinks.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar5.gif" ALT="Resources"></A><A HREF="Feedback.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar6.gif" ALT="Have Your Say"></A><A HREF="WNew.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="Bar7.gif" ALT="What's New"></A><BR><BR></CENTER>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="WNew.h.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<H1>The Emergence of Electronic Commerce:<BR>When is a Deal Really a Deal?*</H1>

<P><I>Disputes arising from electronic commerce are getting piecemeal responses. But the very nature of the
media calls for concerted action on an international scale.</I><BR><B>By David Woolford and Simon Chester</B></P>

<P>In today's business environment, technologies are evolving at a dazzling rate. Every day busnesses
conduct a vast number of commercial transactions that crisscross the globe. Each transaction
has at least one common element: the communication of information. Historically, communication was
either direct (typically face-to-face or over the telephone), or via the postal or other personal
delivery systems. Telex communication started over 50 years ago but grew increasingly obsolete as
fax technology spread. Today, more and more businesses are using electronic data interchange (EDI)
and electronic mail (e-mail) to communicate. With the burgeoning use and popularity of the Internet,
these types of communication are exponentially increasing in number.</P>

<P>Yet, save for a few recent cases and some legislative developments, the challenge raised by new
technology to the legal principles governing contract has not been settled. The global marketplace
needs clear legal ground rules, and the issues raised will have to be addressed. When exactly, for
example, is a deal really a deal? If a deal does exist, when and where is it made? Which
jurisdiction's laws will govern, especially where parties in different jurisdictions use third party
network service providers (VANs) located elsewhere?</P>

<P>To appreciate the questions raised by the new technologies, their impact on other issues surrounding
the construction and enforcement of binding contracts, and 
where the law is and ought to be going, an understanding 
of the origins and development of the common law principles applicable to business commerce is
useful.</P>
<BR>
<H2>Binding agreements</H2>

<P>Whether a court will enforce an agreement as a contract depends on whether the agreement satisfies a
number of well-established legal requirements: 
<UL>
<LI>the parties must intend to create legal relationships; 
<LI>there must be communication between the parties of both a valid offer and a valid acceptance;
<LI>each party must either confer a benefit on the other party or incur a detriment (consideration); and 
<LI>the agreement may have to comply with certain formal requirements (such as writing and signature)
imposed by whatever jurisdiction will regulate disputes under the contract (governing law).
</UL>
The first and third requirements for a valid contract are largely unaffected by the parties' choice
of communication medium. But, in this electronic age, the question of whether or not an offer or an
acceptance has been made can be problematic. The use of a non-print medium also poses problems for
the formal requirements.</P>

<P>Commercial transactions made or altered by use of the technologies of the 1990s -<I>fax, EDI and e-mail&nbsp;</I>
- also raise questions regarding contract formation and enforceability that courts will
increasingly have to grapple with. Consideration must be given to: 
<UL>
<LI>Do the new media work?
<LI>How should risk be allocated if communications accepting or revoking a deal are not received or
are otherwise problematic?
<LI>When and where was the contract formed?
<LI>What is the governing law of the contract?
</UL>
<BR>
<H2>Methods of Communication</H2>

<H3>The Traditional View</H3>

<P>Common law courts have long accepted that the general course of business between parties will
determine how acceptance of a contractual offer is to be communicated or delivered, unless the
contract or a particular statute provides otherwise. The common law <I>postal rule&nbsp;</I> developed alongside the
postal services in the 19th century: an offer sent to an individual by post implicitly authorized an
acceptance by mail unless there was express language to the contrary. In the early years of this
century common law courts made similar leaps of faith where offers were communicated by cable or
telex.</P>

<P>However, the technologies of the 1990s have yet to be definitively endorsed by the courts. Legal
history of technological evolution could supply a precedent to endorse these new communications, but
whether this will be accepted is far from certain. And while the courts may imply consent to use such
technologies from a history of similar communications between the parties, the law has no clear
response to a situation where a party employs a new medium to deliver an acceptance, for example,
acceptance by e-mail, where traditionally all dealings were made by fax.</P>
<BR>
<H3>Facsimile Transmissions</H3>

<P>It is only recently that Canadian courts have had to deal with questions of facsimile technology -
the smattering of cases contrasts sharply with the pervasiveness of the fax machine itself.
Nevertheless, it seems to be accepted that fax is a permitted medium of communication unless
expressly forbidden. The key issue here is to determine whether and when a party receives a faxed
document. A party wanting to challenge the validity of a faxed communication cannot simply allege
that the communication should have been made by an alternative medium, since Canadian case law would
validate the communication of an offer or acceptance by fax (so long as it is received by the other
party) on the grounds that it is as convenient a method of communication as any other. This will
probably be the outcome even when a faxed offer or acceptance flows from contractual arrangements
that date from times before facsimile technology existed or was even imagined. Contractual changes
made by facsimile transmissions will also be valid if the court concludes that the parties so
intended.</P>
<BR>
<H3>EDI & E-mail Transmissions</H3>

<P>Canadian courts have not yet considered the legal validity of commerce conducted by EDI and e-mail
technologies. They are still relatively new, and civil disputes generally take a considerable time
to reach the courts. Perhaps the issues have not been litigated because potential litigants feel that
any benefit from a clear legal endorsement of the medium will likely be outweighed by the damage
to the business relationship. The potential litigants probably settle the issue pragmatically and get
back to business.</P>

<P>Although the lack of case law has meant that some of the core issues are still in theory open,
several things suggest that the EDI and e-mail technology will be endorsed. Chief among these is the
enthusiasm shown in recent Canadian cases for new technologies in general. A comment from the bench
typifies the trend:

<BLOCKQUOTE><I>"The conduct of business has for many years been enhanced by technology improvements in
communication. Those improvements should not be rejected automatically when attempts are made to
apply them to matters involving thelaw. They should be considered and, unless there are compelling reasons for
rejection, they should be encouraged, applied and approved."</I></BLOCKQUOTE>

Other arguments in favour of the validity of these technologies relate more to the practicalities of
commerce than to innate legal principles. The sheer scale, frequency and commercial importance of
transactions using these devices is growing daily. The courts recognize that if they impose some
overly technical or restrictive condition, parliament would inevitably be forced to overturn it,
perhaps almost immediately.</P>

<P>If parties customarily transfer data electronically, they will have consented to the use of the
technology. But parties who want to restructure their commercial relationships to take advantage of
the benefits that accrue from the use of electronic commerce would be well 
advised to enter into a trading partner agreement. Such an agreement should include a declaration
that the parties recognize the validity of EDI and e-mail transmissions and consent to their use as
valid communication media.</P>
<BR>
<H3>Allocating Risk</H3>

<P>Parties using new technological media need to think about who should bear the risk if there are
problems with communication, and who should be responsible for confirming receipt of an acceptance.
Under the postal rule, acceptance will be effective as soon as it is mailed, whether the offeror
receives it or not. The rule rests on the notion that the offeror is in the best position to know
whether there may have been a miscommunication.</P>

<P>The rules for allocating risks for telex transmissions, first laid out by Lord Denning some 40 years
ago, are based on a similar rationale but lead to a different result. The offeree generally knows
whether there has been a problem in communication and so should bear the burden of ensuring a
successful delivery of its acceptance.</P>

<P>A party sending a message by telex can generally tell if that message has or has not been received by
the other party's machine, and so the onus of ensuring reception has not been problematic.
However, where a sender reasonably believes that an acceptance has been successfully sent but the
intended recipient is blissfully unaware of this, the courts have held that no contact arises.
Similarly, if the offeree is unaware that the offeror has revoked the deal, the revocation will be
unsuccessful. But where a message has been received but is garbled or incomplete as a result of some
system failure, the couts have shifted the onus of asking for the message to be repeated onto the
recipient. Failure to request a repeat will give rise to an estoppel should the receiver later claim
non-communication of acceptance or revocation.</P>

<P>These principles would appear to be compatible with fax, EDI and e-mail technologies. As some
observers have noted, risk allocation rests on theories of agency and contract law rather than on the
characteristics of individual technology. The result may change based on the medium used but the
process of analysis is the same. Nevertheless, parties should stipulate in their general trading
agreement which party will bear the risks in transmission. This is especially important where third
party network service providers are employed to facilitate or effect transmission.</P>
<BR>
<H2>When and Where is a Deal Made?</H2>

<P>These questions are most pertinent when contracting parties are in different jurisdictions. The
common law rule is that acceptance is understood as a final and unqualified expression of assent
which must be communicated to the offeror. The postal rule shifts this slightly, since an acceptance is
deemed to be received - and a contract thus created - at the time and place of posting. The
rationale is that the offeror has made the post office its agent.</P>

<P>The prevailing commonwealth case law on telex transmissions, in recognizing that the technology
affords  virtually instantaneous communication, has held that a contract is formed at the place where the
acceptance is received. The timing of such reception - hence the precise point in time when a
contract arises - is not always so clear. Some courts have concluded that it is not unreasonable to
consider an acceptance received when it reaches the offeror's address, even if that is out of
working hours and no one will see it at the time of delivery. Commonwealth courts, however, appear
resolved that no general rule should apply in all cases.</P>

<P>American courts have taken a very different position. They consider that a contract formed using
instantaneous media is created at the time the acceptance was sent and at the place from which it
was sent (i.e. an extension of the postal rule).</P>

<P>Few cases have considered when and where an acceptance communicated by fax is deemed received. The
prevailing authority, which is Australian, holds that a facsimile acceptance is deemed received
when it reaches the recipient's address, even if it can be proved tht nobody was there to receive it.
This sounds straight forward but opens up an alarming spectre of liability. In light of this, it
would be prudent to include in the offer words stipulating when it will be deemed received if sent by
fax, or expressly prohibiting acceptance by this mode of communication.</P>

<P>While there were more than 65,000 EDI users in the United States and Canada by the end of 1993,
little case law exists on when and where contracts created by this medium arise. In light of the
similarities with fax technology, in particular the speed of delivery, it can plausibly be argued
that an acceptance will be deemed received (and a contract deemed to arise) at the place where it was
received, either at the time of reception or at a reasonable time thereafter.</P>
<BR>
<H3>A U.S. Example</H3>

<P>In the United States, one case analysed what could be held to constitute an acceptance where a
transmission acknowledge- ment of receipt is made automatically by a computer. It concluded that this
kind of functional communication did not amount to an acceptance creating a contract. It merely
confirmed reception without the receiver consciously considering its contents.</P>

<P>This U.S. case seems to fit the Commonwealth legal principle that the time of reception should not
always be deemed to be the time of acceptance. Nonetheless, trading agreement partners should
stipulate when acceptances will be deemed received.</P>
<BR>
<H2>Conflict of Law Issues</H2>

<P>Parties located in different legal systems will face problems as to which system will or should
determine whether a contract is legally binding. In the past, courts applied rigid principles which
determined the appropriate law of a contract largely by formal reference to such factors as the
place of contracting, the place of performance and the nationality of the parties. Today's common
law rules governing conflict of law are more flexible. In essence, the rule now is that questions of
form and substance should be resolved by the proper law of the contract. Courts have held this to
be the law of the jurisdiction by which the parties expressly provide that the contract be governed
or, in the absence of such an expression, the legal system with which the transaction has its
closest and most real connection.</P>

<P>This rule is intended to protect parties from having to comply with particular requirements of a legal
system with which they have no intrinsic connection but which has merely been, for example, the
location of the transmission or reception of their acceptance.</P>

<P>The freedom to choose a jurisdiction is qualified by common law rules requiring that the choice be
<I>bona fide&nbsp;</I>, legal and not contrary to public policy in the sense of having been deliberately made to
avoid an otherwise applicable rule. In practice, there are few problems.</P>

<P>These rules are flexible enough to deal with deemed place and time of contracting for electronic
commerce. Where the jurisdiction is not specified, these issues can be especially problematic in
contracts between Canadian and U.S. parties because of the different positions their national courts
have taken on the deemed place of contracting by the use of instantaneous communication
technology. Equally problematic are situations where contracting parties employ a third party
outside the jurisdictions concerned in order to facilitate transmission.</P>

<P>The courts resolve the conflicts of law issues by considering the jurisdiction with the most
substantial links, or nexus, to the contract. Thanks to the Internet, electronic transmissions,
particularly e-mail messages, are now regularly routed around the world through jurisdictions which
have nothing to do with the transactions. So, in the absence of an express governing law clause,
the place where the contract is to be performed (rather than the place of contracting) is likely to
be the factor that courts will focus on to resolve the question of proper law. The best advice,
however, is for contracting parties to establish a governing law clause in their trading partner
agreement.</P>
<BR>
<H2>Formal Requirements</H2>

<P>Despite being otherwise valid under the governing law, certain types of contracts must also satisfy
formal requirements in order to be binding. They must, for example, be in writing and signed.
Electronic commerce, due to its inherent non-print characteristics, is laying these requirements open
to close and novel scrutiny.</P>

<BR>
<H3>Written Contracts</H3>

<P>When parliament passed the Statute of Frauds in 1677, it could hardly have dreamt that the writing
requirement would be difficult. This statute provided that no action could be brought in respect of
certain defined types of contracts (such as contracts of guarantee and agreements relating to land,
or not to be performed within one year) unless there was a note or memorandum of the agreement.
Sale of goods acts and consumer protection legislation also have provisions imposing a writing
requirement on contracts in excess of specified monetary amounts.</P>

<P>Over the past 300 years, courts have cut back this writing requirement by holding that the writing
need neither be in any particular form nor contemporaneous 
with the formation of the contract. (Thus, a computer printout of a contract containing elec-tronic
signatures may be just as valid as one written by hand in ink on a piece of paper.)</P>

<P>The emergence of electronic commerce has further strained this formality. At the least, we may need
to expand the definition of what constitutes a writing. Perhaps we should abandon the principle
entirely. And, whether the courts exp
and the definition or legislatures do away with the writing requirement may simply turn on who gets
to the issue first.</P>

<P>Some legislatures have taken the initiative by expanding the direction of the term writing and
eliminating the instances where a written contract is necessary. In the United States, the Uniform
Commercial Code (UCC) definition in Article 1-201 has been amended to expressly include faxed
documents. The Vienna International Sale of Goods Convention settled as long as ago as 1980 that
international sales contracts need not be concluded in writing or have any formal requirements. The
UK Copyright Act contains an expansive definition accepting any notation, regardless of the medium
on which it is recorded. Interpretation statutes in Canada define the term <I>writing&nbsp;</I> as words recorded
in a medium that is visible in form. This would seem to cover a faxed document. Ontario has
recently passed a <I>Statute Law Amendment Act&nbsp;</I> doing away with the writing requirement in the province's
Sale of Goods Act for contracts over Cdn.$40 (U.S.$29). The same amending legislation eliminated
the writing requirement in Ontario's Statute of Frauds for contracts not to be performed within one
year.</P>

<P>In Canada, the enforceability of faxed contracts appears settled in light of the meaning ascribed to
the term <I>writing&nbsp;</I>. But the status of purely electronic (ie. paperless) forms of communication is
still open. Lawmakers are starting to grapple with this surging phenomenon. Meanwhile, parties
should safeguard enforceability by stipulating within their trading partner agreements that
electronic transmissions are writings.</P>
<BR>
<H3>Signed Contracts</H3>

<P>Certain types of contracts need to be signed to be valid. But, as with writing requirements, courts
are interpreting this more loosely. Two core factors emerge. The signature r its symbolic
equivalent must be capable of establishing an evidential link to the signatory and they must signify
approval of the contents of the contract. A recent UK decision held that an automated answer-back
from receiver to sender would not be regarded as a signature because, though it authenticated the
document, it did not convey approval of its contents.</P>

<P>At the moment, EDI and e-mail contracts may present problems because of the difficulty in
independently verifying or establishing the evidential nexus to the signatory. Accordingly, trading
partner
agreements should oblige the parties to establish specific electronic identification or
authenticating numbers or codes, and to agree that these signs are legally sufficient to verify the
identity
of the sender of an electronically-transmitted document and satisfy any statutory signature
requirements.</P>

<P>Industry groups are working on developing a standard means of authenticating electronic messages.
These are expected to use encription-key security features to prevent documents being tampered with
or signatures being forged.</P>
<BR>
<H2>International Standards</H2>

<P>Legislative change and the growing use of electronic trading partner agreements are spurring on legal
change. But they are only the start. As electronic commerce becomes more prevalent so too will
disputes which can be justly resolved only by adapting legal principle. The law will also have to
face up to issues that go beyond contract issues, such as how electronic transmission will be
regarded as evidence and what happens if each party believes that their standard form governs a
transaction. Different countries are starting to address all these issues. The real challenge is to
establish a regime that is consistent with internationally accepted standards and fair and certain to
contracting parties while at the same time fostering - or at least not inhibiting or
discouraging - the business use of new technologies as they develop. The future of cost-effective
electronic commerce demands nothing less.</P>
<BR>

<DL><DD><I>David Woolford and Simon Chester are members of the KNOWlaw<FONT SIZE="-2"><SUP>TM</SUP></FONT> Group<BR>at McMillan Binch, Mississauga
and Toronto.<BR>The authors wish to acknowledge the valuable contribution that Tom Johnston,
Student-at-Law, made to this article.</I></DL>

