<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Playboy Case</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://seamless.seamless.com/rcl/iplaw/playb2.html" > The Internet Law Page: Playboy Enterprises, Inc., v. Frena</A><LI><A HREF="http://www.jmls.edu/cyber/cases/frena.txt" > Playboy Enterprises, Inc., v. Frena 839 F.Supp.1552 (M.D.Fla.1993)
</A></UL></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
FACTS<BR>

<P>
&#183; Frena operated a subscription computer
bulletin board service, Techs Warehouse BBS, that distributed
unauthorized copies of Playboy Enterprises, Inc.'s copyrighted
photographs.
<P>
&#183; 170 of the images were available on
BBS were copied from Playboy's copyrighted materials.
<P>
&#183; No dispute that Playboy owns the copyrights
on the photos in question.
<P>
&#183; Frena admits that every one of the accused
images is substantially similar to the Playboy copyrighted photos
from which the accused image was produced.
<P>
&#183; Infringing photos are essentially exact
copies; only difference is that Playboy's written text appearing
on the same page of the photo has been removed from the infringing
copy.<BR>

<P>
HELD<BR>

<P>
&#183; Playboy succeeded on all points (copyright
infringement, trademark infringement and unfair competition) granted.
<BR>

<P>
REASONING<BR>

<P>
&#183; Frena argued that it was &quot;fair
use&quot; to mount the pictures, but the court did not accept
the argument;
<P>
&#183; his use was clearly commercial;
<P>
&#183; the photos were entertainment;
<P>
&#183; the photos copied an essential part
of Playboy's publication; 
<P>
&#183; the copying would have an adverse impact
on Playboy's potential market;
<P>
&#183; Playboy's registered trademarks, PLAYBOY
and PLAYMATE were used to identify many of the files containing
the photographs;
<P>
&#183; Court found that the marks were strong
enough and distinctive enough to deserve the highest degree of
protection under the Trademark Act of 1946;
<P>
&#183; High likelihood of confusion;
<P>
&#183; Frena used Playboy's name and logo to
benefit from Playboy's reputation.
<P>
&#183; Frena falsely suggested that Playboy
had authorized his product.
<P>
&#183; Removal of Playboy's trademarks from
the photos constitutes &quot;reverse passing off&quot;<BR>


