<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>PEI-Net</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI> PEINET Inc. v. OBrien (1995) 61 C.P.R. (3d) 334 MacDonald C.J.T.D. http://jilt.law.strath.ac.uk/elj/jilt/Confs/Amsterdm.htm</UL></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
Facts
<P>
&#183; PEINET asked the court to stop O'Brien
from using the Internet domain name &quot;PEI.NET&quot; because
it resembled its company name, PEINET INC. 
<P>
&#183; PEINET INC. provided regional access
to the Internet under the domain name, &quot;peinet.pe.ca.&quot;

<P>
&#183; Mr. O'Brien, was an employee of PEINET
INC. until his dismissal in 1994.
<P>
&#183; After being fired, he set up his own
business as an Internet service provider under the name &quot;Island
Services Network&quot;.
<P>
&#183; Mr. O'Brien obtained the domain name
&quot;PEI.NET&quot; (in upper-case letters) from a U.S. Internet
service provider. He later had it changed to &quot;isn.net.&quot;
<BR>

<P>
Issue
<P>
&#183; PEINET claimed O'Brien was &quot;passing-off&quot;
his work as his won. <BR>

<P>
Decision
<P>
&#183; The court dismissed the claim.<BR>

<P>
Reasoning
<P>
&#183; The PEINET name was unlikely to be confused
with PEINET because:
<P>
(i) PEINET used upper-case letters for its
company name, whereas O'Brien's domain name was in lower-case
letters.
<P>
(ii) PEINET INC. did not separate PEI and the
word NET with a period.<BR>

<P>
&#183; The court thought that PEINET's arguments
were superficial; even if it had proved that O'Brien's use of
the domain name &quot;pei.net&quot; infringed the name PEINET
INC., it failed to establish the elements of a passing-off action:
the existence of goodwill, deception of the public due to a misrepresentation,
and actual or potential damage.
<P>
&#183; MacDonald C.J.T.D. concluded that &quot;[b]asically
all that O'Brien did was, for a very short period of time, use
a &quot;telephone&quot; number that was the same as PEINET's name.&quot;
The use consisted of a reference to it in a newspaper article
and a listing on Internet for a very short period of time.

<TABLE>
<TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=100>

