<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Avon.com</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://infolawalert.com/stories/020996b.html" > Avon v. Carnetta Wong Associates (1996) U.S. Dist. Ct. (N.Y.) CV 965 0451.</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
Facts
<P>
&#183; Carnetta Wong Associates (&quot;CWA&quot;)
registered the domain name &quot;avon.com&quot;.
<P>
&#183; Avon accused Wong of unfair competition,
trademark infringement, misappropriation, trademark dilution,
and deceptive acts and practices. 
<P>
&#183; The suit marked the first action under
the new U.S. Federal Trademark Dilution Act of 1995. Previously,
dilution was available only as a state law remedy in 25 states.
<P>
&#183; Under the new legislation, dilution
is defined as &quot;the lessening of the capacity of a famous
mark to identify and distinguish goods or services, regardless
of the presence or absence of (1) competition between the owner
of the famous mark and other parties, or (2) likelihood of confusion,
mistake or deception.&quot;
<P>
&#183; According to Avon, CWA had no intention
of using the site commercially; it merely hoped to force Avon
to pay for the use of the domain name. 
<P>
&#183; After Avon complained, Network Solutions
Inc. (&quot;NSI&quot;) intervened and cancelled CWA's registration.
<BR>

<P>
Decision
<P>
&#183; A court decision over the measures of
damages for trademark dilution and infringement is still pending.

