<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Courts grabbing jurisdiction</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.law.emory.edu/6circuit/july96/96a0228p.06.html" > Compuserve v. Patterson, 6th Circuit</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
FACTS
<P>
&#183; Patterson, a lawyer who lives in Houston,
Texas has a business called FlashPoint Development; subscribed
to CompuServe system where he advertised his computer software
(a program to help people navigate around the Internet) for sale
<P>
&#183; CompuServe began to market a similar
product with markings and names that Patterson thought similar
to his own (i.e. WinNAV, Windows Navigator, FlashPoint Windows
Navigator); Patterson claimed common law trademarks in these
<P>
&#183; CompuServe changed the name of its programs,
but Patterson continued to complain.
<P>
&#183; Patterson demanded $100,000 to settle.
<P>
&#183; CompuServe then asked the federal district
court for the Southern District of Ohio for a ruling that it had
not infringed any common law trademarks of Patterson or FlashPoint
Development, and that it was not otherwise guilty of unfair or
deceptive trade practices.
<P>
&#183; Patterson responded that an Ohio court
had no jurisdiction over him.
<P>
&#183; The District court agreed and dismissed
the action.<BR>

<P>
ISSUE
<P>
&#183; Did CompuServe show that Patterson's
contacts with Ohio, which have been almost entirely electronic
in nature, are sufficient to ground an Ohio court's jurisdiction
over him?<BR>
<BR>

<P>
HELD
<P>
&#183; CompuServe won an appeal, and the case
was returned to a lower court for further proceedings.
<P>
&#183; The dispute did not arise directly out
of Patterson's user agreement with CompuServe, and Patterson did
not otherwise have sufficient contacts with Ohio to justify asserting
jurisdiction.<BR>

<P>
REASONING
<P>
&#183; To determine whether personal jurisdiction
exists over a defendant, federal courts apply the law of the forum
state, subject to the limits of the Due Process Clause.
<P>
&#183; To determine as to whether the non-resident
defendant has sufficient contacts with the forum state that the
district court's exercise of jurisdiction would comport with &quot;traditional
notions of fair play and substantial justice&quot;, the court
looks to 3 criteria:<BR>

<P>
1. The defendant must purposefully avail himself
of the privilege of acting in the forum state or causing a consequence
in the forum state.
<P>
2. The cause of action must arise from the
defendant's activities there.
<P>
3. The acts of the defendant or consequences
caused by the defendant must have a substantial enough connection
with the forum to make the exercise of jurisdiction over the defendant
reasonable.<BR>

<P>
&#183; Patterson has knowingly made an effort,
and purposefully contracted to market a product in other states,
with Ohio-based CompuServe operating, in effect, as his distribution
center. Thus, it is reasonable to subject Patterson to suit in
Ohio, the state which is home to the computer network service
he chose to employ.<BR>

<P>
. The &quot;legal&quot; requirement save satisfied
when the defendant's contacts with the forum state proximately
result from actions by the defendant himself that create a substantial
connection with the forum State, and when the defendant's conduct
and connection with the forum are such that he should reasonably
anticipate being hauled into court here. The law does not require
the defendant to be physically present in the forum state.<BR>

<P>
&#183; Once Patterson had subscribed to CompuServe
and entered into the Shareware Registration Agreement, he was
on notice that his contracts would be governed by Ohio law.
<P>
&#183; Ohio has written and interpreted its
long-arm statute, and particularly its &quot;transacting business&quot;
subsection, with the intent of reaching as far as the Due Process
Clause will allow.
<P>
&#183; Patterson also &quot;originated and
maintained&quot; contacts with Ohio when he believed that CompuServe's
competing product unlawfully infringed on his own software.
<P>
&#183; Patterson knowingly reached out to CompuServe's
Ohio home, and he benefited from CompuServe's handling of his
software and the fees that it generated.<BR>

<P>
. If a defendant's contacts with the forum
state are related to the operative facts of the controversy, then
an action will be deemed to have arisen from those contacts.
<P>
&#183; Patterson's contacts with Ohio are certainly
related to the operative facts of the controversy; he placed his
software on CompuServe's Ohio-based system; he used that system
to advertise his software and sell it; the proceeds of those sales
flowed to him through Ohio; no one disputed that Patterson placed,
marketed, and sold his software ONLY on Ohio-based CompuServe.
<BR>
<BR>


