<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Bensusan Restaurant Corp v. King</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.counsel.com/features/jazz.html" > Bensusan Restaurant Corp. v. King (Missouri Jazz Club) 96 Civ. 3992  (Federal Court Southern District) </A><LI><A HREF="http://www.thoughtport.com/thenote/" > Missouri Club page</A><LI><A HREF="http://www.interjazz.com/clubs/bluenote/whatisbn.html" >NY club page</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
FACTS<BR>

<P>
&#183; Small Missouri jazz club called &quot;The
Blue Note&quot; had a site on the Net. Information about the Missouri
club was available to New Yorkers on the Internet The Blue Note
in Greenwich Village, a legendary jazz venue, sued the Missouri
club of the same name for allegedly &quot;selling or promoting&quot;
an infringing product.<BR>

<P>
HELD<BR>

<P>
&#183; The court said it did not have to hear
the case.<BR>

<P>
REASONING
<P>
&#183; Because ticket information and tickets
for the Missouri club must be obtained in Missouri and the club
did not &quot;purposefully direct&quot; its Internet pitch at
New Yorkers, assertions of jurisdiction under New York's long-arm
statute fail.
<P>
&#183; The mere fact that a person can gain
information on the allegedly infringing product is not the equivalent
of a person advertising, promoting, selling or otherwise making
an effort to target its product in New York.
<P>
&#183; Court found that because Missouri club
reports 99 percent of its patronage and revenue from local residents,
there was no reasonable expectation of New York damage stemming
from the information on the Web site.<BR>
<BR>


