<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Pres-Kap Inc. v. System One</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.jmls.edu/cyber/cases/pres-kap.txt" > Pres-Kap, Inc. v. System One, Direct Access, Inc.  (June 21, 1994) (District Court of Appeal of Florida, 3rd District)</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
FACTS<BR>

<P>
&#183; Pres-Kap is a Delaware subsidiary of
Eastern Airlines. It owns and operates a computerized airline
reservation system; the computer base for this system, as well
as the billing and main business office, is located in Miami,
Florida; Pres-Kap also maintains a branch business office in New
York City.
<P>
&#183; System One operates a travel agency
in Rockland County, New York; all its travel business is conducted
out of that office.
<P>
&#183; Pres-Kap, through its NY office, made
a deal to provide airline reservations to System One. All of the
contracts (including earlier ones with Eastern Airlines) were
made in New York. 
<P>
&#183; When equipment supplied under the contract
malfunctioned, System One contacted NY office but got no response;
it stopped making lease payments and so Pres-Kap sued.
<P>
&#183; The travel agency's contact with Florida
was very limited: (1) it forwarded all rental payments to the
Pres-Kap's billing office in Miami; (2) the computer database
which it accessed through computer terminals, is located in Miami.
<BR>

<P>
ISSUE<BR>

<P>
&#183; Appeal by a non-resident defendant corporation
from a non-final order denying its motion to dismiss a breach
contract action for lack of personal jurisdiction over it.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
HELD<BR>

<P>
&#183; The appeal court held it could not exercise
jurisdiction over a non-resident.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
REASONING<BR>

<P>
&#183; In order for a state court to subject
a nonresident defendant to a personal jurisdiction judgment, due
process requires that the nonresident defendant have certain minimum
contacts with the forum state so that bringing the action does
not offend traditional notions of fair play and substantial justice.
<P>
&#183; The minimal contacts could not convert
an obviously New York-based transaction into a Florida transaction
so that the travel agent could reasonably expect to be sued.
<P>
&#183; The travel agency did not even know
the exact electronic location of the computer database.
<P>
&#183; Even if such knowledge had been shown,
this would not have altered the travel agent's reasonable expectation
that New York courts would handle any dispute between the parties.
<P>
&#183; Any other decision would have far-reaching
implications for business and professional people who use &quot;on-line&quot;
computer services for which payments are made to out-of-state
companies where the database is located; such a result would be
beyond the reasonable expectations of such computer-information
users, and would offend traditional notions of fair play and substantial
justice.<BR>
<BR>


