<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Scientology</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.cybercom.net/~rnewman/scientology/home.html" > Religious Technology Center v. Netcom On-Line Communication Services Inc.	(1995) (U.S. Dist. Ct.) Whyte J.
</A></P></UL>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
Facts
<P>
&#183; Religious Technology Center (&quot;RTC&quot;)
and Bridge Publications (BP) held copyrights in the unpublished
and published works of L. Ron Hubbard, the founder of the Church
of Scientology.
<P>
&#183; The defendant, Dennis Erlich, was a
former minister of Scientology turned vocal critic of the Church.
He posted criticism of the Church on a discussion group called
alt.religion.scientology.
<P>
&#183; The Church alleged that Erlich infringed
their copyrights when he posted portions of their works on the
discussion group.
<P>
&#183; Erlich's name was revealed in February
1995 when Finnish police in Helsinki presented Johan Helsingius
with a warrant demanding the name of the person who had been using
his anonymous server (anon.penet.fi) to post messages on the discussion.
When he refused, he was told that failure to comply would result
in the confiscation of his system and the identities of all those
who had used his system would be revealed. Rather than put these
people at risk, he divulged Erlich's name. Since then, the anonymous
server has been shut down. 
<P>
&#183; Erlich himself was confronted by police
at his California home. The cops searched his home, confiscated
all magnetic media and deleted files from his hard disk that they
found offensive.
<P>
&#183; The Church ordered BBS operator Tom
Klemesrud and Netcom to cut-off Erlich's access to their systems.
They refused. 
<P>
&#183; Netcom called itself a &quot;passive
transmitter&quot; and claimed it could not control content or
determine whether the millions of daily messages violated copyright.
<P>
&#183; In response, the church cited 1,200
instances in which Netcom cut off subscriber accounts for offensive
messages.
<P>
&#183; The court rejected Netcom's &quot;fair
use&quot; defence in an earlier motion for an interim injunction.
<BR>

<P>
Issues
<P>
&#183; Should BBS operators and Internet access
providers be liable for copyright infringement committed by a
BBS subscriber?<BR>

<P>
Decision
<P>
&#183; The court held that Netcom was not liable
for direct infringement or vicariously liable. The court left
open the issue of contributory liability, but refused to order
Netcom to cut off access. <BR>

<P>
Reasoning<BR>

<P>
Direct Infringement
<P>
&#183; The court found that Netcom did not
take any affirmative action that directly resulted in copying
of Scientology texts. Its software system automatically received,
copied and forwarded messages from subscribers on the Usenet.
Likewise, Klemesrud's system operated without human intervention.
<P>
&#183; The court compared Netcom to a phone
company which would not be liable for carrying an infringing fax
transmission or for storing an infringing audio recording on its
voice-mail.
<P>
&#183; The court held that where a BBS merely
stores and passes along all messages sent by subscribers and others,
it should not be seen as causing the works to be publicly distributed
or displayed.
<P>
&#183; The court expressed concern about expanding
the scope of liability on the Internet when there is already a
party directly liable for causing the copies to be made (i.e.
the user).
<P>
&#183; &quot;The court does not find workable
a theory of infringement that would hold the entire Internet liable
for activities that cannot reasonably be deterred. Billions of
bits of data flow through the Internet and are necessarily stored
on servers throughout the network and it is thus practically impossible
to screen out infringing bits from noninfringing bits.&quot;<BR>

<P>
Vicarious Liability
<P>
&#183; On the facts, Scientology failed to
show the two elements necessary to establish contributory negligence:
the right and the ability to control the infringer and direct
financial gain. The court held that Scientology failed to establish
that Netcom benefited financially from the postings.<BR>

<P>
Contributory Infringement
<P>
&#183; The court left open the issue of contributory
infringement. There was evidence that Netcom knew or should have
known that Erlich was infringing their copyrights after receiving
a letter from Scientology. 
<P>
&#183; There was also evidence that Netcom
exhibited a degree of control and, therefore, had materially contributed
to the &quot;infringing conduct&quot;. The court noted that unlike
a landlord who leases property, Netcom retained some ability over
how its &quot;leased premises&quot; were used.<BR>

<P>
Fair Use 
<P>
&#183; The court considered the purpose and
character of the use, the nature of the copyrighted work, the
portion of the work used and the effect of the use upon the potential
market. The court's biggest concern was whether the use would
effect the potential market. The court was not particularly concerned
about the amount of the work copied in and of itself, since Netcom
was not able to selectively copy portions of the work posted by
Erlich. <BR>

<P>
NOTE: A similar copyright case, pitting Scientology
affiliates against Internet access provider, Gateway Digital Service
Inc., is scheduled for trial in January in the federal court in
Virginia.<BR>

<P>
Cases Referred to in the Judgment
<P>
&#183; MAI Systems Corp. v. Peak Computer Inc.
991F.2d 511, 518 (9th Cir. 1993).
<P>
&#183; Playboy Enterprises Inc. v. Frena 839
F.Supp. 1552, 1554 (M.D.Fla. 1993).
<P>
&#183; Sega Enterprises Ltd. v. Maphia 857
F.Supp. 679, 683 (N.D.Cal. 1994).<BR>


