<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Liability of I.S.P.</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.mcbinch.com/netlaw/cubby.html" > Cubby v. CompuServe (1991) No. 90 Civ. 6571 (N.Y. Dist. Ct.).</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P>
<P>
Facts
<P>
&#183; Cubby sued CompuServe for libel, business
disparagement and unfair competition based on allegedly defamatory
statements carried on one of CompuServe's services, Rumorville.
<P>
&#183; Cubby claimed that Rumorville published
false and defamatory statements relating to the computer database,
Skuttlebut - a service designed by Cubby Inc. to compete directly
with Rumorville.
<P>
&#183; Subscribers to CompuServe pay a membership
fee and on-line time usage fees for access to a general on-line
information service and special &quot;forums&quot; comprised of
electronic bulletin boards, interactive on-line conferences and
topical databases.
<P>
&#183; One publication available as part of
CompuServe's Journalism Forum was Rumorville USA. It was managed
by Cameron Communications Inc. (&quot;CCI&quot;) and owned by
Don Fitzpatrick Associates (&quot;DFA&quot;).
<P>
&#183; Under a contract between DFA and CCI,
DFA agreed to accept &quot;total responsibility for the contents&quot;
of Rumorville.
<P>
&#183; CompuServe had no opportunity to review
Rumorville's contents before DFA uploaded it into CompuServe's
computer banks, where it was immediately available to approved
subscribers. 
<P>
&#183; CompuServe did not have notice of any
complaints about the contents of the Rumorville publication or
about DFA until the action was filed.<BR>

<P>
Issue
<P>
&#183; Was CompuServe legally responsible for
materials posted on Rumorville by a third party? <BR>

<P>
Decision
<P>
&#183; The court rejected an argument that
the case could be decided summarily.<BR>

<P>
Reasoning
<P>
&#183; The court concluded that CompuServe
was more akin to a bookstore than a publisher. As a distributor,
it could not be held directly liable because it neither knew nor
had reason to know of the allegedly defamatory statements.
<P>
&#183; Nor was CompuServe vicariously liable.
CompuServe could refuse to carry a given publication, but once
it made the decision to do so, it was limited in its ability to
exert editorial control. In this case, Rumorville was owned and
operated by third parties over which CompuServe had no direct
control. 
<P>
&#183; The claims of business disparagement
and unfair competition were also dismissed because CompuServe
had no knowledge of the harmful statements. <BR>

