<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Carriage or Content</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.mcbinch.com/netlaw/prodigy.html" > Stratton Oakmonth v. Prodigy Services Co., 23 Media L. Rep. (BNA) 1794 (1995). </UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P>
Facts
<P>
&#183; Stratton Oakmonth, a small brokerage
firm specializing in penny stocks, sued Prodigy for $200 million.
<P>
&#183; A user posted statements on &quot;Money
Talk&quot;, a computer bulletin board service carried by Prodigy,
accusing Stratton and its officers of criminal activity. 
<P>
&#183; According to Prodigy's stated policy,
it was a family-oriented computer network. It held itself out
as an on-line service that exercised editorial control over the
content of messages posted on its computer bulletin boards.
<P>
&#183; Prodigy also had &quot;content guidelines&quot;
which requested users to refrain from posting notes that were
insulting or in bad taste.
<P>
&#183; The service also made use of a software
screening program which automatically prescreened all bulletin
board postings for offensive language.
<P>
&#183; Bulletin board leaders were responsible
for enforcing Prodigy's guidelines. They could remove messages
from boards with the &quot;emergency delete function&quot; and
replace them with explanations for the deletions.
<P>
&#183; Sixty thousand messages were posted
daily on Prodigy's bulletin boards.<BR>

<P>
Issues
<P>
&#183; Was Prodigy a publisher of the statements
on Money Talk?<BR>

<P>
Decision
<P>
&#183; The court granted summary judgment against
Prodigy.<BR>

<P>
Reasoning
<P>
&#183; The court distinguished Cubby on two
grounds: (1) Prodigy held itself out to the public and its members
as controlling the content of its computer bulletin boards; and,
(2) Prodigy implemented this control through its automatic software
screening program and the active use of technology and manpower
to delete offensive notes from its computer bulletin boards.
<P>
&#183; The court concluded, therefore, that
Prodigy was a publisher of the statements of &quot;Money Talk.&quot;
<P>
&#183; The court noted, however, that &quot;[c]omputer
bulletin boards should generally be regarded in the same context
as bookstores libraries and network affiliates.&quot; It emphasized
that it was Prodigy's own policies, technology and staffing decisions
which led to the conclusion that Prodigy was a publisher.<BR>

<P>
NOTE: Stratton agreed in late 1995 to drop
its $200 million action against Prodigy in return for an apology
and an undisclosed settlement. Prodigy failed, however, to persuade
the trial court judge to withdraw his decision. Prodigy has since
filed a motion for reconsideration and, if unsuccessful, may appeal.
<BR>


