<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Applicable Standards</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://college.antioch.edu/~jerwin/us_vs_thomas.html" > United States of America v. Thomas (January 29, 1996) (Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit)</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
FACTS<BR>

<P>
&#183; The operators of an electronic bulletin
board in California were convicted of having obscene material
on their BBS according to the standards of Memphis, Tennessee.
Robert and Carleen Thomas began operating the Amateur Action Bulletin
Board System (AABBS) from their home in Milpitas, California in
February 1991, which enabled subscribers to download sexually
explicit images and join in chat groups to discuss the materials.
<P>
&#183; The Thomas's' digitized collection reached
approximately 14,000 images, largely gleaned from sexually explicit
magazines (which they scanned to convert the pictures into computer
files); they promoted their service as the &quot;nastiest place
on earth&quot;
<P>
&#183; Customers could also purchase sexually
explicit videotapes, which were requested via e-mail and delivered
using the services of UPS.
<P>
&#183; Access to the files was limited to members
who were given a password after they paid a membership fee and
submitted a signed application form (which included the applicant's
age, address, telephone number and signature).
<P>
&#183; In July 1993, a US Postal Inspector
received complaint regarding the AABBs from an individual who
lived in Memphis, Tennessee; the Inspector assumed an alias and
became a member of AABBS; retrieved information, requested videos
and participated in chat lines.
<P>
&#183; Thomas's' were subsequently charged
on 12 counts, including: conspiracy to violate federal obscenity
laws, knowingly using and causing to be used a facility and means
of interstate commerce - a combined computer/telephone system
- for the purpose of transporting obscene, computer-generated
materials in interstate commerce; shipping obscene videotapes
via U.P.S.; causing the transportation of materials depicting
minors engaged in sexually explicit conduct; and Mr. Thomas alone
was charged with one count of forfeiture .
<P>
&#183; Thomas's were tried in federal district
court in Memphis and convicted of distributing obscene materials
in interstate commerce; Robert Thomas found guilty of all counts
except that dealing with child pornography; Carleen Thomas found
guilty on first 10 counts.<BR>

<P>
APPEAL<BR>

<P>
&#183; Thomas's' appeal decision, arguing,
among other things that the materials they offered were not obscene
by the standards of their own Bay Area community, and wondered
whey they were in court in Memphis.<BR>

<P>
HELD<BR>

<P>
&#183; Robert and Carleen Thomas' convictions
and sentences (37 and 30 months, respectively) affirmed.<BR>

<P>
ISSUES <BR>

<P>
&#183; This case reveals the difficulty of
applying &quot;community standards&quot;, in a world of computer
networks, - the test by which a piece of work is judged obscene,
according to the legal doctrine that the Supreme Court established
in its 1973 decision of Miller v. California.
<P>
&#183; This case is important also because
it considers whose obscenity standards should apply material is
considered indecent. 
<P>
&#183; If material placed on the Internet in
one community can be viewed by anyone in the world, then the question
is by what obscenity standards are they to be judged?<BR>

<P>
REASONING<BR>

<P>
&#183; Prosecutions may be brought either in
the district of dispatch or the district of receipt, where a message
is sent or received. Obscenity is determined by the standards
of either community.
<P>
&#183; It is not unconstitutional to subject
interstate distributors of obscenity to varying community standards
<P>
&#183; If defendants did not wish to subject
themselves to liability in jurisdictions with less tolerant standards
for determining obscenity, they could have refused to give passwords
to members in those districts, thus precluding the risk of liability
<P>
&#183; The computer-generated images and videotapes
involved here betrayed bestiality, incest, rape, sex scenes involving
defalcation, urination etc.<BR>


