<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Shae v. Reno; ACLU v. Reno</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="tsld018.htm" > Both Shea v. Reno </A>and<A HREF="tsld019.htm" > ACLU v. Reno</A> consider whether it is constitutional. <A HREF="http://www.altculture.com/site/entries/communicat.html" > The Communications Decency Act of 1996</A> attempts to limit and criminalize the distribution of indecent and patently offensive materials on-line. The law was actually an amendment tacked on to the Senate Commerce Committees version of the ...first major reform of U.S. communications law since the advent of network television.  Those convicted of transmitting indecent material on-line face fines up to $250,000 and maximum prison terms of two years.<BR><BR><LI>In both cases, courts ruled that the CDA is unnecessarily broad and unconstitutional.<BR><BR><LI>The government will appeal and lawyers on all sides expect the cases to be consolidated in the U.S. Supreme Court.</UL></P>
<P></P> 
