<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>Shea v. Reno</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.eff.org/pub/Legal/Cases/Am_Reporter_v_DoJ/960729.decision" > Shea v. Reno (July 29, 1996) 96 Civ. Q976 7 LC (District Court for the Southern District of New York</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
FACTS<BR>

<P>
&#183; Shea edits and owns The American Reporter,
the US daily newspaper distributed exclusively through electronic
means. <BR>

<P>
&#183; challenged the law because it breached
his free speech rights. He attacked because it was vague - no
one had a clear idea of what conduct will subject them to prosecution
or criminal liability. He also claimed the Act was too broad because
it targets a broader category of speech than necessary to achieve
the government's goal and constitutes a ban on certain constitutionally
protected speech between adults.<BR>

<P>
1. The court was not sympathetic to vagueness
arguments.
<P>
2. But it did think Shea might well succeed
in arguing about the breadth of the Act, and that it banned constitutionally
protected indecent communication between adults.
<P>
3. Washington conceded that the attacked provisions
were unconstitutional as a total ban on such communication.
<P>
4. Current technology provides no feasible
means for most serve to use the defences in the statute.<BR>

<P>
DEFENCES <BR>

<P>
&#183; The CDA provides several defences, including:
<BR>

<P>
1. taking reasonable, effective, and appropriate
measures in good faith to prevent access by minors.
<P>
2. restricting access to communication prohibited
under the Act by requiring the use of a verified credit card,
debit account, adult access code, or adult personal identification
number.<BR>

<P>
&#183; There is no basis for concluding that
Internet services are less able than other publishers to become
familiar with relevant community standards; the court suggests
that interactive computer services would cultivate a heightened
awareness of regional cultural differences, to which they must
be sensitive.
<P>
&#183; A user must take several steps to access
material through an interactive communications service; indecent
content on the Internet ordinarily does not assault a user without
warning; strict scrutiny will apply to determine whether the Act
is overbroad 
<P>
&#183; There is no persuasive evidence that
a substantial portion of Internet services can make available
material potentially within the scope of the law without fear
of prosecution or criminal liability; the defences offer no assurance
that content providers will not be prosecuted under the Act.<BR>


