<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>McMillan Binch Netlaw!</TITLE>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" l gen true comment "RSACi North America Server" by "abacchus@mcbinch.com" for "http://www.mcbinch.com" on "1996.04.16T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 l 0))'> 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="Tile7.gif">
<IMG SRC="netlaw.gif"><BR>
 <P><H2>ACLU v. Reno</H2>
</P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/Exon_bill/HTML/960612_aclu_v_reno_decision.html" > ACLU v. Reno (June 11, 1996) (District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania)</UL></A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P> 
<P><P>
FACTS<BR>

<P>
&#183; The suit was brought by a number of
organizations and individuals who, associated with the computer
and communications industries, or who publish or post materials
on the Internet. They sued the federal government to prevent implementation
of the CDA.
<P>
&#183; They had previously won a temporary
restraining order based on the fact that &quot;indecency provision&quot;
of the CDA is unconstitutionally vague.
<P>
&#183; They argued that the CDA is directed
to communications over the Internet which might be deemed &quot;indecent&quot;
or &quot;patently offensive&quot; for children breached free speech
and due process guarantees.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
HELD<BR>

<P>
&#183; Motion for preliminary injunction granted.
<P>
&#183; Plaintiffs have established a reasonable
probability of eventual success in the litigation by demonstrating
that CDA is unconstitutional to the extent that reaches indecency.
<P>
&#183; Government may only regulate indecent
speech for a compelling reason, and in the least restrictive manner.
<BR>

<P>
REASONING<BR>

<P>
&#183; In seeking preliminary injunctive relief,
plaintiffs must show:
<P>
(1) a reasonable probability of eventual success
in the litigation; and
<P>
(2) irreparable injury if relief is not granted;
[also, where appropriate]
<P>
(3) the possibility of harm to other interested
persons from the grant or denial of the injunction
<P>
(4) the public interest<BR>

<P>
&#183; Plaintiffs have shown irreparable injury,
no party has any interest in the enforcement of an unconstitutional
law, and so the public interest requires that the law not be enforced.


<TABLE>
<TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=100>

<A HREF = "tsld017.htm">Previous slide </A> </TD>
<TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=100>

<A HREF = "tsld020.htm">Next slide </A>  </TD>
<TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=150>

<A HREF = "Welcome.htm">Back to the first slide </A>  </TD>
<TD HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=150>

<A HREF = "sld019.htm">View Graphic Version </A>  </TD>
</TABLE>
<BR>
</p>
